[31m-<br/><a id="linkgod" name="linkgod"></a> <br/>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- WHEN GOD LAUGHS (with compliments to Harry Cowell)[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “The gods, the gods are stronger; time[m
[31m- Falls down before them, all men’s knees[m
[31m- Bow, all men’s prayers and sorrows climb[m
[31m- Like incense toward them; yea, for these[m
[31m- Are gods, Felise.”[m
[31m- </pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Carquinez had relaxed finally. He stole a glance at the rattling windows,[m
[31m- looked upward at the beamed roof, and listened for a moment to the savage[m
[31m- roar of the south-easter as it caught the bungalow in its bellowing jaws.[m
[31m- Then he held his glass between him and the fire and laughed for joy[m
[31m- through the golden wine.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is beautiful,” he said. “It is sweetly sweet. It is a woman’s wine,[m
[31m- and it was made for gray-robed saints to drink.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “We grow it on our own warm hills,” I said, with pardonable California[m
[31m- pride. “You rode up yesterday through the vines from which it was made.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was worth while to get Carquinez to loosen up. Nor was he ever really[m
[31m- himself until he felt the mellow warmth of the vine singing in his blood.[m
[31m- He was an artist, it is true, always an artist; but somehow, sober, the[m
[31m- high pitch and lilt went out of his thought-processes and he was prone to[m
[31m- be as deadly dull as a British Sunday⁠—not dull as other men are[m
[31m- dull, but dull when measured by the sprightly wight that Monte Carquinez[m
[31m- was when he was really himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- From all this it must not be inferred that Carquinez, who is my dear[m
[31m- friend and dearer comrade, was a sot. Far from it. He rarely erred. As I[m
[31m- have said, he was an artist. He knew when he had enough, and enough, with[m
[31m- him, was equilibrium⁠—the equilibrium that is yours and mine when we[m
[31m- are sober.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His was a wise and instinctive temperateness that savoured of the Greek.[m
[31m- Yet he was far from Greek. “I am Aztec, I am Inca, I am Spaniard,” I have[m
[31m- heard him say. And in truth he looked it, a compound of strange and[m
[31m- ancient races, what with his swarthy skin and the asymmetry and[m
[31m- primitiveness of his features. His eyes, under massively arched brows,[m
[31m- were wide apart and black with the blackness that is barbaric, while[m
[31m- before them was perpetually falling down a great black mop of hair through[m
[31m- which he gazed like a roguish satyr from a thicket. He invariably wore a[m
[31m- soft flannel shirt under his velvet-corduroy jacket, and his necktie was[m
[31m- red. This latter stood for the red flag (he had once lived with the[m
[31m- socialists of Paris), and it symbolized the blood and brotherhood of man.[m
[31m- Also, he had never been known to wear anything on his head save a[m
[31m- leather-banded sombrero. It was even rumoured that he had been born with[m
[31m- this particular piece of headgear. And in my experience it was provocative[m
[31m- of nothing short of sheer delight to see that Mexican sombrero hailing a[m
[31m- cab in Piccadilly or storm-tossed in the crush for the New York Elevated.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As I have said, Carquinez was made quick by wine⁠—“as the clay was[m
[31m- made quick when God breathed the breath of life into it,” was his way of[m
[31m- saying it. I confess that he was blasphemously intimate with God; and I[m
[31m- must add that there was no blasphemy in him. He was at all times honest,[m
[31m- and, because he was compounded of paradoxes, greatly misunderstood by[m
[31m- those who did not know him. He could be as elementally raw at times as a[m
[31m- screaming savage; and at other times as delicate as a maid, as subtle as a[m
[31m- Spaniard. And⁠—well, was he not Aztec? Inca? Spaniard?[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And now I must ask pardon for the space I have given him. (He is my[m
[31m- friend, and I love him.) The house was shaking to the storm, as he drew[m
[31m- closer to the fire and laughed at it through his wine. He looked at me,[m
[31m- and by the added lustre of his eye, and by the alertness of it, I knew[m
[31m- that at last he was pitched in his proper key.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And so you think you’ve won out against the gods?” he demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why the gods?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Whose will but theirs has put satiety upon man?” he cried.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And whence the will in me to escape satiety?” I asked triumphantly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Again the gods,” he laughed. “It is their game we play. They deal and[m
[31m- shuffle all the cards … and take the stakes. Think not that you have[m
[31m- escaped by fleeing from the mad cities. You with your vine-clad hills,[m
[31m- your sunsets and your sunrises, your homely fare and simple round of[m
[31m- living![m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ve watched you ever since I came. You have not won. You have[m
[31m- surrendered. You have made terms with the enemy. You have made confession[m
[31m- that you are tired. You have flown the white flag of fatigue. You have[m
[31m- nailed up a notice to the effect that life is ebbing down in you. You have[m
[31m- run away from life. You have played a trick, shabby trick. You have balked[m
[31m- at the game. You refuse to play. You have thrown your cards under the[m
[31m- table and run away to hide, here amongst your hills.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He tossed his straight hair back from his flashing eyes, and scarcely[m
[31m- interrupted to roll a long, brown, Mexican cigarette.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But the gods know. It is an old trick. All the generations of man have[m
[31m- tried it … and lost. The gods know how to deal with such as you. To[m
[31m- pursue is to possess, and to possess is to be sated. And so you, in your[m
[31m- wisdom, have refused any longer to pursue. You have elected surcease. Very[m
[31m- well. You will become sated with surcease. You say you have escaped[m
[31m- satiety! You have merely bartered it for senility. And senility is another[m
[31m- name for satiety. It is satiety’s masquerade. Bah!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But look at me!” I cried.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Carquinez was ever a demon for haling ones soul out and making rags and[m
[31m- tatters of it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He looked me witheringly up and down.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You see no signs,” I challenged.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Decay is insidious,” he retorted. “You are rotten ripe.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- I laughed and forgave him for his very deviltry. But he refused to be[m
[31m- forgiven.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Do I not know?” he asked. “The gods always win. I have watched men play[m
[31m- for years what seemed a winning game. In the end they lost.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t you ever make mistakes?” I asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He blew many meditative rings of smoke before replying.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, I was nearly fooled, once. Let me tell you. There was Marvin Fiske.[m
[31m- You remember him? And his Dantesque face and poet’s soul, singing his[m
[31m- chant of the flesh, the very priest of Love? And there was Ethel Baird,[m
[31m- whom also you must remember.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A warm saint,” I said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That is she! Holy as Love, and sweeter! Just a woman, made for love; and[m
[31m- yet⁠—how shall I say?⁠—drenched through with holiness as your[m
[31m- own air here is with the perfume of flowers. Well, they married. They[m
[31m- played a hand with the gods⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And they won, they gloriously won!” I broke in.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Carquinez looked at me pityingly, and his voice was like a funeral bell.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They lost. They supremely, colossally lost.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But the world believes otherwise,” I ventured coldly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The world conjectures. The world sees only the face of things. But I[m
[31m- know. Has it ever entered your mind to wonder why she took the veil,[m
[31m- buried herself in that dolorous convent of the living dead?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Because she loved him so, and when he died …”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Speech was frozen on my lips by Carquinez’s sneer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A pat answer,” he said, “machine-made like a piece of cotton-drill. The[m
[31m- world’s judgment! And much the world knows about it. Like you, she fled[m
[31m- from life. She was beaten. She flung out the white flag of fatigue. And no[m
[31m- beleaguered city ever flew that flag in such bitterness and tears.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now I shall tell you the whole tale, and you must believe me, for I know.[m
[31m- They had pondered the problem of satiety. They loved Love. They knew to[m
[31m- the uttermost farthing the value of Love. They loved him so well that they[m
[31m- were fain to keep him always, warm and a-thrill in their hearts. They[m
[31m- welcomed his coming; they feared to have him depart.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Love was desire, they held, a delicious pain. He was ever seeking[m
[31m- easement, and when he found that for which he sought, he died. Love denied[m
[31m- was Love alive; Love granted was Love deceased. Do you follow me? They saw[m
[31m- it was not the way of life to be hungry for what it has. To eat and still[m
[31m- be hungry⁠—man has never accomplished that feat. The problem of[m
[31m- satiety. That is it. To have and to keep the sharp famine-edge of appetite[m
[31m- at the groaning board. This was their problem, for they loved Love. Often[m
[31m- did they discuss it, with all Love’s sweet ardours brimming in their eyes;[m
[31m- his ruddy blood spraying their cheeks; his voice playing in and out with[m
[31m- their voices, now hiding as a tremolo in their throats, and again shading[m
[31m- a tone with that ineffable tenderness which he alone can utter.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How do I know all this? I saw⁠—much. More I learned from her diary.[m
[31m- This I found in it, from Fiona Macleod: ‘For, truly, that wandering voice,[m
[31m- that twilight-whisper, that breath so dewy-sweet, that flame-winged[m
[31m- lute-player whom none sees but for a moment, in a rainbow-shimmer of joy,[m
[31m- or a sudden lightning-flare of passion, this exquisite mystery we call[m
[31m- Amor, comes, to some rapt visionaries at least, not with a song upon the[m
[31m- lips that all may hear, or with blithe viol of public music, but as one[m
[31m- wrought by ecstasy, dumbly eloquent with desire.’[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How to keep the flame-winged lute-player with his dumb eloquence of[m
[31m- desire? To feast him was to lose him. Their love for each other was a[m
[31m- great love. Their granaries were overflowing with plenitude; yet they[m
[31m- wanted to keep the sharp famine-edge of their love undulled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nor were they lean little fledglings theorizing on the threshold of Love.[m
[31m- They were robust and realized souls. They had loved before, with others,[m
[31m- in the days before they met; and in those days they had throttled Love[m
[31m- with caresses, and killed him with kisses, and buried him in the pit of[m
[31m- satiety.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They were not cold wraiths, this man and woman. They were warm human.[m
[31m- They had no Saxon soberness in their blood. The colour of it was[m
[31m- sunset-red. They glowed with it. Temperamentally theirs was the French joy[m
[31m- in the flesh. They were idealists, but their idealism was Gallic. It was[m
[31m- not tempered by the chill and sombre fluid that for the English serves as[m
[31m- blood. There was no stoicism about them. They were Americans, descended[m
[31m- out of the English, and yet the refraining and self-denying of the English[m
[31m- spirit-groping were not theirs.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They were all this that I have said, and they were made for joy, only[m
[31m- they achieved a concept. A curse on concepts! They played with logic, and[m
[31m- this was their logic.⁠—But first let me tell you of a talk we had one[m
[31m- night. It was of Gautier’s Madeline de Maupin. You remember the maid? She[m
[31m- kissed once, and once only, and kisses she would have no more. Not that[m
[31m- she found kisses were not sweet, but that she feared with repetition they[m
[31m- would cloy. Satiety again! She tried to play without stakes against the[m
[31m- gods. Now this is contrary to a rule of the game the gods themselves have[m
[31m- made. Only the rules are not posted over the table. Mortals must play in[m
[31m- order to learn the rules.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, to the logic. The man and the woman argued thus: Why kiss once[m
[31m- only? If to kiss once were wise, was it not wiser to kiss not at all? Thus[m
[31m- could they keep Love alive. Fasting, he would knock forever at their[m
[31m- hearts.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Perhaps it was out of their heredity that they achieved this unholy[m
[31m- concept. The breed will out and sometimes most fantastically. Thus in them[m
[31m- did cursed Albion array herself a scheming wanton, a bold,[m
[31m- cold-calculating, and artful hussy. After all, I do not know. But this I[m
[31m- know: it was out of their inordinate desire for joy that they forewent[m
[31m- joy.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “As he said (I read it long afterward in one of his letters to her): ‘To[m
[31m- hold you in my arms, close, and yet not close. To yearn for you, and never[m
[31m- to have you, and so always to have you.’ And she: ‘For you to be always[m
[31m- just beyond my reach. To be ever attaining you, and yet never attaining[m
[31m- you, and for this to last forever, always fresh and new, and always with[m
[31m- the first flush upon us.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That is not the way they said it. On my lips their love-philosophy is[m
[31m- mangled. And who am I to delve into their soul-stuff? I am a frog, on the[m
[31m- dank edge of a great darkness, gazing goggle-eyed at the mystery and[m
[31m- wonder of their flaming souls.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And they were right, as far as they went. Everything is good … as long[m
[31m- as it is unpossessed. Satiety and possession are Death’s horses; they run[m
[31m- in span.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “ ‘And time could only tutor us to eke[m
[31m- Our rapture’s warmth with custom’s afterglow.’[m
[31m-</pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They got that from a sonnet of Alfred Austin’s. It was called ‘Love’s[m
[31m- Wisdom.’ It was the one kiss of Madeline de Maupin. How did it run?[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “ ‘Kiss we and part; no further can we go;[m
[31m- And better death than we from high to low[m
[31m- Should dwindle, or decline from strong to weak.’[m
[31m-</pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But they were wiser. They would not kiss and part. They would not kiss at[m
[31m- all, and thus they planned to stay at Love’s topmost peak. They married.[m
[31m- You were in England at the time. And never was there such a marriage. They[m
[31m- kept their secret to themselves. I did not know, then. Their rapture’s[m
[31m- warmth did not cool. Their love burned with increasing brightness. Never[m
[31m- was there anything like it. The time passed, the months, the years, and[m
[31m- ever the flame-winged lute-player grew more resplendent.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Everybody marvelled. They became the wonderful lovers, and they were[m
[31m- greatly envied. Sometimes women pitied her because she was childless; it[m
[31m- is the form the envy of such creatures takes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And I did not know their secret. I pondered and I marvelled. As first I[m
[31m- had expected, subconsciously I imagine, the passing of their love. Then I[m
[31m- became aware that it was Time that passed and Love that remained. Then I[m
[31m- became curious. What was their secret? What were the magic fetters with[m
[31m- which they bound Love to them? How did they hold the graceless elf? What[m
[31m- elixir of eternal love had they drunk together as had Tristram and Iseult[m
[31m- of old time? And whose hand had brewed the fairy drink?[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “As I say, I was curious, and I watched them. They were love-mad. They[m
[31m- lived in an unending revel of Love. They made a pomp and ceremonial of it.[m
[31m- They saturated themselves in the art and poetry of Love. No, they were not[m
[31m- neurotics. They were sane and healthy, and they were artists. But they had[m
[31m- accomplished the impossible. They had achieved deathless desire.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And I? I saw much of them and their everlasting miracle of Love. I[m
[31m- puzzled and wondered, and then one day⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Carquinez broke off abruptly and asked, “Have you ever read, ‘Love’s[m
[31m- Waiting Time’?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- I shook my head.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Page wrote it⁠—Curtis Hidden Page, I think. Well, it was that bit of[m
[31m- verse that gave me the clue. One day, in the window-seat near the big[m
[31m- piano⁠—you remember how she could play? She used to laugh, sometimes,[m
[31m- and doubt whether it was for them I came, or for the music. She called me[m
[31m- a ‘music-sot’ once, a ‘sound-debauchee.’ What a voice he had! When he sang[m
[31m- I believed in immortality, my regard for the gods grew almost patronizing[m
[31m- and I devised ways and means whereby I surely could outwit them and their[m
[31m- tricks.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It was a spectacle for God, that man and woman, years married, and[m
[31m- singing love-songs with a freshness virginal as new-born Love himself,[m
[31m- with a ripeness and wealth of ardour that young lovers can never know.[m
[31m- Young lovers were pale and anaemic beside that long-married pair. To see[m
[31m- them, all fire and flame and tenderness, at a trembling distance,[m
[31m- lavishing caresses of eye and voice with every action, through every[m
[31m- silence⁠—their love driving them toward each other, and they[m
[31m- withholding like fluttering moths, each to the other a candle-flame, and[m
[31m- revolving each about the other in the mad gyrations of an amazing[m
[31m- orbit-flight! It seemed, in obedience to some great law of physics, more[m
[31m- potent than gravitation and more subtle, that they must corporeally melt[m
[31m- each into each there before my very eyes. Small wonder they were called[m
[31m- the wonderful lovers.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I have wandered. Now to the clue. One day in the window-seat I found a[m
[31m- book of verse. It opened of itself, betraying long habit, to ‘Love’s[m
[31m- Waiting Time.’ The page was thumbed and limp with overhandling, and there[m
[31m- I read:⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “ ‘So sweet it is to stand but just apart,[m
[31m- To know each other better, and to keep[m
[31m- The soft, delicious sense of two that touch … O love, not yet! … Sweet, let us keep our love[m
[31m- Wrapped round with sacred mystery awhile,[m
[31m- Waiting the secret of the coming years,[m
[31m- That come not yet, not yet … sometime … not yet … Oh, yet a little while our love may grow![m
[31m- When it has blossomed it will haply die.[m
[31m- Feed it with lipless kisses, let it sleep,[m
[31m- Bedded in dead denial yet some while … Oh, yet a little while, a little while.’[m
[31m-</pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I folded the book on my thumb and sat there silent and without moving for[m
[31m- a long time. I was stunned by the clearness of vision the verse had[m
[31m- imparted to me. It was illumination. It was like a bolt of God’s lightning[m
[31m- in the Pit. They would keep Love, the fickle sprite, the forerunner of[m
[31m- young life⁠—young life that is imperative to be born![m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I conned the lines over in my mind⁠—‘Not yet, sometime’⁠—‘O[m
[31m- Love, not yet’⁠—‘Feed it with lipless kisses, let it sleep.’ And I[m
[31m- laughed aloud, ha, ha! I saw with white vision their blameless souls. They[m
[31m- were children. They did not understand. They played with Nature’s fire and[m
[31m- bedded with a naked sword. They laughed at the gods. They would stop the[m
[31m- cosmic sap. They had invented a system, and brought it to the gaming-table[m
[31m- of life, and expected to win out. ‘Beware!’ I cried. ‘The gods are behind[m
[31m- the table. They make new rules for every system that is devised. You have[m
[31m- no chance to win.’[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I did not so cry to them. I waited. They would learn that their[m
[31m- system was worthless and throw it away. They would be content with[m
[31m- whatever happiness the gods gave them and not strive to wrest more away.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I watched. I said nothing. The months continued to come and go, and still[m
[31m- the famine-edge of their love grew the sharper. Never did they dull it[m
[31m- with a permitted love-clasp. They ground and whetted it on self-denial,[m
[31m- and sharper and sharper it grew. This went on until even I doubted. Did[m
[31m- the gods sleep? I wondered. Or were they dead? I laughed to myself. The[m
[31m- man and the woman had made a miracle. They had outwitted God. They had[m
[31m- shamed the flesh, and blackened the face of the good Earth Mother. They[m
[31m- had played with her fire and not been burned. They were immune. They were[m
[31m- themselves gods, knowing good from evil and tasting not. ‘Was this the way[m
[31m- gods came to be?’ I asked myself. ‘I am a frog,’ I said. ‘But for my[m
[31m- mud-lidded eyes I should have been blinded by the brightness of this[m
[31m- wonder I have witnessed. I have puffed myself up with my wisdom and passed[m
[31m- judgment upon gods.’[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yet even in this, my latest wisdom, I was wrong. They were not gods. They[m
[31m- were man and woman⁠—soft clay that sighed and thrilled, shot through[m
[31m- with desire, thumbed with strange weaknesses which the gods have not.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Carquinez broke from his narrative to roll another cigarette and to laugh[m
[31m- harshly. It was not a pretty laugh; it was like the mockery of a devil,[m
[31m- and it rose over and rode the roar of the storm that came muffled to our[m
[31m- ears from the crashing outside world.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I am a frog,” he said apologetically. “How were they to understand? They[m
[31m- were artists, not biologists. They knew the clay of the studio, but they[m
[31m- did not know the clay of which they themselves were made. But this I will[m
[31m- say⁠—they played high. Never was there such a game before, and I[m
[31m- doubt me if there will ever be such a game again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Never was lovers’ ecstasy like theirs. They had not killed Love with[m
[31m- kisses. They had quickened him with denial. And by denial they drove him[m
[31m- on till he was all aburst with desire. And the flame-winged lute-player[m
[31m- fanned them with his warm wings till they were all but swooning. It was[m
[31m- the very delirium of Love, and it continued undiminished and increasing[m
[31m- through the weeks and months.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They longed and yearned, with all the fond pangs and sweet delicious[m
[31m- agonies, with an intensity never felt by lovers before nor since.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And then one day the drowsy gods ceased nodding. They aroused and looked[m
[31m- at the man and woman who had made a mock of them. And the man and woman[m
[31m- looked into each other’s eyes one morning and knew that something was[m
[31m- gone. It was the flame-winged one. He had fled, silently, in the night,[m
[31m- from their anchorites’ board.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They looked into each other’s eyes and knew that they did not care.[m
[31m- Desire was dead. Do you understand? Desire was dead. And they had never[m
[31m- kissed. Not once had they kissed. Love was gone. They would never yearn[m
[31m- and burn again. For them there was nothing left⁠—no more tremblings[m
[31m- and flutterings and delicious anguishes, no more throbbing and pulsing,[m
[31m- and sighing and song. Desire was dead. It had died in the night, on a[m
[31m- couch cold and unattended; nor had they witnessed its passing. They[m
[31m- learned it for the first time in each other’s eyes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The gods may not be kind, but they are often merciful. They had twirled[m
[31m- the little ivory ball and swept the stakes from the table. All that[m
[31m- remained was the man and woman gazing into each other’s cold eyes. And[m
[31m- then he died. That was the mercy. Within the week Marvin Fiske was dead⁠—you[m
[31m- remember the accident. And in her diary, written at this time, I long[m
[31m- afterward read Mitchell Kennerly’s:⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “ ‘There was not a single hour[m
[31m- We might have kissed and did not kiss.’ ”[m
[31m- </pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh, the irony of it!” I cried out.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And Carquinez, in the firelight a veritable Mephistopheles in velvet[m
[31m- jacket, fixed me with his black eyes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And they won, you said? The world’s judgment! I have told you, and I[m
[31m- know. They won as you are winning, here in your hills.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But you,” I demanded hotly; “you with your orgies of sound and sense,[m
[31m- with your mad cities and madder frolics⁠—bethink you that you win?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He shook his head slowly. “Because you with your sober bucolic regime,[m
[31m- lose, is no reason that I should win. We never win. Sometimes we think we[m
[31m- win. That is a little pleasantry of the gods.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0001" name="link2H_4_0001">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- THE APOSTATE[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “Now I wake me up to work;[m
[31m- I pray the Lord I may not shirk.[m
[31m- If I should die before the night,[m
[31m- I pray the Lord my work’s all right.[m
[31m- Amen.”[m
[31m- </pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If you don’t git up, Johnny, I won’t give you a bite to eat!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The threat had no effect on the boy. He clung stubbornly to sleep,[m
[31m- fighting for its oblivion as the dreamer fights for his dream. The boy’s[m
[31m- hands loosely clenched themselves, and he made feeble, spasmodic blows at[m
[31m- the air. These blows were intended for his mother, but she betrayed[m
[31m- practised familiarity in avoiding them as she shook him roughly by the[m
[31m- shoulder.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Lemme ‘lone!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was a cry that began, muffled, in the deeps of sleep, that swiftly[m
[31m- rushed upward, like a wail, into passionate belligerence, and that died[m
[31m- away and sank down into an inarticulate whine. It was a bestial cry, as of[m
[31m- a soul in torment, filled with infinite protest and pain.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But she did not mind. She was a sad-eyed, tired-faced woman, and she had[m
[31m- grown used to this task, which she repeated every day of her life. She got[m
[31m- a grip on the bedclothes and tried to strip them down; but the boy,[m
[31m- ceasing his punching, clung to them desperately. In a huddle, at the foot[m
[31m- of the bed, he still remained covered. Then she tried dragging the bedding[m
[31m- to the floor. The boy opposed her. She braced herself. Hers was the[m
[31m- superior weight, and the boy and bedding gave, the former instinctively[m
[31m- following the latter in order to shelter against the chill of the room[m
[31m- that bit into his body.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As he toppled on the edge of the bed it seemed that he must fall[m
[31m- head-first to the floor. But consciousness fluttered up in him. He righted[m
[31m- himself and for a moment perilously balanced. Then he struck the floor on[m
[31m- his feet. On the instant his mother seized him by the shoulders and shook[m
[31m- him. Again his fists struck out, this time with more force and directness.[m
[31m- At the same time his eyes opened. She released him. He was awake.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All right,” he mumbled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She caught up the lamp and hurried out, leaving him in darkness.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’ll be docked,” she warned back to him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He did not mind the darkness. When he had got into his clothes, he went[m
[31m- out into the kitchen. His tread was very heavy for so thin and light a[m
[31m- boy. His legs dragged with their own weight, which seemed unreasonable[m
[31m- because they were such skinny legs. He drew a broken-bottomed chair to the[m
[31m- table.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Johnny,” his mother called sharply.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He arose as sharply from the chair, and, without a word, went to the sink.[m
[31m- It was a greasy, filthy sink. A smell came up from the outlet. He took no[m
[31m- notice of it. That a sink should smell was to him part of the natural[m
[31m- order, just as it was a part of the natural order that the soap should be[m
[31m- grimy with dish-water and hard to lather. Nor did he try very hard to make[m
[31m- it lather. Several splashes of the cold water from the running faucet[m
[31m- completed the function. He did not wash his teeth. For that matter he had[m
[31m- never seen a toothbrush, nor did he know that there existed beings in the[m
[31m- world who were guilty of so great a foolishness as tooth washing.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You might wash yourself wunst a day without bein’ told,” his mother[m
[31m- complained.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She was holding a broken lid on the pot as she poured two cups of coffee.[m
[31m- He made no remark, for this was a standing quarrel between them, and the[m
[31m- one thing upon which his mother was hard as adamant. “Wunst” a day it was[m
[31m- compulsory that he should wash his face. He dried himself on a greasy[m
[31m- towel, damp and dirty and ragged, that left his face covered with shreds[m
[31m- of lint.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I wish we didn’t live so far away,” she said, as he sat down. “I try to[m
[31m- do the best I can. You know that. But a dollar on the rent is such a[m
[31m- savin’, an’ we’ve more room here. You know that.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He scarcely followed her. He had heard it all before, many times. The[m
[31m- range of her thought was limited, and she was ever harking back to the[m
[31m- hardship worked upon them by living so far from the mills.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A dollar means more grub,” he remarked sententiously. “I’d sooner do the[m
[31m- walkin’ an’ git the grub.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He ate hurriedly, half chewing the bread and washing the unmasticated[m
[31m- chunks down with coffee. The hot and muddy liquid went by the name of[m
[31m- coffee. Johnny thought it was coffee⁠—and excellent coffee. That was[m
[31m- one of the few of life’s illusions that remained to him. He had never[m
[31m- drunk real coffee in his life.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In addition to the bread, there was a small piece of cold pork. His mother[m
[31m- refilled his cup with coffee. As he was finishing the bread, he began to[m
[31m- watch if more was forthcoming. She intercepted his questioning glance.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now, don’t be hoggish, Johnny,” was her comment. “You’ve had your share.[m
[31m- Your brothers an’ sisters are smaller’n you.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He did not answer the rebuke. He was not much of a talker. Also, he ceased[m
[31m- his hungry glancing for more. He was uncomplaining, with a patience that[m
[31m- was as terrible as the school in which it had been learned. He finished[m
[31m- his coffee, wiped his mouth on the back of his hand, and started to rise.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Wait a second,” she said hastily. “I guess the loaf kin stand you another[m
[31m- slice⁠—a thin un.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There was legerdemain in her actions. With all the seeming of cutting a[m
[31m- slice from the loaf for him, she put loaf and slice back in the bread box[m
[31m- and conveyed to him one of her own two slices. She believed she had[m
[31m- deceived him, but he had noted her sleight-of-hand. Nevertheless, he took[m
[31m- the bread shamelessly. He had a philosophy that his mother, because of her[m
[31m- chronic sickliness, was not much of an eater anyway.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She saw that he was chewing the bread dry, and reached over and emptied[m
[31m- her coffee cup into his.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t set good somehow on my stomach this morning,” she explained.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A distant whistle, prolonged and shrieking, brought both of them to their[m
[31m- feet. She glanced at the tin alarm-clock on the shelf. The hands stood at[m
[31m- half-past five. The rest of the factory world was just arousing from[m
[31m- sleep. She drew a shawl about her shoulders, and on her head put a dingy[m
[31m- hat, shapeless and ancient.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “We’ve got to run,” she said, turning the wick of the lamp and blowing[m
[31m- down the chimney.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They groped their way out and down the stairs. It was clear and cold, and[m
[31m- Johnny shivered at the first contact with the outside air. The stars had[m
[31m- not yet begun to pale in the sky, and the city lay in blackness. Both[m
[31m- Johnny and his mother shuffled their feet as they walked. There was no[m
[31m- ambition in the leg muscles to swing the feet clear of the ground.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- After fifteen silent minutes, his mother turned off to the right.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t be late,” was her final warning from out of the dark that was[m
[31m- swallowing her up.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He made no response, steadily keeping on his way. In the factory quarter,[m
[31m- doors were opening everywhere, and he was soon one of a multitude that[m
[31m- pressed onward through the dark. As he entered the factory gate the[m
[31m- whistle blew again. He glanced at the east. Across a ragged sky-line of[m
[31m- housetops a pale light was beginning to creep. This much he saw of the day[m
[31m- as he turned his back upon it and joined his work gang.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He took his place in one of many long rows of machines. Before him, above[m
[31m- a bin filled with small bobbins, were large bobbins revolving rapidly.[m
[31m- Upon these he wound the jute-twine of the small bobbins. The work was[m
[31m- simple. All that was required was celerity. The small bobbins were emptied[m
[31m- so rapidly, and there were so many large bobbins that did the emptying,[m
[31m- that there were no idle moments.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He worked mechanically. When a small bobbin ran out, he used his left hand[m
[31m- for a brake, stopping the large bobbin and at the same time, with thumb[m
[31m- and forefinger, catching the flying end of twine. Also, at the same time,[m
[31m- with his right hand, he caught up the loose twine-end of a small bobbin.[m
[31m- These various acts with both hands were performed simultaneously and[m
[31m- swiftly. Then there would come a flash of his hands as he looped the[m
[31m- weaver’s knot and released the bobbin. There was nothing difficult about[m
[31m- weaver’s knots. He once boasted he could tie them in his sleep. And for[m
[31m- that matter, he sometimes did, toiling centuries long in a single night at[m
[31m- tying an endless succession of weaver’s knots.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Some of the boys shirked, wasting time and machinery by not replacing the[m
[31m- small bobbins when they ran out. And there was an overseer to prevent[m
[31m- this. He caught Johnny’s neighbour at the trick, and boxed his ears.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Look at Johnny there⁠—why ain’t you like him?” the overseer[m
[31m- wrathfully demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny’s bobbins were running full blast, but he did not thrill at the[m
[31m- indirect praise. There had been a time … but that was long ago, very long[m
[31m- ago. His apathetic face was expressionless as he listened to himself being[m
[31m- held up as a shining example. He was the perfect worker. He knew that. He[m
[31m- had been told so, often. It was a commonplace, and besides it didn’t seem[m
[31m- to mean anything to him any more. From the perfect worker he had evolved[m
[31m- into the perfect machine. When his work went wrong, it was with him as[m
[31m- with the machine, due to faulty material. It would have been as possible[m
[31m- for a perfect nail-die to cut imperfect nails as for him to make a[m
[31m- mistake.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And small wonder. There had never been a time when he had not been in[m
[31m- intimate relationship with machines. Machinery had almost been bred into[m
[31m- him, and at any rate he had been brought up on it. Twelve years before,[m
[31m- there had been a small flutter of excitement in the loom room of this very[m
[31m- mill. Johnny’s mother had fainted. They stretched her out on the floor in[m
[31m- the midst of the shrieking machines. A couple of elderly women were called[m
[31m- from their looms. The foreman assisted. And in a few minutes there was one[m
[31m- more soul in the loom room than had entered by the doors. It was Johnny,[m
[31m- born with the pounding, crashing roar of the looms in his ears, drawing[m
[31m- with his first breath the warm, moist air that was thick with flying lint.[m
[31m- He had coughed that first day in order to rid his lungs of the lint; and[m
[31m- for the same reason he had coughed ever since.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The boy alongside of Johnny whimpered and sniffed. The boy’s face was[m
[31m- convulsed with hatred for the overseer who kept a threatening eye on him[m
[31m- from a distance; but every bobbin was running full. The boy yelled[m
[31m- terrible oaths into the whirling bobbins before him; but the sound did not[m
[31m- carry half a dozen feet, the roaring of the room holding it in and[m
[31m- containing it like a wall.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Of all this Johnny took no notice. He had a way of accepting things.[m
[31m- Besides, things grow monotonous by repetition, and this particular[m
[31m- happening he had witnessed many times. It seemed to him as useless to[m
[31m- oppose the overseer as to defy the will of a machine. Machines were made[m
[31m- to go in certain ways and to perform certain tasks. It was the same with[m
[31m- the overseer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But at eleven o’clock there was excitement in the room. In an apparently[m
[31m- occult way the excitement instantly permeated everywhere. The one-legged[m
[31m- boy who worked on the other side of Johnny bobbed swiftly across the floor[m
[31m- to a bin truck that stood empty. Into this he dived out of sight, crutch[m
[31m- and all. The superintendent of the mill was coming along, accompanied by a[m
[31m- young man. He was well dressed and wore a starched shirt⁠—a[m
[31m- gentleman, in Johnny’s classification of men, and also, “the Inspector.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He looked sharply at the boys as he passed along. Sometimes he stopped and[m
[31m- asked questions. When he did so, he was compelled to shout at the top of[m
[31m- his lungs, at which moments his face was ludicrously contorted with the[m
[31m- strain of making himself heard. His quick eye noted the empty machine[m
[31m- alongside of Johnny’s, but he said nothing. Johnny also caught his eye,[m
[31m- and he stopped abruptly. He caught Johnny by the arm to draw him back a[m
[31m- step from the machine; but with an exclamation of surprise he released the[m
[31m- arm.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Pretty skinny,” the superintendent laughed anxiously.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Pipe stems,” was the answer. “Look at those legs. The boy’s got the[m
[31m- rickets⁠—incipient, but he’s got them. If epilepsy doesn’t get him in[m
[31m- the end, it will be because tuberculosis gets him first.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny listened, but did not understand. Furthermore he was not interested[m
[31m- in future ills. There was an immediate and more serious ill that[m
[31m- threatened him in the form of the inspector.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now, my boy, I want you to tell me the truth,” the inspector said, or[m
[31m- shouted, bending close to the boy’s ear to make him hear. “How old are[m
[31m- you?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Fourteen,” Johnny lied, and he lied with the full force of his lungs. So[m
[31m- loudly did he lie that it started him off in a dry, hacking cough that[m
[31m- lifted the lint which had been settling in his lungs all morning.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Looks sixteen at least,” said the superintendent.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Or sixty,” snapped the inspector.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He’s always looked that way.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How long?” asked the inspector, quickly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “For years. Never gets a bit older.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Or younger, I dare say. I suppose he’s worked here all those years?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Off and on⁠—but that was before the new law was passed,” the[m
[31m- superintendent hastened to add.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Machine idle?” the inspector asked, pointing at the unoccupied machine[m
[31m- beside Johnny’s, in which the part-filled bobbins were flying like mad.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Looks that way.” The superintendent motioned the overseer to him and[m
[31m- shouted in his ear and pointed at the machine. “Machine’s idle,” he[m
[31m- reported back to the inspector.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They passed on, and Johnny returned to his work, relieved in that the ill[m
[31m- had been averted. But the one-legged boy was not so fortunate. The[m
[31m- sharp-eyed inspector haled him out at arms length from the bin truck. His[m
[31m- lips were quivering, and his face had all the expression of one upon whom[m
[31m- was fallen profound and irremediable disaster. The overseer looked[m
[31m- astounded, as though for the first time he had laid eyes on the boy, while[m
[31m- the superintendent’s face expressed shock and displeasure.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I know him,” the inspector said. “He’s twelve years old. I’ve had him[m
[31m- discharged from three factories inside the year. This makes the fourth.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He turned to the one-legged boy. “You promised me, word and honour, that[m
[31m- you’d go to school.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The one-legged boy burst into tears. “Please, Mr. Inspector, two babies[m
[31m- died on us, and we’re awful poor.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What makes you cough that way?” the inspector demanded, as though[m
[31m- charging him with crime.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And as in denial of guilt, the one-legged boy replied: “It ain’t nothin’.[m
[31m- I jes’ caught a cold last week, Mr. Inspector, that’s all.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the end the one-legged boy went out of the room with the inspector, the[m
[31m- latter accompanied by the anxious and protesting superintendent. After[m
[31m- that monotony settled down again. The long morning and the longer[m
[31m- afternoon wore away and the whistle blew for quitting time. Darkness had[m
[31m- already fallen when Johnny passed out through the factory gate. In the[m
[31m- interval the sun had made a golden ladder of the sky, flooded the world[m
[31m- with its gracious warmth, and dropped down and disappeared in the west[m
[31m- behind a ragged sky-line of housetops.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Supper was the family meal of the day⁠—the one meal at which Johnny[m
[31m- encountered his younger brothers and sisters. It partook of the nature of[m
[31m- an encounter, to him, for he was very old, while they were distressingly[m
[31m- young. He had no patience with their excessive and amazing juvenility. He[m
[31m- did not understand it. His own childhood was too far behind him. He was[m
[31m- like an old and irritable man, annoyed by the turbulence of their young[m
[31m- spirits that was to him arrant silliness. He glowered silently over his[m
[31m- food, finding compensation in the thought that they would soon have to go[m
[31m- to work. That would take the edge off of them and make them sedate and[m
[31m- dignified⁠—like him. Thus it was, after the fashion of the human,[m
[31m- that Johnny made of himself a yardstick with which to measure the[m
[31m- universe.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- During the meal, his mother explained in various ways and with infinite[m
[31m- repetition that she was trying to do the best she could; so that it was[m
[31m- with relief, the scant meal ended, that Johnny shoved back his chair and[m
[31m- arose. He debated for a moment between bed and the front door, and finally[m
[31m- went out the latter. He did not go far. He sat down on the stoop, his[m
[31m- knees drawn up and his narrow shoulders drooping forward, his elbows on[m
[31m- his knees and the palms of his hands supporting his chin.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As he sat there, he did no thinking. He was just resting. So far as his[m
[31m- mind was concerned, it was asleep. His brothers and sisters came out, and[m
[31m- with other children played noisily about him. An electric globe at the[m
[31m- corner lighted their frolics. He was peevish and irritable, that they[m
[31m- knew; but the spirit of adventure lured them into teasing him. They joined[m
[31m- hands before him, and, keeping time with their bodies, chanted in his face[m
[31m- weird and uncomplimentary doggerel. At first he snarled curses at them⁠—curses[m
[31m- he had learned from the lips of various foremen. Finding this futile, and[m
[31m- remembering his dignity, he relapsed into dogged silence.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His brother Will, next to him in age, having just passed his tenth[m
[31m- birthday, was the ringleader. Johnny did not possess particularly kindly[m
[31m- feelings toward him. His life had early been embittered by continual[m
[31m- giving over and giving way to Will. He had a definite feeling that Will[m
[31m- was greatly in his debt and was ungrateful about it. In his own playtime,[m
[31m- far back in the dim past, he had been robbed of a large part of that[m
[31m- playtime by being compelled to take care of Will. Will was a baby then,[m
[31m- and then, as now, their mother had spent her days in the mills. To Johnny[m
[31m- had fallen the part of little father and little mother as well.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Will seemed to show the benefit of the giving over and the giving way. He[m
[31m- was well-built, fairly rugged, as tall as his elder brother and even[m
[31m- heavier. It was as though the life-blood of the one had been diverted into[m
[31m- the other’s veins. And in spirits it was the same. Johnny was jaded, worn[m
[31m- out, without resilience, while his younger brother seemed bursting and[m
[31m- spilling over with exuberance.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The mocking chant rose louder and louder. Will leaned closer as he danced,[m
[31m- thrusting out his tongue. Johnny’s left arm shot out and caught the other[m
[31m- around the neck. At the same time he rapped his bony fist to the other’s[m
[31m- nose. It was a pathetically bony fist, but that it was sharp to hurt was[m
[31m- evidenced by the squeal of pain it produced. The other children were[m
[31m- uttering frightened cries, while Johnny’s sister, Jennie, had dashed into[m
[31m- the house.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He thrust Will from him, kicked him savagely on the shins, then reached[m
[31m- for him and slammed him face downward in the dirt. Nor did he release him[m
[31m- till the face had been rubbed into the dirt several times. Then the mother[m
[31m- arrived, an anaemic whirlwind of solicitude and maternal wrath.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why can’t he leave me alone?” was Johnny’s reply to her upbraiding.[m
[31m- “Can’t he see I’m tired?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m as big as you,” Will raged in her arms, his face a mass of tears,[m
[31m- dirt, and blood. “I’m as big as you now, an’ I’m goin’ to git bigger. Then[m
[31m- I’ll lick you⁠—see if I don’t.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You ought to be to work, seein’ how big you are,” Johnny snarled. “That’s[m
[31m- what’s the matter with you. You ought to be to work. An’ it’s up to your[m
[31m- ma to put you to work.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But he’s too young,” she protested. “He’s only a little boy.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I was younger’n him when I started to work.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny’s mouth was open, further to express the sense of unfairness that[m
[31m- he felt, but the mouth closed with a snap. He turned gloomily on his heel[m
[31m- and stalked into the house and to bed. The door of his room was open to[m
[31m- let in warmth from the kitchen. As he undressed in the semi-darkness he[m
[31m- could hear his mother talking with a neighbour woman who had dropped in.[m
[31m- His mother was crying, and her speech was punctuated with spiritless[m
[31m- sniffles.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I can’t make out what’s gittin’ into Johnny,” he could hear her say. “He[m
[31m- didn’t used to be this way. He was a patient little angel.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ he is a good boy,” she hastened to defend. “He’s worked faithful, an’[m
[31m- he did go to work too young. But it wasn’t my fault. I do the best I can,[m
[31m- I’m sure.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Prolonged sniffling from the kitchen, and Johnny murmured to himself as[m
[31m- his eyelids closed down, “You betcher life I’ve worked faithful.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The next morning he was torn bodily by his mother from the grip of sleep.[m
[31m- Then came the meagre breakfast, the tramp through the dark, and the pale[m
[31m- glimpse of day across the housetops as he turned his back on it and went[m
[31m- in through the factory gate. It was another day, of all the days, and all[m
[31m- the days were alike.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And yet there had been variety in his life⁠—at the times he changed[m
[31m- from one job to another, or was taken sick. When he was six, he was little[m
[31m- mother and father to Will and the other children still younger. At seven[m
[31m- he went into the mills⁠—winding bobbins. When he was eight, he got[m
[31m- work in another mill. His new job was marvellously easy. All he had to do[m
[31m- was to sit down with a little stick in his hand and guide a stream of[m
[31m- cloth that flowed past him. This stream of cloth came out of the maw of a[m
[31m- machine, passed over a hot roller, and went on its way elsewhere. But he[m
[31m- sat always in one place, beyond the reach of daylight, a gas-jet flaring[m
[31m- over him, himself part of the mechanism.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He was very happy at that job, in spite of the moist heat, for he was[m
[31m- still young and in possession of dreams and illusions. And wonderful[m
[31m- dreams he dreamed as he watched the steaming cloth streaming endlessly by.[m
[31m- But there was no exercise about the work, no call upon his mind, and he[m
[31m- dreamed less and less, while his mind grew torpid and drowsy.[m
[31m- Nevertheless, he earned two dollars a week, and two dollars represented[m
[31m- the difference between acute starvation and chronic underfeeding.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But when he was nine, he lost his job. Measles was the cause of it. After[m
[31m- he recovered, he got work in a glass factory. The pay was better, and the[m
[31m- work demanded skill. It was piecework, and the more skilful he was, the[m
[31m- bigger wages he earned. Here was incentive. And under this incentive he[m
[31m- developed into a remarkable worker.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was simple work, the tying of glass stoppers into small bottles. At his[m
[31m- waist he carried a bundle of twine. He held the bottles between his knees[m
[31m- so that he might work with both hands. Thus, in a sitting position and[m
[31m- bending over his own knees, his narrow shoulders grew humped and his chest[m
[31m- was contracted for ten hours each day. This was not good for the lungs,[m
[31m- but he tied three hundred dozen bottles a day.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The superintendent was very proud of him, and brought visitors to look at[m
[31m- him. In ten hours three hundred dozen bottles passed through his hands.[m
[31m- This meant that he had attained machine-like perfection. All waste[m
[31m- movements were eliminated. Every motion of his thin arms, every movement[m
[31m- of a muscle in the thin fingers, was swift and accurate. He worked at high[m
[31m- tension, and the result was that he grew nervous. At night his muscles[m
[31m- twitched in his sleep, and in the daytime he could not relax and rest. He[m
[31m- remained keyed up and his muscles continued to twitch. Also he grew sallow[m
[31m- and his lint-cough grew worse. Then pneumonia laid hold of the feeble[m
[31m- lungs within the contracted chest, and he lost his job in the glass-works.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Now he had returned to the jute mills where he had first begun with[m
[31m- winding bobbins. But promotion was waiting for him. He was a good worker.[m
[31m- He would next go on the starcher, and later he would go into the loom[m
[31m- room. There was nothing after that except increased efficiency.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The machinery ran faster than when he had first gone to work, and his mind[m
[31m- ran slower. He no longer dreamed at all, though his earlier years had been[m
[31m- full of dreaming. Once he had been in love. It was when he first began[m
[31m- guiding the cloth over the hot roller, and it was with the daughter of the[m
[31m- superintendent. She was much older than he, a young woman, and he had seen[m
[31m- her at a distance only a paltry half-dozen times. But that made no[m
[31m- difference. On the surface of the cloth stream that poured past him, he[m
[31m- pictured radiant futures wherein he performed prodigies of toil, invented[m
[31m- miraculous machines, won to the mastership of the mills, and in the end[m
[31m- took her in his arms and kissed her soberly on the brow.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But that was all in the long ago, before he had grown too old and tired to[m
[31m- love. Also, she had married and gone away, and his mind had gone to sleep.[m
[31m- Yet it had been a wonderful experience, and he used often to look back[m
[31m- upon it as other men and women look back upon the time they believed in[m
[31m- fairies. He had never believed in fairies nor Santa Claus; but he had[m
[31m- believed implicitly in the smiling future his imagination had wrought into[m
[31m- the steaming cloth stream.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He had become a man very early in life. At seven, when he drew his first[m
[31m- wages, began his adolescence. A certain feeling of independence crept up[m
[31m- in him, and the relationship between him and his mother changed. Somehow,[m
[31m- as an earner and breadwinner, doing his own work in the world, he was more[m
[31m- like an equal with her. Manhood, full-blown manhood, had come when he was[m
[31m- eleven, at which time he had gone to work on the night shift for six[m
[31m- months. No child works on the night shift and remains a child.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There had been several great events in his life. One of these had been[m
[31m- when his mother bought some California prunes. Two others had been the two[m
[31m- times when she cooked custard. Those had been events. He remembered them[m
[31m- kindly. And at that time his mother had told him of a blissful dish she[m
[31m- would sometime make⁠—“floating island,” she had called it, “better[m
[31m- than custard.” For years he had looked forward to the day when he would[m
[31m- sit down to the table with floating island before him, until at last he[m
[31m- had relegated the idea of it to the limbo of unattainable ideals.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Once he found a silver quarter lying on the sidewalk. That, also, was a[m
[31m- great event in his life, withal a tragic one. He knew his duty on the[m
[31m- instant the silver flashed on his eyes, before even he had picked it up.[m
[31m- At home, as usual, there was not enough to eat, and home he should have[m
[31m- taken it as he did his wages every Saturday night. Right conduct in this[m
[31m- case was obvious; but he never had any spending of his money, and he was[m
[31m- suffering from candy hunger. He was ravenous for the sweets that only on[m
[31m- red-letter days he had ever tasted in his life.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He did not attempt to deceive himself. He knew it was sin, and[m
[31m- deliberately he sinned when he went on a fifteen-cent candy debauch. Ten[m
[31m- cents he saved for a future orgy; but not being accustomed to the carrying[m
[31m- of money, he lost the ten cents. This occurred at the time when he was[m
[31m- suffering all the torments of conscience, and it was to him an act of[m
[31m- divine retribution. He had a frightened sense of the closeness of an awful[m
[31m- and wrathful God. God had seen, and God had been swift to punish, denying[m
[31m- him even the full wages of sin.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In memory he always looked back upon that as the one great criminal deed[m
[31m- of his life, and at the recollection his conscience always awoke and gave[m
[31m- him another twinge. It was the one skeleton in his closet. Also, being so[m
[31m- made, and circumstanced, he looked back upon the deed with regret. He was[m
[31m- dissatisfied with the manner in which he had spent the quarter. He could[m
[31m- have invested it better, and, out of his later knowledge of the quickness[m
[31m- of God, he would have beaten God out by spending the whole quarter at one[m
[31m- fell swoop. In retrospect he spent the quarter a thousand times, and each[m
[31m- time to better advantage.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There was one other memory of the past, dim and faded, but stamped into[m
[31m- his soul everlasting by the savage feet of his father. It was more like a[m
[31m- nightmare than a remembered vision of a concrete thing⁠—more like the[m
[31m- race-memory of man that makes him fall in his sleep and that goes back to[m
[31m- his arboreal ancestry.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- This particular memory never came to Johnny in broad daylight when he was[m
[31m- wide awake. It came at night, in bed, at the moment that his consciousness[m
[31m- was sinking down and losing itself in sleep. It always aroused him to[m
[31m- frightened wakefulness, and for the moment, in the first sickening start,[m
[31m- it seemed to him that he lay crosswise on the foot of the bed. In the bed[m
[31m- were the vague forms of his father and mother. He never saw what his[m
[31m- father looked like. He had but one impression of his father, and that was[m
[31m- that he had savage and pitiless feet.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His earlier memories lingered with him, but he had no late memories. All[m
[31m- days were alike. Yesterday or last year were the same as a thousand years⁠—or[m
[31m- a minute. Nothing ever happened. There were no events to mark the march of[m
[31m- time. Time did not march. It stood always still. It was only the whirling[m
[31m- machines that moved, and they moved nowhere⁠—in spite of the fact[m
[31m- that they moved faster.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- When he was fourteen, he went to work on the starcher. It was a colossal[m
[31m- event. Something had at last happened that could be remembered beyond a[m
[31m- night’s sleep or a week’s pay-day. It marked an era. It was a machine[m
[31m- Olympiad, a thing to date from. “When I went to work on the starcher,” or,[m
[31m- “after,” or “before I went to work on the starcher,” were sentences often[m
[31m- on his lips.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He celebrated his sixteenth birthday by going into the loom room and[m
[31m- taking a loom. Here was an incentive again, for it was piece-work. And he[m
[31m- excelled, because the clay of him had been moulded by the mills into the[m
[31m- perfect machine. At the end of three months he was running two looms, and,[m
[31m- later, three and four.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At the end of his second year at the looms he was turning out more yards[m
[31m- than any other weaver, and more than twice as much as some of the less[m
[31m- skilful ones. And at home things began to prosper as he approached the[m
[31m- full stature of his earning power. Not, however, that his increased[m
[31m- earnings were in excess of need. The children were growing up. They ate[m
[31m- more. And they were going to school, and school-books cost money. And[m
[31m- somehow, the faster he worked, the faster climbed the prices of things.[m
[31m- Even the rent went up, though the house had fallen from bad to worse[m
[31m- disrepair.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He had grown taller; but with his increased height he seemed leaner than[m
[31m- ever. Also, he was more nervous. With the nervousness increased his[m
[31m- peevishness and irritability. The children had learned by many bitter[m
[31m- lessons to fight shy of him. His mother respected him for his earning[m
[31m- power, but somehow her respect was tinctured with fear.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There was no joyousness in life for him. The procession of the days he[m
[31m- never saw. The nights he slept away in twitching unconsciousness. The rest[m
[31m- of the time he worked, and his consciousness was machine consciousness.[m
[31m- Outside this his mind was a blank. He had no ideals, and but one illusion;[m
[31m- namely, that he drank excellent coffee. He was a work-beast. He had no[m
[31m- mental life whatever; yet deep down in the crypts of his mind, unknown to[m
[31m- him, were being weighed and sifted every hour of his toil, every movement[m
[31m- of his hands, every twitch of his muscles, and preparations were making[m
[31m- for a future course of action that would amaze him and all his little[m
[31m- world.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was in the late spring that he came home from work one night aware of[m
[31m- unusual tiredness. There was a keen expectancy in the air as he sat down[m
[31m- to the table, but he did not notice. He went through the meal in moody[m
[31m- silence, mechanically eating what was before him. The children um’d and[m
[31m- ah’d and made smacking noises with their mouths. But he was deaf to them.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “D’ye know what you’re eatin’?” his mother demanded at last, desperately.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He looked vacantly at the dish before him, and vacantly at her.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Floatin’ island,” she announced triumphantly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Floating island!” the children chorussed loudly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh,” he said. And after two or three mouthfuls, he added, “I guess I[m
[31m- ain’t hungry to-night.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He dropped the spoon, shoved back his chair, and arose wearily from the[m
[31m- table.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ I guess I’ll go to bed.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His feet dragged more heavily than usual as he crossed the kitchen floor.[m
[31m- Undressing was a Titan’s task, a monstrous futility, and he wept weakly as[m
[31m- he crawled into bed, one shoe still on. He was aware of a rising, swelling[m
[31m- something inside his head that made his brain thick and fuzzy. His lean[m
[31m- fingers felt as big as his wrist, while in the ends of them was a[m
[31m- remoteness of sensation vague and fuzzy like his brain. The small of his[m
[31m- back ached intolerably. All his bones ached. He ached everywhere. And in[m
[31m- his head began the shrieking, pounding, crashing, roaring of a million[m
[31m- looms. All space was filled with flying shuttles. They darted in and out,[m
[31m- intricately, amongst the stars. He worked a thousand looms himself, and[m
[31m- ever they speeded up, faster and faster, and his brain unwound, faster and[m
[31m- faster, and became the thread that fed the thousand flying shuttles.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He did not go to work next morning. He was too busy weaving colossally on[m
[31m- the thousand looms that ran inside his head. His mother went to work, but[m
[31m- first she sent for the doctor. It was a severe attack of la grippe, he[m
[31m- said. Jennie served as nurse and carried out his instructions.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was a very severe attack, and it was a week before Johnny dressed and[m
[31m- tottered feebly across the floor. Another week, the doctor said, and he[m
[31m- would be fit to return to work. The foreman of the loom room visited him[m
[31m- on Sunday afternoon, the first day of his convalescence. The best weaver[m
[31m- in the room, the foreman told his mother. His job would be held for him.[m
[31m- He could come back to work a week from Monday.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why don’t you thank ’im, Johnny?” his mother asked anxiously.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He’s ben that sick he ain’t himself yet,” she explained apologetically to[m
[31m- the visitor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny sat hunched up and gazing steadfastly at the floor. He sat in the[m
[31m- same position long after the foreman had gone. It was warm outdoors, and[m
[31m- he sat on the stoop in the afternoon. Sometimes his lips moved. He seemed[m
[31m- lost in endless calculations.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Next morning, after the day grew warm, he took his seat on the stoop. He[m
[31m- had pencil and paper this time with which to continue his calculations,[m
[31m- and he calculated painfully and amazingly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What comes after millions?” he asked at noon, when Will came home from[m
[31m- school. “An’ how d’ye work ’em?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- That afternoon finished his task. Each day, but without paper and pencil,[m
[31m- he returned to the stoop. He was greatly absorbed in the one tree that[m
[31m- grew across the street. He studied it for hours at a time, and was[m
[31m- unusually interested when the wind swayed its branches and fluttered its[m
[31m- leaves. Throughout the week he seemed lost in a great communion with[m
[31m- himself. On Sunday, sitting on the stoop, he laughed aloud, several times,[m
[31m- to the perturbation of his mother, who had not heard him laugh for years.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Next morning, in the early darkness, she came to his bed to rouse him. He[m
[31m- had had his fill of sleep all the week, and awoke easily. He made no[m
[31m- struggle, nor did he attempt to hold on to the bedding when she stripped[m
[31m- it from him. He lay quietly, and spoke quietly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It ain’t no use, ma.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’ll be late,” she said, under the impression that he was still stupid[m
[31m- with sleep.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m awake, ma, an’ I tell you it ain’t no use. You might as well lemme[m
[31m- alone. I ain’t goin’ to git up.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But you’ll lose your job!” she cried.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I ain’t goin’ to git up,” he repeated in a strange, passionless voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She did not go to work herself that morning. This was sickness beyond any[m
[31m- sickness she had ever known. Fever and delirium she could understand; but[m
[31m- this was insanity. She pulled the bedding up over him and sent Jennie for[m
[31m- the doctor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- When that person arrived, Johnny was sleeping gently, and gently he awoke[m
[31m- and allowed his pulse to be taken.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothing the matter with him,” the doctor reported. “Badly debilitated,[m
[31m- that’s all. Not much meat on his bones.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He’s always been that way,” his mother volunteered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now go ‘way, ma, an’ let me finish my snooze.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny spoke sweetly and placidly, and sweetly and placidly he rolled over[m
[31m- on his side and went to sleep.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At ten o’clock he awoke and dressed himself. He walked out into the[m
[31m- kitchen, where he found his mother with a frightened expression on her[m
[31m- face.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m goin’ away, ma,” he announced, “an’ I jes’ want to say good-bye.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She threw her apron over her head and sat down suddenly and wept. He[m
[31m- waited patiently.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I might a-known it,” she was sobbing.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Where?” she finally asked, removing the apron from her head and gazing up[m
[31m- at him with a stricken face in which there was little curiosity.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I don’t know⁠—anywhere.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As he spoke, the tree across the street appeared with dazzling brightness[m
[31m- on his inner vision. It seemed to lurk just under his eyelids, and he[m
[31m- could see it whenever he wished.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ your job?” she quavered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I ain’t never goin’ to work again.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “My God, Johnny!” she wailed, “don’t say that!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- What he had said was blasphemy to her. As a mother who hears her child[m
[31m- deny God, was Johnny’s mother shocked by his words.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What’s got into you, anyway?” she demanded, with a lame attempt at[m
[31m- imperativeness.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Figures,” he answered. “Jes’ figures. I’ve ben doin’ a lot of figurin’[m
[31m- this week, an’ it’s most surprisin’.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I don’t see what that’s got to do with it,” she sniffled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny smiled patiently, and his mother was aware of a distinct shock at[m
[31m- the persistent absence of his peevishness and irritability.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll show you,” he said. “I’m plum’ tired out. What makes me tired?[m
[31m- Moves. I’ve ben movin’ ever since I was born. I’m tired of movin’, an’ I[m
[31m- ain’t goin’ to move any more. Remember when I worked in the glass-house? I[m
[31m- used to do three hundred dozen a day. Now I reckon I made about ten[m
[31m- different moves to each bottle. That’s thirty-six thousan’ moves a day.[m
[31m- Ten days, three hundred an’ sixty thousan’ moves. One month, one million[m
[31m- an’ eighty thousan’ moves. Chuck out the eighty thousan’ ”⁠—he spoke[m
[31m- with the complacent beneficence of a philanthropist⁠—“chuck out the[m
[31m- eighty thousan’, that leaves a million moves a month⁠—twelve million[m
[31m- moves a year.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “At the looms I’m movin’ twic’st as much. That makes twenty-five million[m
[31m- moves a year, an’ it seems to me I’ve ben a movin’ that way ‘most a[m
[31m- million years.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now this week I ain’t moved at all. I ain’t made one move in hours an’[m
[31m- hours. I tell you it was swell, jes’ settin’ there, hours an’ hours, an’[m
[31m- doin’ nothin’. I ain’t never ben happy before. I never had any time. I’ve[m
[31m- ben movin’ all the time. That ain’t no way to be happy. An’ I ain’t going[m
[31m- to do it any more. I’m jes’ goin’ to set, an’ set, an’ rest, an’ rest, and[m
[31m- then rest some more.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But what’s goin’ to come of Will an’ the children?” she asked[m
[31m- despairingly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s it, ‘Will an’ the children,’ ” he repeated.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But there was no bitterness in his voice. He had long known his mother’s[m
[31m- ambition for the younger boy, but the thought of it no longer rankled.[m
[31m- Nothing mattered any more. Not even that.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I know, ma, what you’ve ben plannin’ for Will⁠—keepin’ him in school[m
[31m- to make a book-keeper out of him. But it ain’t no use, I’ve quit. He’s got[m
[31m- to go to work.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ after I have brung you up the way I have,” she wept, starting to[m
[31m- cover her head with the apron and changing her mind.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You never brung me up,” he answered with sad kindliness. “I brung myself[m
[31m- up, ma, an’ I brung up Will. He’s bigger’n me, an’ heavier, an’ taller.[m
[31m- When I was a kid, I reckon I didn’t git enough to eat. When he come along[m
[31m- an’ was a kid, I was workin’ an’ earnin’ grub for him too. But that’s done[m
[31m- with. Will can go to work, same as me, or he can go to hell, I don’t care[m
[31m- which. I’m tired. I’m goin’ now. Ain’t you goin’ to say goodbye?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She made no reply. The apron had gone over her head again, and she was[m
[31m- crying. He paused a moment in the doorway.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m sure I done the best I knew how,” she was sobbing.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He passed out of the house and down the street. A wan delight came into[m
[31m- his face at the sight of the lone tree. “Jes’ ain’t goin’ to do nothin’,”[m
[31m- he said to himself, half aloud, in a crooning tone. He glanced wistfully[m
[31m- up at the sky, but the bright sun dazzled and blinded him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was a long walk he took, and he did not walk fast. It took him past the[m
[31m- jute-mill. The muffled roar of the loom room came to his ears, and he[m
[31m- smiled. It was a gentle, placid smile. He hated no one, not even the[m
[31m- pounding, shrieking machines. There was no bitterness in him, nothing but[m
[31m- an inordinate hunger for rest.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The houses and factories thinned out and the open spaces increased as he[m
[31m- approached the country. At last the city was behind him, and he was[m
[31m- walking down a leafy lane beside the railroad track. He did not walk like[m
[31m- a man. He did not look like a man. He was a travesty of the human. It was[m
[31m- a twisted and stunted and nameless piece of life that shambled like a[m
[31m- sickly ape, arms loose-hanging, stoop-shouldered, narrow-chested,[m
[31m- grotesque and terrible.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He passed by a small railroad station and lay down in the grass under a[m
[31m- tree. All afternoon he lay there. Sometimes he dozed, with muscles that[m
[31m- twitched in his sleep. When awake, he lay without movement, watching the[m
[31m- birds or looking up at the sky through the branches of the tree above him.[m
[31m- Once or twice he laughed aloud, but without relevance to anything he had[m
[31m- seen or felt.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- After twilight had gone, in the first darkness of the night, a freight[m
[31m- train rumbled into the station. When the engine was switching cars on to[m
[31m- the side-track, Johnny crept along the side of the train. He pulled open[m
[31m- the side-door of an empty box-car and awkwardly and laboriously climbed[m
[31m- in. He closed the door. The engine whistled. Johnny was lying down, and in[m
[31m- the darkness he smiled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0002" name="link2H_4_0002">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- A WICKED WOMAN[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was because she had broken with Billy that Loretta had come visiting to[m
[31m- Santa Clara. Billy could not understand. His sister had reported that he[m
[31m- had walked the floor and cried all night. Loretta had not slept all night[m
[31m- either, while she had wept most of the night. Daisy knew this, because it[m
[31m- was in her arms that the weeping had been done. And Daisy’s husband,[m
[31m- Captain Kitt, knew, too. The tears of Loretta, and the comforting by[m
[31m- Daisy, had lost him some sleep.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Now Captain Kitt did not like to lose sleep. Neither did he want Loretta[m
[31m- to marry Billy⁠—nor anybody else. It was Captain Kitt’s belief that[m
[31m- Daisy needed the help of her younger sister in the household. But he did[m
[31m- not say this aloud. Instead, he always insisted that Loretta was too young[m
[31m- to think of marriage. So it was Captain Kitt’s idea that Loretta should be[m
[31m- packed off on a visit to Mrs. Hemingway. There wouldn’t be any Billy[m
[31m- there.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Before Loretta had been at Santa Clara a week, she was convinced that[m
[31m- Captain Kitt’s idea was a good one. In the first place, though Billy[m
[31m- wouldn’t believe it, she did not want to marry Billy. And in the second[m
[31m- place, though Captain Kitt wouldn’t believe it, she did not want to leave[m
[31m- Daisy. By the time Loretta had been at Santa Clara two weeks, she was[m
[31m- absolutely certain that she did not want to marry Billy. But she was not[m
[31m- so sure about not wanting to leave Daisy. Not that she loved Daisy less,[m
[31m- but that she⁠—had doubts.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The day of Loretta’s arrival, a nebulous plan began shaping itself in Mrs. Hemingway’s brain. The second day she remarked to Jack Hemingway, her[m
[31m- husband, that Loretta was so innocent a young thing that were it not for[m
[31m- her sweet guilelessness she would be positively stupid. In proof of which,[m
[31m- Mrs. Hemingway told her husband several things that made him chuckle. By[m
[31m- the third day Mrs. Hemingway’s plan had taken recognizable form. Then it[m
[31m- was that she composed a letter. On the envelope she wrote: “Mr. Edward[m
[31m- Bashford, Athenian Club, San Francisco.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Dear Ned,” the letter began. She had once been violently loved by him for[m
[31m- three weeks in her pre-marital days. But she had covenanted herself to[m
[31m- Jack Hemingway, who had prior claims, and her heart as well; and Ned[m
[31m- Bashford had philosophically not broken his heart over it. He merely added[m
[31m- the experience to a large fund of similarly collected data out of which he[m
[31m- manufactured philosophy. Artistically and temperamentally he was a Greek⁠—a[m
[31m- tired Greek. He was fond of quoting from Nietzsche, in token that he, too,[m
[31m- had passed through the long sickness that follows upon the ardent search[m
[31m- for truth; that he too had emerged, too experienced, too shrewd, too[m
[31m- profound, ever again to be afflicted by the madness of youths in their[m
[31m- love of truth. “ ‘To worship appearance,’ ” he often quoted; “ ‘to believe in[m
[31m- forms, in tones, in words, in the whole Olympus of appearance!’ ” This[m
[31m- particular excerpt he always concluded with, “ ‘Those Greeks were[m
[31m- superficial⁠—OUT OF PROFUNDITY!’ ”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He was a fairly young Greek, jaded and worn. Women were faithless and[m
[31m- unveracious, he held⁠—at such times that he had relapses and[m
[31m- descended to pessimism from his wonted high philosophical calm. He did not[m
[31m- believe in the truth of women; but, faithful to his German master, he did[m
[31m- not strip from them the airy gauzes that veiled their untruth. He was[m
[31m- content to accept them as appearances and to make the best of it. He was[m
[31m- superficial⁠—OUT OF PROFUNDITY.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Jack says to be sure to say to you, ‘good swimming,’ ” Mrs. Hemingway[m
[31m- wrote in her letter; “and also ‘to bring your fishing duds along.’ ” Mrs. Hemingway wrote other things in the letter. She told him that at last she[m
[31m- was prepared to exhibit to him an absolutely true, unsullied, and innocent[m
[31m- woman. “A more guileless, immaculate bud of womanhood never blushed on the[m
[31m- planet,” was one of the several ways in which she phrased the inducement.[m
[31m- And to her husband she said triumphantly, “If I don’t marry Ned off this[m
[31m- time⁠—” leaving unstated the terrible alternative that she lacked[m
[31m- either vocabulary to express or imagination to conceive.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Contrary to all her forebodings, Loretta found that she was not unhappy at[m
[31m- Santa Clara. Truly, Billy wrote to her every day, but his letters were[m
[31m- less distressing than his presence. Also, the ordeal of being away from[m
[31m- Daisy was not so severe as she had expected. For the first time in her[m
[31m- life she was not lost in eclipse in the blaze of Daisy’s brilliant and[m
[31m- mature personality. Under such favourable circumstances Loretta came[m
[31m- rapidly to the front, while Mrs. Hemingway modestly and shamelessly[m
[31m- retreated into the background.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Loretta began to discover that she was not a pale orb shining by[m
[31m- reflection. Quite unconsciously she became a small centre of things. When[m
[31m- she was at the piano, there was some one to turn the pages for her and to[m
[31m- express preferences for certain songs. When she dropped her handkerchief,[m
[31m- there was some one to pick it up. And there was some one to accompany her[m
[31m- in ramblings and flower gatherings. Also, she learned to cast flies in[m
[31m- still pools and below savage riffles, and how not to entangle silk lines[m
[31m- and gut-leaders with the shrubbery.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jack Hemingway did not care to teach beginners, and fished much by[m
[31m- himself, or not at all, thus giving Ned Bashford ample time in which to[m
[31m- consider Loretta as an appearance. As such, she was all that his[m
[31m- philosophy demanded. Her blue eyes had the direct gaze of a boy, and out[m
[31m- of his profundity he delighted in them and forbore to shudder at the[m
[31m- duplicity his philosophy bade him to believe lurked in their depths. She[m
[31m- had the grace of a slender flower, the fragility of colour and line of[m
[31m- fine china, in all of which he pleasured greatly, without thought of the[m
[31m- Life Force palpitating beneath and in spite of Bernard Shaw⁠—in whom[m
[31m- he believed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Loretta burgeoned. She swiftly developed personality. She discovered a[m
[31m- will of her own and wishes of her own that were not everlastingly entwined[m
[31m- with the will and the wishes of Daisy. She was petted by Jack Hemingway,[m
[31m- spoiled by Alice Hemingway, and devotedly attended by Ned Bashford. They[m
[31m- encouraged her whims and laughed at her follies, while she developed the[m
[31m- pretty little tyrannies that are latent in all pretty and delicate women.[m
[31m- Her environment acted as a soporific upon her ancient desire always to[m
[31m- live with Daisy. This desire no longer prodded her as in the days of her[m
[31m- companionship with Billy. The more she saw of Billy, the more certain she[m
[31m- had been that she could not live away from Daisy. The more she saw of Ned[m
[31m- Bashford, the more she forgot her pressing need of Daisy.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ned Bashford likewise did some forgetting. He confused superficiality with[m
[31m- profundity, and entangled appearance with reality until he accounted them[m
[31m- one. Loretta was different from other women. There was no masquerade about[m
[31m- her. She was real. He said as much to Mrs. Hemingway, and more, who agreed[m
[31m- with him and at the same time caught her husband’s eyelid drooping down[m
[31m- for the moment in an unmistakable wink.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was at this time that Loretta received a letter from Billy that was[m
[31m- somewhat different from his others. In the main, like all his letters, it[m
[31m- was pathological. It was a long recital of symptoms and sufferings, his[m
[31m- nervousness, his sleeplessness, and the state of his heart. Then followed[m
[31m- reproaches, such as he had never made before. They were sharp enough to[m
[31m- make her weep, and true enough to put tragedy into her face. This tragedy[m
[31m- she carried down to the breakfast table. It made Jack and Mrs. Hemingway[m
[31m- speculative, and it worried Ned. They glanced to him for explanation, but[m
[31m- he shook his head.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll find out to-night,” Mrs. Hemingway said to her husband.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But Ned caught Loretta in the afternoon in the big living-room. She tried[m
[31m- to turn away. He caught her hands, and she faced him with wet lashes and[m
[31m- trembling lips. He looked at her, silently and kindly. The lashes grew[m
[31m- wetter.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There, there, don’t cry, little one,” he said soothingly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He put his arm protectingly around her shoulder. And to his shoulder, like[m
[31m- a tired child, she turned her face. He thrilled in ways unusual for a[m
[31m- Greek who has recovered from the long sickness.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh, Ned,” she sobbed on his shoulder, “if you only knew how wicked I am!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He smiled indulgently, and breathed in a great breath freighted with the[m
[31m- fragrance of her hair. He thought of his world-experience of women, and[m
[31m- drew another long breath. There seemed to emanate from her the perfect[m
[31m- sweetness of a child⁠—“the aura of a white soul,” was the way he[m
[31m- phrased it to himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Then he noticed that her sobs were increasing.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What’s the matter, little one?” he asked pettingly and almost paternally.[m
[31m- “Has Jack been bullying you? Or has your dearly beloved sister failed to[m
[31m- write?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She did not answer, and he felt that he really must kiss her hair, that he[m
[31m- could not be responsible if the situation continued much longer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Tell me,” he said gently, “and we’ll see what I can do.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I can’t. You will despise me.⁠—Oh, Ned, I am so ashamed!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He laughed incredulously, and lightly touched her hair with his lips⁠—so[m
[31m- lightly that she did not know.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Dear little one, let us forget all about it, whatever it is. I want to[m
[31m- tell you how I love⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She uttered a sharp cry that was all delight, and then moaned⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Too late!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Too late?” he echoed in surprise.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh, why did I? Why did I?” she was moaning.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He was aware of a swift chill at his heart.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What?” he asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh, I … he … Billy.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I am such a wicked woman, Ned. I know you will never speak to me again.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “This⁠—er⁠—this Billy,” he began haltingly. “He is your[m
[31m- brother?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “No … he … I didn’t know. I was so young. I could not help it. Oh, I[m
[31m- shall go mad! I shall go mad!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was then that Loretta felt his shoulder and the encircling arm become[m
[31m- limp. He drew away from her gently, and gently he deposited her in a big[m
[31m- chair, where she buried her face and sobbed afresh. He twisted his[m
[31m- moustache fiercely, then drew up another chair and sat down.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I⁠—I do not understand,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I am so unhappy,” she wailed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why unhappy?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Because … he … he wants me to marry him.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His face cleared on the instant, and he placed a hand soothingly on hers.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That should not make any girl unhappy,” he remarked sagely. “Because you[m
[31m- don’t love him is no reason⁠—of course, you don’t love him?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Loretta shook her head and shoulders in a vigorous negative.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Bashford wanted to make sure.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “No,” she asserted explosively. “I don’t love Billy! I don’t want to love[m
[31m- Billy!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Because you don’t love him,” Bashford resumed with confidence, “is no[m
[31m- reason that you should be unhappy just because he has proposed to you.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She sobbed again, and from the midst of her sobs she cried⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s the trouble. I wish I did love him. Oh, I wish I were dead!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now, my dear child, you are worrying yourself over trifles.” His other[m
[31m- hand crossed over after its mate and rested on hers. “Women do it every[m
[31m- day. Because you have changed your mind or did not know your mind, because[m
[31m- you have⁠—to use an unnecessarily harsh word⁠—jilted a man⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Jilted!” She had raised her head and was looking at him with tear-dimmed[m
[31m- eyes. “Oh, Ned, if that were all!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All?” he asked in a hollow voice, while his hands slowly retreated from[m
[31m- hers. He was about to speak further, then remained silent.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I don’t want to marry him,” Loretta broke forth protestingly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then I shouldn’t,” he counselled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I ought to marry him.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “OUGHT to marry him?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She nodded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That is a strong word.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I know it is,” she acquiesced, while she strove to control her trembling[m
[31m- lips. Then she spoke more calmly. “I am a wicked woman, a terribly wicked[m
[31m- woman. No one knows how wicked I am⁠—except Billy.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There was a pause. Ned Bashford’s face was grave, and he looked queerly at[m
[31m- Loretta.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He⁠—Billy knows?” he asked finally.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A reluctant nod and flaming cheeks was the reply.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He debated with himself for a while, seeming, like a diver, to be[m
[31m- preparing himself for the plunge.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Tell me about it.” He spoke very firmly. “You must tell me all of it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And will you⁠—ever⁠—forgive me?” she asked in a faint, small[m
[31m- voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He hesitated, drew a long breath, and made the plunge.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes,” he said desperately. “I’ll forgive you. Go ahead.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There was no one to tell me,” she began. “We were with each other so[m
[31m- much. I did not know anything of the world⁠—then.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She paused to meditate. Bashford was biting his lip impatiently.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If I had only known⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She paused again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, go on,” he urged.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “We were together almost every evening.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Billy?” he demanded, with a savageness that startled her.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, of course, Billy. We were with each other so much … If I had only[m
[31m- known … There was no one to tell me … I was so young⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Her lips parted as though to speak further, and she regarded him[m
[31m- anxiously.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The scoundrel!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- With the explosion Ned Bashford was on his feet, no longer a tired Greek,[m
[31m- but a violently angry young man.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Billy is not a scoundrel; he is a good man,” Loretta defended, with a[m
[31m- firmness that surprised Bashford.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I suppose you’ll be telling me next that it was all your fault,” he said[m
[31m- sarcastically.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She nodded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What?” he shouted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It was all my fault,” she said steadily. “I should never have let him. I[m
[31m- was to blame.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Bashford ceased from his pacing up and down, and when he spoke, his voice[m
[31m- was resigned.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All right,” he said. “I don’t blame you in the least, Loretta. And you[m
[31m- have been very honest. But Billy is right, and you are wrong. You must get[m
[31m- married.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “To Billy?” she asked, in a dim, far-away voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, to Billy. I’ll see to it. Where does he live? I’ll make him.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I don’t want to marry Billy!” she cried out in alarm. “Oh, Ned, you[m
[31m- won’t do that?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I shall,” he answered sternly. “You must. And Billy must. Do you[m
[31m- understand?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Loretta buried her face in the cushioned chair back, and broke into a[m
[31m- passionate storm of sobs.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- All that Bashford could make out at first, as he listened, was: “But I[m
[31m- don’t want to leave Daisy! I don’t want to leave Daisy!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He paced grimly back and forth, then stopped curiously to listen.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How was I to know?⁠—Boo⁠—hoo,” Loretta was crying. “He didn’t[m
[31m- tell me. Nobody else ever kissed me. I never dreamed a kiss could be so[m
[31m- terrible … until, boo-hoo … until he wrote to me. I only got the letter[m
[31m- this morning.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His face brightened. It seemed as though light was dawning on him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Is that what you’re crying about?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “N⁠—no.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His heart sank.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then what are you crying about?” he asked in a hopeless voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Because you said I had to marry Billy. And I don’t want to marry Billy. I[m
[31m- don’t want to leave Daisy. I don’t know what I want. I wish I were dead.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He nerved himself for another effort.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now look here, Loretta, be sensible. What is this about kisses. You[m
[31m- haven’t told me everything?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I⁠—I don’t want to tell you everything.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She looked at him beseechingly in the silence that fell.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Must I?” she quavered finally.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You must,” he said imperatively. “You must tell me everything.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, then … must I?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You must.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He … I … we …” she began flounderingly. Then blurted out, “I let him,[m
[31m- and he kissed me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Go on,” Bashford commanded desperately.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s all,” she answered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All?” There was a vast incredulity in his voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All?” In her voice was an interrogation no less vast.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I mean⁠—er⁠—nothing worse?” He was overwhelmingly aware of his[m
[31m- own awkwardness.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Worse?” She was frankly puzzled. “As though there could be! Billy said⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “When did he say it?” Bashford demanded abruptly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “In his letter I got this morning. Billy said that my … our … our kisses[m
[31m- were terrible if we didn’t get married.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Bashford’s head was swimming.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What else did Billy say?” he asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He said that when a woman allowed a man to kiss her, she always married[m
[31m- him⁠—that it was terrible if she didn’t. It was the custom, he said;[m
[31m- and I say it is a bad, wicked custom, and I don’t like it. I know I’m[m
[31m- terrible,” she added defiantly, “but I can’t help it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Bashford absent-mindedly brought out a cigarette.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Do you mind if I smoke?” he asked, as he struck a match.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Then he came to himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I beg your pardon,” he cried, flinging away match and cigarette. “I don’t[m
[31m- want to smoke. I didn’t mean that at all. What I mean is⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He bent over Loretta, caught her hands in his, then sat on the arm of the[m
[31m- chair and softly put one arm around her.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Loretta, I am a fool. I mean it. And I mean something more. I want you to[m
[31m- be my wife.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He waited anxiously in the pause that followed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You might answer me,” he urged.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I will … if⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, go on. If what?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If I don’t have to marry Billy.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You can’t marry both of us,” he almost shouted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And it isn’t the custom … what … what Billy said?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “No, it isn’t the custom. Now, Loretta, will you marry me?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t be angry with me,” she pouted demurely.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He gathered her into his arms and kissed her.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I wish it were the custom,” she said in a faint voice, from the midst of[m
[31m- the embrace, “because then I’d have to marry you, Ned dear … wouldn’t I?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0003" name="link2H_4_0003">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- JUST MEAT[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He strolled to the corner and glanced up and down the intersecting street,[m
[31m- but saw nothing save the oases of light shed by the street lamps at the[m
[31m- successive crossings. Then he strolled back the way he had come. He was a[m
[31m- shadow of a man, sliding noiselessly and without undue movement through[m
[31m- the semi-darkness. Also he was very alert, like a wild animal in the[m
[31m- jungle, keenly perceptive and receptive. The movement of another in the[m
[31m- darkness about him would need to have been more shadowy than he to have[m
[31m- escaped him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In addition to the running advertisement of the state of affairs carried[m
[31m- to him by his senses, he had a subtler perception, a FEEL, of the[m
[31m- atmosphere around him. He knew that the house in front of which he paused[m
[31m- for a moment, contained children. Yet by no willed effort of perception[m
[31m- did he have this knowledge. For that matter, he was not even aware that he[m
[31m- knew, so occult was the impression. Yet, did a moment arise in which[m
[31m- action, in relation to that house, were imperative, he would have acted on[m
[31m- the assumption that it contained children. He was not aware of all that he[m
[31m- knew about the neighbourhood.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the same way, he knew not how, he knew that no danger threatened in the[m
[31m- footfalls that came up the cross street. Before he saw the walker, he knew[m
[31m- him for a belated pedestrian hurrying home. The walker came into view at[m
[31m- the crossing and disappeared on up the street. The man that watched, noted[m
[31m- a light that flared up in the window of a house on the corner, and as it[m
[31m- died down he knew it for an expiring match. This was conscious[m
[31m- identification of familiar phenomena, and through his mind flitted the[m
[31m- thought, “Wanted to know what time.” In another house one room was[m
[31m- lighted. The light burned dimly and steadily, and he had the feel that it[m
[31m- was a sick-room.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He was especially interested in a house across the street in the middle of[m
[31m- the block. To this house he paid most attention. No matter what way he[m
[31m- looked, nor what way he walked, his looks and his steps always returned to[m
[31m- it. Except for an open window above the porch, there was nothing unusual[m
[31m- about the house. Nothing came in nor out. Nothing happened. There were no[m
[31m- lighted windows, nor had lights appeared and disappeared in any of the[m
[31m- windows. Yet it was the central point of his consideration. He rallied to[m
[31m- it each time after a divination of the state of the neighbourhood.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Despite his feel of things, he was not confident. He was supremely[m
[31m- conscious of the precariousness of his situation. Though unperturbed by[m
[31m- the footfalls of the chance pedestrian, he was as keyed up and sensitive[m
[31m- and ready to be startled as any timorous deer. He was aware of the[m
[31m- possibility of other intelligences prowling about in the darkness⁠—intelligences[m
[31m- similar to his own in movement, perception, and divination.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Far down the street he caught a glimpse of something that moved. And he[m
[31m- knew it was no late home-goer, but menace and danger. He whistled twice to[m
[31m- the house across the street, then faded away shadow-like to the corner and[m
[31m- around the corner. Here he paused and looked about him carefully.[m
[31m- Reassured, he peered back around the corner and studied the object that[m
[31m- moved and that was coming nearer. He had divined aright. It was a[m
[31m- policeman.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The man went down the cross street to the next corner, from the shelter of[m
[31m- which he watched the corner he had just left. He saw the policeman pass[m
[31m- by, going straight on up the street. He paralleled the policeman’s course,[m
[31m- and from the next corner again watched him go by; then he returned the way[m
[31m- he had come. He whistled once to the house across the street, and after a[m
[31m- time whistled once again. There was reassurance in the whistle, just as[m
[31m- there had been warning in the previous double whistle.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He saw a dark bulk outline itself on the roof of the porch and slowly[m
[31m- descend a pillar. Then it came down the steps, passed through the small[m
[31m- iron gate, and went down the sidewalk, taking on the form of a man. He[m
[31m- that watched kept on his own side of the street and moved on abreast to[m
[31m- the corner, where he crossed over and joined the other. He was quite small[m
[31m- alongside the man he accosted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How’d you make out, Matt?” he asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The other grunted indistinctly, and walked on in silence a few steps.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I reckon I landed the goods,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim chuckled in the darkness, and waited for further information. The[m
[31m- blocks passed by under their feet, and he grew impatient.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, how about them goods?” he asked. “What kind of a haul did you make,[m
[31m- anyway?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I was too busy to figger it out, but it’s fat. I can tell you that much,[m
[31m- Jim, it’s fat. I don’t dast to think how fat it is. Wait till we get to[m
[31m- the room.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim looked at him keenly under the street lamp of the next crossing, and[m
[31m- saw that his face was a trifle grim and that he carried his left arm[m
[31m- peculiarly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What’s the matter with your arm?” he demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The little cuss bit me. Hope I don’t get hydrophoby. Folks gets[m
[31m- hydrophoby from manbite sometimes, don’t they?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Gave you fight, eh?” Jim asked encouragingly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The other grunted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’re harder’n hell to get information from,” Jim burst out irritably.[m
[31m- “Tell us about it. You ain’t goin’ to lose money just a-tellin’ a guy.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I guess I choked him some,” came the answer. Then, by way of explanation,[m
[31m- “He woke up on me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You did it neat. I never heard a sound.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Jim,” the other said with seriousness, “it’s a hangin’ matter. I fixed[m
[31m- ‘m. I had to. He woke up on me. You an’ me’s got to do some layin’ low for[m
[31m- a spell.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim gave a low whistle of comprehension.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Did you hear me whistle?” he asked suddenly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Sure. I was all done. I was just comin’ out.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It was a bull. But he wasn’t on a little bit. Went right by an’ kept[m
[31m- a-paddin’ the hoof out a sight. Then I come back an’ gave you the whistle.[m
[31m- What made you take so long after that?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I was waitin’ to make sure,” Matt explained. “I was mighty glad when I[m
[31m- heard you whistle again. It’s hard work waitin’. I just sat there an’[m
[31m- thought an’ thought … oh, all kinds of things. It’s remarkable what a[m
[31m- fellow’ll think about. And then there was a darn cat that kept movin’[m
[31m- around the house all’ botherin’ me with its noises.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ it’s fat!” Jim exclaimed irrelevantly and with joy.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m sure tellin’ you, Jim, it’s fat. I’m plum’ anxious for another look[m
[31m- at ’em.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Unconsciously the two men quickened their pace. Yet they did not relax[m
[31m- from their caution. Twice they changed their course in order to avoid[m
[31m- policemen, and they made very sure that they were not observed when they[m
[31m- dived into the dark hallway of a cheap rooming house down town.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Not until they had gained their own room on the top floor, did they[m
[31m- scratch a match. While Jim lighted a lamp, Matt locked the door and threw[m
[31m- the bolts into place. As he turned, he noticed that his partner was[m
[31m- waiting expectantly. Matt smiled to himself at the other’s eagerness.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Them search-lights is all right,” he said, drawing forth a small pocket[m
[31m- electric lamp and examining it. “But we got to get a new battery. It’s[m
[31m- runnin’ pretty weak. I thought once or twice it’d leave me in the dark.[m
[31m- Funny arrangements in that house. I near got lost. His room was on the[m
[31m- left, an’ that fooled me some.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I told you it was on the left,” Jim interrupted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You told me it was on the right,” Matt went on. “I guess I know what you[m
[31m- told me, an’ there’s the map you drew.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Fumbling in his vest pocket, he drew out a folded slip of paper. As he[m
[31m- unfolded it, Jim bent over and looked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I did make a mistake,” he confessed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You sure did. It got me guessin’ some for a while.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But it don’t matter now,” Jim cried. “Let’s see what you got.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It does matter,” Matt retorted. “It matters a lot … to me. I’ve got to[m
[31m- run all the risk. I put my head in the trap while you stay on the street.[m
[31m- You got to get on to yourself an’ be more careful. All right, I’ll show[m
[31m- you.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He dipped loosely into his trousers pocket and brought out a handful of[m
[31m- small diamonds. He spilled them out in a blazing stream on the greasy[m
[31m- table. Jim let out a great oath.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s nothing,” Matt said with triumphant complacence. “I ain’t begun[m
[31m- yet.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- From one pocket after another he continued bringing forth the spoil. There[m
[31m- were many diamonds wrapped in chamois skin that were larger than those in[m
[31m- the first handful. From one pocket he brought out a handful of very small[m
[31m- cut gems.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Sun dust,” he remarked, as he spilled them on the table in a space by[m
[31m- themselves.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim examined them.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Just the same, they retail for a couple of dollars each,” he said. “Is[m
[31m- that all?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ain’t it enough?” the other demanded in an aggrieved tone.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Sure it is,” Jim answered with unqualified approval. “Better’n I[m
[31m- expected. I wouldn’t take a cent less than ten thousan’ for the bunch.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ten thousan’,” Matt sneered. “They’re worth twic’t that, an’ I don’t know[m
[31m- anything about joolery, either. Look at that big boy!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He picked it out from the sparkling heap and held it near to the lamp with[m
[31m- the air of an expert, weighing and judging.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Worth a thousan’ all by its lonely,” was Jim’s quicker judgment.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A thousan’ your grandmother,” was Matt’s scornful rejoinder. “You[m
[31m- couldn’t buy it for three.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Wake me up! I’m dreamin’!” The sparkle of the gems was in Jim’s eyes, and[m
[31m- he began sorting out the larger diamonds and examining them. “We’re rich[m
[31m- men, Matt⁠—we’ll be regular swells.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’ll take years to get rid of ’em,” was Matt’s more practical thought.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But think how we’ll live! Nothin’ to do but spend the money an’ go on[m
[31m- gettin’ rid of em.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt’s eyes were beginning to sparkle, though sombrely, as his phlegmatic[m
[31m- nature woke up.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I told you I didn’t dast think how fat it was,” he murmured in a low[m
[31m- voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What a killin’! What a killin’!” was the other’s more ecstatic utterance.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I almost forgot,” Matt said, thrusting his hand into his inside coat[m
[31m- pocket.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A string of large pearls emerged from wrappings of tissue paper and[m
[31m- chamois skin. Jim scarcely glanced at them.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They’re worth money,” he said, and returned to the diamonds.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A silence fell on the two men. Jim played with the gems, running them[m
[31m- through his fingers, sorting them into piles, and spreading them out flat[m
[31m- and wide. He was a slender, weazened man, nervous, irritable, high-strung,[m
[31m- and anaemic⁠—a typical child of the gutter, with unbeautiful twisted[m
[31m- features, small-eyed, with face and mouth perpetually and feverishly[m
[31m- hungry, brutish in a cat-like way, stamped to the core with degeneracy.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt did not finger the diamonds. He sat with chin on hands and elbows on[m
[31m- table, blinking heavily at the blazing array. He was in every way a[m
[31m- contrast to the other. No city had bred him. He was heavy-muscled and[m
[31m- hairy, gorilla-like in strength and aspect. For him there was no unseen[m
[31m- world. His eyes were full and wide apart, and there seemed in them a[m
[31m- certain bold brotherliness. They inspired confidence. But a closer[m
[31m- inspection would have shown that his eyes were just a trifle too full,[m
[31m- just a shade too wide apart. He exceeded, spilled over the limits of[m
[31m- normality, and his features told lies about the man beneath.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The bunch is worth fifty thousan’,” Jim remarked suddenly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A hundred thousan’,” Matt said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The silence returned and endured a long time, to be broken again by Jim.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What in hell was he doin’ with ’em all at the house?⁠—that’s what I[m
[31m- want to know. I’d a-thought he’d kept ’em in the safe down at the store.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt had just been considering the vision of the throttled man as he had[m
[31m- last looked upon him in the dim light of the electric lantern; but he did[m
[31m- not start at the mention of him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There’s no tellin’,” he answered. “He might a-ben gettin’ ready to chuck[m
[31m- his pardner. He might a-pulled out in the mornin’ for parts unknown, if we[m
[31m- hadn’t happened along. I guess there’s just as many thieves among honest[m
[31m- men as there is among thieves. You read about such things in the papers,[m
[31m- Jim. Pardners is always knifin’ each other.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A queer, nervous look came into the other’s eyes. Matt did not betray that[m
[31m- he noted it, though he said⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What was you thinkin’ about, Jim?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim was a trifle awkward for the moment.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothin’,” he answered. “Only I was thinkin’ just how funny it was⁠—all[m
[31m- them jools at his house. What made you ask?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothin’. I was just wonderin’, that was all.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The silence settled down, broken by an occasional low and nervous giggle[m
[31m- on the part of Jim. He was overcome by the spread of gems. It was not that[m
[31m- he felt their beauty. He was unaware that they were beautiful in[m
[31m- themselves. But in them his swift imagination visioned the joys of life[m
[31m- they would buy, and all the desires and appetites of his diseased mind and[m
[31m- sickly flesh were tickled by the promise they extended. He builded[m
[31m- wondrous, orgy-haunted castles out of their brilliant fires, and was[m
[31m- appalled at what he builded. Then it was that he giggled. It was all too[m
[31m- impossible to be real. And yet there they blazed on the table before him,[m
[31m- fanning the flame of the lust of him, and he giggled again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I guess we might as well count ’em,” Matt said suddenly, tearing himself[m
[31m- away from his own visions. “You watch me an’ see that it’s square, because[m
[31m- you an’ me has got to be on the square, Jim. Understand?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim did not like this, and betrayed it in his eyes, while Matt did not[m
[31m- like what he saw in his partner’s eyes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Understand?” Matt repeated, almost menacingly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ain’t we always ben square?” the other replied, on the defensive because[m
[31m- of the treachery already whispering in him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It don’t cost nothin’, bein’ square in hard times,” Matt retorted. “It’s[m
[31m- bein’ square in prosperity that counts. When we ain’t got nothin’, we[m
[31m- can’t help bein’ square. We’re prosperous now, an’ we’ve got to be[m
[31m- business men⁠—honest business men. Understand?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s the talk for me,” Jim approved, but deep down in the meagre soul[m
[31m- of him⁠—and in spite of him⁠—wanton and lawless thoughts were[m
[31m- stirring like chained beasts.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt stepped to the food shelf behind the two-burner kerosene cooking[m
[31m- stove. He emptied the tea from a paper bag, and from a second bag emptied[m
[31m- some red peppers. Returning to the table with the bags, he put into them[m
[31m- the two sizes of small diamonds. Then he counted the large gems and[m
[31m- wrapped them in their tissue paper and chamois skin.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Hundred an’ forty-seven good-sized ones,” was his inventory; “twenty real[m
[31m- big ones; two big boys and one whopper; an’ a couple of fistfuls of teeny[m
[31m- ones an’ dust.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He looked at Jim.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Correct,” was the response.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He wrote the count out on a slip of memorandum paper, and made a copy of[m
[31m- it, giving one slip to his partner and retaining the other.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Just for reference,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Again he had recourse to the food shelf, where he emptied the sugar from a[m
[31m- large paper bag. Into this he thrust the diamonds, large and small,[m
[31m- wrapped it up in a bandanna handkerchief, and stowed it away under his[m
[31m- pillow. Then he sat down on the edge of the bed and took off his shoes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ you think they’re worth a hundred thousan’?” Jim asked, pausing and[m
[31m- looking up from the unlacing of his shoe.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Sure,” was the answer. “I seen a dance-house girl down in Arizona once,[m
[31m- with some big sparklers on her. They wasn’t real. She said if they was she[m
[31m- wouldn’t be dancin’. Said they’d be worth all of fifty thousan’, an’ she[m
[31m- didn’t have a dozen of ’em all told.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Who’d work for a livin’?” Jim triumphantly demanded. “Pick an’ shovel[m
[31m- work!” he sneered. “Work like a dog all my life, an’ save all my wages,[m
[31m- an’ I wouldn’t have half as much as we got tonight.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Dish washin’s about your measure, an’ you couldn’t get more’n twenty a[m
[31m- month an’ board. Your figgers is ‘way off, but your point is well taken.[m
[31m- Let them that likes it, work. I rode range for thirty a month when I was[m
[31m- young an’ foolish. Well, I’m older, an’ I ain’t ridin’ range.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He got into bed on one side. Jim put out the light and followed him in on[m
[31m- the other side.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How’s your arm feel?” Jim queried amiably.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Such concern was unusual, and Matt noted it, and replied⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I guess there’s no danger of hydrophoby. What made you ask?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim felt in himself a guilty stir, and under his breath he cursed the[m
[31m- other’s way of asking disagreeable questions; but aloud he answered⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothin’, only you seemed scared of it at first. What are you goin’ to do[m
[31m- with your share, Matt?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Buy a cattle ranch in Arizona an’ set down an’ pay other men to ride[m
[31m- range for me. There’s some several I’d like to see askin’ a job from me,[m
[31m- damn them! An’ now you shut your face, Jim. It’ll be some time before I[m
[31m- buy that ranch. Just now I’m goin’ to sleep.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But Jim lay long awake, nervous and twitching, rolling about restlessly[m
[31m- and rolling himself wide awake every time he dozed. The diamonds still[m
[31m- blazed under his eyelids, and the fire of them hurt. Matt, in spite of his[m
[31m- heavy nature, slept lightly, like a wild animal alert in its sleep; and[m
[31m- Jim noticed, every time he moved, that his partner’s body moved[m
[31m- sufficiently to show that it had received the impression and that it was[m
[31m- trembling on the verge of awakening. For that matter, Jim did not know[m
[31m- whether or not, frequently, the other was awake. Once, quietly, betokening[m
[31m- complete consciousness, Matt said to him: “Aw, go to sleep, Jim. Don’t[m
[31m- worry about them jools. They’ll keep.” And Jim had thought that at that[m
[31m- particular moment Matt had been surely asleep.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the late morning Matt was awake with Jim’s first movement, and[m
[31m- thereafter he awoke and dozed with him until midday, when they got up[m
[31m- together and began dressing.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m goin’ out to get a paper an’ some bread,” Matt said. “You boil the[m
[31m- coffee.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As Jim listened, unconsciously his gaze left Matt’s face and roved to the[m
[31m- pillow, beneath which was the bundle wrapped in the bandanna handkerchief.[m
[31m- On the instant Matt’s face became like a wild beast’s.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Look here, Jim,” he snarled. “You’ve got to play square. If you do me[m
[31m- dirt, I’ll fix you. Understand? I’d eat you, Jim. You know that. I’d bite[m
[31m- right into your throat an’ eat you like that much beefsteak.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His sunburned skin was black with the surge of blood in it, and his[m
[31m- tobacco-stained teeth were exposed by the snarling lips. Jim shivered and[m
[31m- involuntarily cowered. There was death in the man he looked at. Only the[m
[31m- night before that black-faced man had killed another with his hands, and[m
[31m- it had not hurt his sleep. And in his own heart Jim was aware of a[m
[31m- sneaking guilt, of a train of thought that merited all that was[m
[31m- threatened.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt passed out, leaving him still shivering. Then a hatred twisted his[m
[31m- own face, and he softly hurled savage curses at the door. He remembered[m
[31m- the jewels, and hastened to the bed, feeling under the pillow for the[m
[31m- bandanna bundle. He crushed it with his fingers to make certain that it[m
[31m- still contained the diamonds. Assured that Matt had not carried them away,[m
[31m- he looked toward the kerosene stove with a guilty start. Then he hurriedly[m
[31m- lighted it, filled the coffee-pot at the sink, and put it over the flame.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The coffee was boiling when Matt returned, and while the latter cut the[m
[31m- bread and put a slice of butter on the table, Jim poured out the coffee.[m
[31m- It was not until he sat down and had taken a few sips of the coffee, that[m
[31m- Matt pulled out the morning paper from his pocket.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “We was way off,” he said. “I told you I didn’t dast figger out how fat it[m
[31m- was. Look at that.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He pointed to the head-lines on the first page.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “SWIFT NEMESIS ON BUJANNOFF’S TRACK,” they read. “MURDERED IN HIS SLEEP[m
[31m- AFTER ROBBING HIS PARTNER.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There you have it!” Matt cried. “He robbed his partner⁠—robbed him[m
[31m- like a dirty thief.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Half a million of jewels missin’,” Jim read aloud. He put the paper down[m
[31m- and stared at Matt.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s what I told you,” the latter said. “What in hell do we know about[m
[31m- jools? Half a million!⁠—an’ the best I could figger it was a hundred[m
[31m- thousan’. Go on an’ read the rest of it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They read on silently, their heads side by side, the untouched coffee[m
[31m- growing cold; and ever and anon one or the other burst forth with some[m
[31m- salient printed fact.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’d like to seen Metzner’s face when he opened the safe at the store this[m
[31m- mornin’,” Jim gloated.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He hit the high places right away for Bujannoff’s house,” Matt explained.[m
[31m- “Go on an’ read.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Was to have sailed last night at ten on the <em>Sajoda</em> for the South Seas⁠—steamship[m
[31m- delayed by extra freight⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s why we caught ‘m in bed,” Matt interrupted. “It was just luck⁠—like[m
[31m- pickin’ a fifty-to-one winner.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “<em>Sajoda</em> sailed at six this mornin’⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He didn’t catch her,” Matt said. “I saw his alarm-clock was set at five.[m
[31m- That’d given ‘m plenty of time … only I come along an’ put the <em>kibosh</em> on[m
[31m- his time. Go on.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Adolph Metzner in despair⁠—the famous Haythorne pearl necklace⁠—magnificently[m
[31m- assorted pearls⁠—valued by experts at from fifty to seventy thousan’[m
[31m- dollars.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim broke off to swear vilely and solemnly, concluding with, “Those damn[m
[31m- oyster-eggs worth all that money!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He licked his lips and added, “They was beauties an’ no mistake.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Big Brazilian gem,” he read on. “Eighty thousan’ dollars⁠—many[m
[31m- valuable gems of the first water⁠—several thousan’ small diamonds[m
[31m- well worth forty thousan’.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What you don’t know about jools is worth knowin’,” Matt smiled[m
[31m- good-humouredly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Theory of the sleuths,” Jim read. “Thieves must have known⁠—cleverly[m
[31m- kept watch on Bujannoff’s actions⁠—must have learned his plan and[m
[31m- trailed him to his house with the fruits of his robbery⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Clever⁠—hell!” Matt broke out. “That’s the way reputations is[m
[31m- made … in the noospapers. How’d we know he was robbin’ his pardner?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Anyway, we’ve got the goods,” Jim grinned. “Let’s look at ’em again.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He assured himself that the door was locked and bolted, while Matt brought[m
[31m- out the bundle in the bandanna and opened it on the table.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ain’t they beauties, though!” Jim exclaimed at sight of the pearls; and[m
[31m- for a time he had eyes only for them. “Accordin’ to the experts, worth[m
[31m- from fifty to seventy thousan’ dollars.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ women like them things,” Matt commented. “An’ they’ll do everything[m
[31m- to get ’em⁠—sell themselves, commit murder, anything.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Just like you an’ me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Not on your life,” Matt retorted. “I’ll commit murder for ’em, but not[m
[31m- for their own sakes, but for sake of what they’ll get me. That’s the[m
[31m- difference. Women want the jools for themselves, an’ I want the jools for[m
[31m- the women an’ such things they’ll get me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Lucky that men an’ women don’t want the same things,” Jim remarked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s what makes commerce,” Matt agreed; “people wantin’ different[m
[31m- things.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the middle of the afternoon Jim went out to buy food. While he was[m
[31m- gone, Matt cleared the table of the jewels, wrapping them up as before and[m
[31m- putting them under the pillow. Then he lighted the kerosene stove and[m
[31m- started to boil water for coffee. A few minutes later, Jim returned.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Most surprising,” he remarked. “Streets, an’ stores, an’ people just like[m
[31m- they always was. Nothin’ changed. An’ me walking along through it all a[m
[31m- millionaire. Nobody looked at me an’ guessed it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt grunted unsympathetically. He had little comprehension of the lighter[m
[31m- whims and fancies of his partner’s imagination.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Did you get a porterhouse?” he demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Sure, an’ an inch thick. It’s a peach. Look at it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He unwrapped the steak and held it up for the other’s inspection. Then he[m
[31m- made the coffee and set the table, while Matt fried the steak.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t put on too much of them red peppers,” Jim warned. “I ain’t used to[m
[31m- your Mexican cookin’. You always season too hot.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt grunted a laugh and went on with his cooking. Jim poured out the[m
[31m- coffee, but first, into the nicked china cup, he emptied a powder he had[m
[31m- carried in his vest pocket wrapped in a rice-paper. He had turned his back[m
[31m- for the moment on his partner, but he did not dare to glance around at[m
[31m- him. Matt placed a newspaper on the table, and on the newspaper set the[m
[31m- hot frying-pan. He cut the steak in half, and served Jim and himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Eat her while she’s hot,” he counselled, and with knife and fork set the[m
[31m- example.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “She’s a dandy,” was Jim’s judgment, after his first mouthful. “But I tell[m
[31m- you one thing straight. I’m never goin’ to visit you on that Arizona[m
[31m- ranch, so you needn’t ask me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What’s the matter now?” Matt asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Hell’s the matter,” was the answer. “The Mexican cookin’ on your ranch’d[m
[31m- be too much for me. If I’ve got hell a-comin’ in the next life, I’m not[m
[31m- goin’ to torment my insides in this one. Damned peppers!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He smiled, expelled his breath forcibly to cool his burning mouth, drank[m
[31m- some coffee, and went on eating the steak.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What do you think about the next life anyway, Matt?” he asked a little[m
[31m- later, while secretly he wondered why the other had not yet touched his[m
[31m- coffee.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ain’t no next life,” Matt answered, pausing from the steak to take his[m
[31m- first sip of coffee. “Nor heaven nor hell, nor nothin’. You get all that’s[m
[31m- comin’ right here in this life.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ afterward?” Jim queried out of his morbid curiosity, for he knew that[m
[31m- he looked upon a man that was soon to die. “An’ afterward?” he repeated.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Did you ever see a man two weeks dead?” the other asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim shook his head.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, I have. He was like this beefsteak you an’ me is eatin’. It was[m
[31m- once steer cavortin’ over the landscape. But now it’s just meat. That’s[m
[31m- all, just meat. An’ that’s what you an’ me an’ all people come to⁠—meat.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt gulped down the whole cup of coffee, and refilled the cup.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Are you scared to die?” he asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim shook his head. “What’s the use? I don’t die anyway. I pass on an’[m
[31m- live again⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “To go stealin’, an’ lyin’ an’ snivellin’ through another life, an’ go on[m
[31m- that way forever an’ ever an’ ever?” Matt sneered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Maybe I’ll improve,” Jim suggested hopefully. “Maybe stealin’ won’t be[m
[31m- necessary in the life to come.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He ceased abruptly, and stared straight before him, a frightened[m
[31m- expression on his face.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What’s the matter!” Matt demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothin’. I was just wonderin’ ”⁠—Jim returned to himself with an[m
[31m- effort⁠—“about this dyin’, that was all.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But he could not shake off the fright that had startled him. It was as if[m
[31m- an unseen thing of gloom had passed him by, casting upon him the[m
[31m- intangible shadow of its presence. He was aware of a feeling of[m
[31m- foreboding. Something ominous was about to happen. Calamity hovered in the[m
[31m- air. He gazed fixedly across the table at the other man. He could not[m
[31m- understand. Was it that he had blundered and poisoned himself? No, Matt[m
[31m- had the nicked cup, and he had certainly put the poison in the nicked cup.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was all his own imagination, was his next thought. It had played him[m
[31m- tricks before. Fool! Of course it was. Of course something was about to[m
[31m- happen, but it was about to happen to Matt. Had not Matt drunk the whole[m
[31m- cup of coffee?[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim brightened up and finished his steak, sopping bread in the gravy when[m
[31m- the meat was gone.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “When I was a kid⁠—” he began, but broke off abruptly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Again the unseen thing of gloom had fluttered, and his being was vibrant[m
[31m- with premonition of impending misfortune. He felt a disruptive influence[m
[31m- at work in the flesh of him, and in all his muscles there was a seeming[m
[31m- that they were about to begin to twitch. He sat back suddenly, and as[m
[31m- suddenly leaned forward with his elbows on the table. A tremor ran dimly[m
[31m- through the muscles of his body. It was like the first rustling of leaves[m
[31m- before the oncoming of wind. He clenched his teeth. It came again, a[m
[31m- spasmodic tensing of his muscles. He knew panic at the revolt within his[m
[31m- being. His muscles no longer recognized his mastery over them. Again they[m
[31m- spasmodically tensed, despite the will of him, for he had willed that they[m
[31m- should not tense. This was revolution within himself, this was anarchy;[m
[31m- and the terror of impotence rushed up in him as his flesh gripped and[m
[31m- seemed to seize him in a clutch, chills running up and down his back and[m
[31m- sweat starting on his brow. He glanced about the room, and all the details[m
[31m- of it smote him with a strange sense of familiarity. It was as though he[m
[31m- had just returned from a long journey. He looked across the table at his[m
[31m- partner. Matt was watching him and smiling. An expression of horror spread[m
[31m- over Jim’s face.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “My God, Matt!” he screamed. “You ain’t doped me?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt smiled and continued to watch him. In the paroxysm that followed, Jim[m
[31m- did not become unconscious. His muscles tensed and twitched and knotted,[m
[31m- hurting him and crushing him in their savage grip. And in the midst of it[m
[31m- all, it came to him that Matt was acting queerly. He was travelling the[m
[31m- same road. The smile had gone from his face, and there was on it an intent[m
[31m- expression, as if he were listening to some inner tale of himself and[m
[31m- trying to divine the message. Matt got up and walked across the room and[m
[31m- back again, then sat down.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You did this, Jim,” he said quietly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I didn’t think you’d try to fix ME,” Jim answered reproachfully.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh, I fixed you all right,” Matt said, with teeth close together and[m
[31m- shivering body. “What did you give me?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Strychnine.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Same as I gave you,” Matt volunteered. “It’s a hell of a mess, ain’t it?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’re lyin’, Matt,” Jim pleaded. “You ain’t doped me, have you?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I sure did, Jim; an’ I didn’t overdose you, neither. I cooked it in as[m
[31m- neat as you please in your half the porterhouse.⁠—Hold on! Where’re[m
[31m- you goin’?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim had made a dash for the door, and was throwing back the bolts. Matt[m
[31m- sprang in between and shoved him away.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Drug store,” Jim panted. “Drug store.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “No you don’t. You’ll stay right here. There ain’t goin’ to be any runnin’[m
[31m- out an’ makin’ a poison play on the street⁠—not with all them jools[m
[31m- reposin’ under the pillow. Savve? Even if you didn’t die, you’d be in the[m
[31m- hands of the police with a whole lot of explanations comin’. Emetics is[m
[31m- the stuff for poison. I’m just as bad bit as you, an’ I’m goin’ to take a[m
[31m- emetic. That’s all they’d give you at a drug store, anyway.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He thrust Jim back into the middle of the room and shot the bolts into[m
[31m- place. As he went across the floor to the food shelf, he passed one hand[m
[31m- over his brow and flung off the beaded sweat. It spattered audibly on the[m
[31m- floor. Jim watched agonizedly as Matt got the mustard-can and a cup and[m
[31m- ran for the sink. He stirred a cupful of mustard and water and drank it[m
[31m- down. Jim had followed him and was reaching with trembling hands for the[m
[31m- empty cup. Again Matt shoved him away. As he mixed a second cupful, he[m
[31m- demanded⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “D’you think one cup’ll do for me? You can wait till I’m done.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim started to totter toward the door, but Matt checked him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If you monkey with that door, I’ll twist your neck. Savve? You can take[m
[31m- yours when I’m done. An’ if it saves you, I’ll twist your neck, anyway.[m
[31m- You ain’t got no chance, nohow. I told you many times what you’d get if[m
[31m- you did me dirt.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But you did me dirt, too,” Jim articulated with an effort.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt was drinking the second cupful, and did not answer. The sweat had got[m
[31m- into Jim’s eyes, and he could scarcely see his way to the table, where he[m
[31m- got a cup for himself. But Matt was mixing a third cupful, and, as before,[m
[31m- thrust him away.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I told you to wait till I was done,” Matt growled. “Get outa my way.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And Jim supported his twitching body by holding on to the sink, the while[m
[31m- he yearned toward the yellowish concoction that stood for life. It was by[m
[31m- sheer will that he stood and clung to the sink. His flesh strove to double[m
[31m- him up and bring him to the floor. Matt drank the third cupful, and with[m
[31m- difficulty managed to get to a chair and sit down. His first paroxysm was[m
[31m- passing. The spasms that afflicted him were dying away. This good effect[m
[31m- he ascribed to the mustard and water. He was safe, at any rate. He wiped[m
[31m- the sweat from his face, and, in the interval of calm, found room for[m
[31m- curiosity. He looked at his partner.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A spasm had shaken the mustard can out of Jim’s hands, and the contents[m
[31m- were spilled upon the floor. He stooped to scoop some of the mustard into[m
[31m- the cup, and the succeeding spasm doubled him upon the floor. Matt smiled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Stay with it,” he encouraged. “It’s the stuff all right. It’s fixed me[m
[31m- up.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Jim heard him and turned toward him a stricken face, twisted with[m
[31m- suffering and pleading. Spasm now followed spasm till he was in[m
[31m- convulsions, rolling on the floor and yellowing his face and hair in the[m
[31m- mustard.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt laughed hoarsely at the sight, but the laugh broke midway. A tremor[m
[31m- had run through his body. A new paroxysm was beginning. He arose and[m
[31m- staggered across to the sink, where, with probing forefinger, he vainly[m
[31m- strove to assist the action of the emetic. In the end, he clung to the[m
[31m- sink as Jim had clung, filled with the horror of going down to the floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The other’s paroxysm had passed, and he sat up, weak and fainting, too[m
[31m- weak to rise, his forehead dripping, his lips flecked with a foam made[m
[31m- yellow by the mustard in which he had rolled. He rubbed his eyes with his[m
[31m- knuckles, and groans that were like whines came from his throat.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What are you snifflin’ about?” Matt demanded out of his agony. “All you[m
[31m- got to do is die. An’ when you die you’re dead.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I … ain’t … snifflin’ … it’s … the … mustard … stingin’ … my …  eyes,” Jim panted with desperate slowness.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was his last successful attempt at speech. Thereafter he babbled[m
[31m- incoherently, pawing the air with shaking arms till a fresh convulsion[m
[31m- stretched him on the floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Matt struggled back to the chair, and, doubled up on it, with his arms[m
[31m- clasped about his knees, he fought with his disintegrating flesh. He came[m
[31m- out of the convulsion cool and weak. He looked to see how it went with the[m
[31m- other, and saw him lying motionless.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He tried to soliloquize, to be facetious, to have his last grim laugh at[m
[31m- life, but his lips made only incoherent sounds. The thought came to him[m
[31m- that the emetic had failed, and that nothing remained but the drug store.[m
[31m- He looked toward the door and drew himself to his feet. There he saved[m
[31m- himself from falling by clutching the chair. Another paroxysm had begun.[m
[31m- And in the midst of the paroxysm, with his body and all the parts of it[m
[31m- flying apart and writhing and twisting back again into knots, he clung to[m
[31m- the chair and shoved it before him across the floor. The last shreds of[m
[31m- his will were leaving him when he gained the door. He turned the key and[m
[31m- shot back one bolt. He fumbled for the second bolt, but failed. Then he[m
[31m- leaned his weight against the door and slid down gently to the floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0004" name="link2H_4_0004">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- CREATED HE THEM[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<h3>[m
[31m- She met him at the door.[m
[31m- </h3>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I did not think you would be so early.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is half past eight.” He looked at his watch. “The train leaves at[m
[31m- 9.12.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He was very businesslike, until he saw her lips tremble as she abruptly[m
[31m- turned and led the way.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’ll be all right, little woman,” he said soothingly. “Doctor Bodineau’s[m
[31m- the man. He’ll pull him through, you’ll see.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They entered the living-room. His glance quested apprehensively about,[m
[31m- then turned to her.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Where’s Al?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She did not answer, but with a sudden impulse came close to him and stood[m
[31m- motionless. She was a slender, dark-eyed woman, in whose face was stamped[m
[31m- the strain and stress of living. But the fine lines and the haunted look[m
[31m- in the eyes were not the handiwork of mere worry. He knew whose handiwork[m
[31m- it was as he looked upon it, and she knew when she consulted her mirror.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’s no use, Mary,” he said. He put his hand on her shoulder. “We’ve[m
[31m- tried everything. It’s a wretched business, I know, but what else can we[m
[31m- do? You’ve failed. Doctor Bodineau’s all that’s left.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If I had another chance …” she began falteringly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “We’ve threshed that all out,” he answered harshly. “You’ve got to buck[m
[31m- up, now. You know what conclusion we arrived at. You know you haven’t the[m
[31m- ghost of a hope in another chance.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She shook her head. “I know it. But it is terrible, the thought of his[m
[31m- going away to fight it out alone.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He won’t be alone. There’s Doctor Bodineau. And besides, it’s a beautiful[m
[31m- place.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She remained silent.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is the only thing,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is the only thing,” she repeated mechanically.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He looked at his watch. “Where’s Al?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll send him.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- When the door had closed behind her, he walked over to the window and[m
[31m- looked out, drumming absently with his knuckles on the pane.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Hello.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He turned and responded to the greeting of the man who had just entered.[m
[31m- There was a perceptible drag to the man’s feet as he walked across toward[m
[31m- the window and paused irresolutely halfway.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ve changed my mind, George,” he announced hurriedly and nervously. “I’m[m
[31m- not going.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He plucked at his sleeve, shuffled with his feet, dropped his eyes, and[m
[31m- with a strong effort raised them again to confront the other.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George regarded him silently, his nostrils distending and his lean fingers[m
[31m- unconsciously crooking like an eagle’s talons about to clutch.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In line and feature, there was much of resemblance between the two men;[m
[31m- and yet, in the strongest resemblances there was a radical difference.[m
[31m- Theirs were the same black eyes, but those of the man at the window were[m
[31m- sharp and straight looking, while those of the man in the middle of the[m
[31m- room were cloudy and furtive. He could not face the other’s gaze, and[m
[31m- continually and vainly struggled with himself to do so. The high cheek[m
[31m- bones with the hollows beneath were the same, yet the texture of the[m
[31m- hollows seemed different. The thin-lipped mouths were from the same mould,[m
[31m- but George’s lips were firm and muscular, while Al’s were soft and loose⁠—the[m
[31m- lips of an ascetic turned voluptuary. There was also a sag at the corners.[m
[31m- His flesh hinted of grossness, especially so in the eagle-like aquiline[m
[31m- nose that must once have been like the other’s, but that had lost the[m
[31m- austerity the other’s still retained.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Al fought for steadiness in the middle of the floor. The silence bothered[m
[31m- him. He had a feeling that he was about to begin swaying back and forth.[m
[31m- He moistened his lips with his tongue.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m going to stay,” he said desperately.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He dropped his eyes and plucked again at his sleeve.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And you are only twenty-six years old,” George said at last. “You poor,[m
[31m- feeble old man.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t be so sure of that,” Al retorted, with a flash of belligerence.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Do you remember when we swam that mile and a half across the channel?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, and what of it?” A sullen expression was creeping across Al’s face.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And do you remember when we boxed in the barn after school?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I could take all you gave me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All I gave you!” George’s voice rose momentarily to a higher pitch. “You[m
[31m- licked me four afternoons out of five. You were twice as strong as I⁠—three[m
[31m- times as strong. And now I’d be afraid to land on you with a sofa cushion;[m
[31m- you’d crumple up like a last year’s leaf. You’d die, you poor, miserable[m
[31m- old man.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You needn’t abuse me just because I’ve changed my mind,” the other[m
[31m- protested, the hint of a whine in his voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His wife entered, and he looked appealingly to her; but the man at the[m
[31m- window strode suddenly up to him and burst out⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You don’t know your own mind for two successive minutes! You haven’t any[m
[31m- mind, you spineless, crawling worm!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You can’t make me angry.” Al smiled with cunning, and glanced[m
[31m- triumphantly at his wife. “You can’t make me angry,” he repeated, as[m
[31m- though the idea were thoroughly gratifying to him. “I know your game. It’s[m
[31m- my stomach, I tell you. I can’t help it. Before God, I can’t! Isn’t it my[m
[31m- stomach, Mary?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- She glanced at George and spoke composedly, though she hid a trembling[m
[31m- hand in a fold of her skirt.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Isn’t it time?” she asked softly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Her husband turned upon her savagely. “I’m not going to go!” he cried.[m
[31m- “That’s just what I’ve been telling … him. And I tell you again, all of[m
[31m- you, I’m not going. You can’t bully me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why, Al, dear, you said⁠—” she began.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Never mind what I said!” he broke out. “I’ve said something else right[m
[31m- now, and you’ve heard it, and that settles it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He walked across the room and threw himself with emphasis into a Morris[m
[31m- chair. But the other man was swiftly upon him. The talon-like fingers[m
[31m- gripped his shoulders, jerked him to his feet, and held him there.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’ve reached the limit, Al, and I want you to understand it. I’ve tried[m
[31m- to treat you like … like my brother, but hereafter I shall treat you like[m
[31m- the thing that you are. Do you understand?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The anger in his voice was cold. The blaze in his eyes was cold. It was[m
[31m- vastly more effective than any outburst, and Al cringed under it and under[m
[31m- the clutching hand that was bruising his shoulder muscles.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is only because of me that you have this house, that you have the food[m
[31m- you eat. Your position? Any other man would have been shown the door a[m
[31m- year ago⁠—two years ago. I have held you in it. Your salary has been[m
[31m- charity. It has been paid out of my pocket. Mary … her dresses … that[m
[31m- gown she has on is made over; she wears the discarded dresses of her[m
[31m- sisters, of my wife. Charity⁠—do you understand? Your children⁠—they[m
[31m- are wearing the discarded clothes of my children, of the children of my[m
[31m- neighbours who think the clothes went to some orphan asylum. And it is an[m
[31m- orphan asylum … or it soon will be.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He emphasized each point with an unconscious tightening of his grip on the[m
[31m- shoulder. Al was squirming with the pain of it. The sweat was starting out[m
[31m- on his forehead.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Now listen well to me,” his brother went on. “In three minutes you will[m
[31m- tell me that you are going with me. If you don’t, Mary and the children[m
[31m- will be taken away from you⁠—to-day. You needn’t ever come to the[m
[31m- office. This house will be closed to you. And in six months I shall have[m
[31m- the pleasure of burying you. You have three minutes to make up your mind.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Al made a strangling movement, and reached up with weak fingers to the[m
[31m- clutching hand.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “My heart … let me go … you’ll be the death of me,” he gasped.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The hand thrust him down forcibly into the Morris chair and released him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The clock on the mantle ticked loudly. George glanced at it, and at Mary.[m
[31m- She was leaning against the table, unable to conceal her trembling. He[m
[31m- became unpleasantly aware of the feeling of his brother’s fingers on his[m
[31m- hand. Quite unconsciously he wiped the back of the hand upon his coat. The[m
[31m- clock ticked on in the silence. It seemed to George that the room[m
[31m- reverberated with his voice. He could hear himself still speaking.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll go,” came from the Morris chair.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was a weak and shaken voice, and it was a weak and shaken man that[m
[31m- pulled himself out of the Morris chair. He started toward the door.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Where are you going?” George demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Suit case,” came the response. “Mary’ll send the trunk later. I’ll be[m
[31m- back in a minute.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The door closed after him. A moment later, struck with sudden suspicion,[m
[31m- George was opening the door. He glanced in. His brother stood at a[m
[31m- sideboard, in one hand a decanter, in the other hand, bottom up and to his[m
[31m- lips, a whisky glass.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Across the glass Al saw that he was observed. It threw him into a panic.[m
[31m- Hastily he tried to refill the glass and get it to his lips; but glass and[m
[31m- decanter were sent smashing to the floor. He snarled. It was like the[m
[31m- sound of a wild beast. But the grip on his shoulder subdued and frightened[m
[31m- him. He was being propelled toward the door.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The suit case,” he gasped. “It’s there in that room. Let me get it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Where’s the key?” his brother asked, when he had brought it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It isn’t locked.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The next moment the suit case was spread open, and George’s hand was[m
[31m- searching the contents. From one side it brought out a bottle of whisky,[m
[31m- from the other side a flask. He snapped the case to.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Come on,” he said. “If we miss one car, we miss that train.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He went out into the hallway, leaving Al with his wife. It was like a[m
[31m- funeral, George thought, as he waited.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His brother’s overcoat caught on the knob of the front door and delayed[m
[31m- its closing long enough for Mary’s first sob to come to their ears.[m
[31m- George’s lips were very thin and compressed as he went down the steps. In[m
[31m- one hand he carried the suit case. With the other hand he held his[m
[31m- brother’s arm.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As they neared the corner, he heard the electric car a block away, and[m
[31m- urged his brother on. Al was breathing hard. His feet dragged and[m
[31m- shuffled, and he held back.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A hell of a brother YOU are,” he panted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- For reply, he received a vicious jerk on his arm. It reminded him of his[m
[31m- childhood when he was hurried along by some angry grown-up. And like a[m
[31m- child, he had to be helped up the car step. He sank down on an outside[m
[31m- seat, panting, sweating, overcome by the exertion. He followed George’s[m
[31m- eyes as the latter looked him up and down.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A hell of a brother YOU are,” was George’s comment when he had finished[m
[31m- the inspection.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Moisture welled into Al’s eyes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’s my stomach,” he said with self-pity.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I don’t wonder,” was the retort. “Burnt out like the crater of a volcano.[m
[31m- Fervent heat isn’t a circumstance.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Thereafter they did not speak. When they arrived at the transfer point,[m
[31m- George came to himself with a start. He smiled. With fixed gaze that did[m
[31m- not see the houses that streamed across his field of vision, he had[m
[31m- himself been sunk deep in self-pity. He helped his brother from the car,[m
[31m- and looked up the intersecting street. The car they were to take was not[m
[31m- in sight.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Al’s eyes chanced upon the corner grocery and saloon across the way. At[m
[31m- once he became restless. His hands passed beyond his control, and he[m
[31m- yearned hungrily across the street to the door that swung open even as he[m
[31m- looked and let in a happy pilgrim. And in that instant he saw the[m
[31m- white-jacketed bartender against an array of glittering glass. Quite[m
[31m- unconsciously he started to cross the street.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Hold on.” George’s hand was on his arm.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I want some whisky,” he answered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’ve already had some.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That was hours ago. Go on, George, let me have some. It’s the last day.[m
[31m- Don’t shut off on me until we get there⁠—God knows it will be soon[m
[31m- enough.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George glanced desperately up the street. The car was in sight.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There isn’t time for a drink,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I don’t want a drink. I want a bottle.” Al’s voice became wheedling. “Go[m
[31m- on, George. It’s the last, the very last.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “No.” The denial was as final as George’s thin lips could make it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Al glanced at the approaching car. He sat down suddenly on the curbstone.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What’s the matter?” his brother asked, with momentary alarm.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothing. I want some whisky. It’s my stomach.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Come on now, get up.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George reached for him, but was anticipated, for his brother sprawled flat[m
[31m- on the pavement, oblivious to the dirt and to the curious glances of the[m
[31m- passers-by. The car was clanging its gong at the crossing, a block away.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’ll miss it,” Al grinned from the pavement. “And it will be your[m
[31m- fault.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George’s fists clenched tightly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “For two cents I’d give you a thrashing.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And miss the car,” was the triumphant comment from the pavement.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George looked at the car. It was halfway down the block. He looked at his[m
[31m- watch. He debated a second longer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All right,” he said. “I’ll get it. But you get on that car. If you miss[m
[31m- it, I’ll break the bottle over your head.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He dashed across the street and into the saloon. The car came in and[m
[31m- stopped. There were no passengers to get off. Al dragged himself up the[m
[31m- steps and sat down. He smiled as the conductor rang the bell and the car[m
[31m- started. The swinging door of the saloon burst open. Clutching in his hand[m
[31m- the suit case and a pint bottle of whisky, George started in pursuit. The[m
[31m- conductor, his hand on the bell cord, waited to see if it would be[m
[31m- necessary to stop. It was not. George swung lightly aboard, sat down[m
[31m- beside his brother, and passed him the bottle.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You might have got a quart,” Al said reproachfully.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He extracted the cork with a pocket corkscrew, and elevated the bottle.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m sick … my stomach,” he explained in apologetic tones to the[m
[31m- passenger who sat next to him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the train they sat in the smoking-car. George felt that it was[m
[31m- imperative. Also, having successfully caught the train, his heart[m
[31m- softened. He felt more kindly toward his brother, and accused himself of[m
[31m- unnecessary harshness. He strove to atone by talking about their mother,[m
[31m- and sisters, and the little affairs and interests of the family. But Al[m
[31m- was morose, and devoted himself to the bottle. As the time passed, his[m
[31m- mouth hung looser and looser, while the rings under his eyes seemed to[m
[31m- puff out and all his facial muscles to relax.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’s my stomach,” he said, once, when he finished the bottle and dropped[m
[31m- it under the seat; but the swift hardening of his brother’s face did not[m
[31m- encourage further explanations.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The conveyance that met them at the station had all the dignity and[m
[31m- luxuriousness of a private carriage. George’s eyes were keen for the ear[m
[31m- marks of the institution to which they were going, but his apprehensions[m
[31m- were allayed from moment to moment. As they entered the wide gateway and[m
[31m- rolled on through the spacious grounds, he felt sure that the[m
[31m- institutional side of the place would not jar upon his brother. It was[m
[31m- more like a summer hotel, or, better yet, a country club. And as they[m
[31m- swept on through the spring sunshine, the songs of birds in his ears, and[m
[31m- in his nostrils the breath of flowers, George sighed for a week of rest in[m
[31m- such a place, and before his eyes loomed the arid vista of summer in town[m
[31m- and at the office. There was not room in his income for his brother and[m
[31m- himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Let us take a walk in the grounds,” he suggested, after they had met[m
[31m- Doctor Bodineau and inspected the quarters assigned to Al. “The carriage[m
[31m- leaves for the station in half an hour, and we’ll just have time.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’s beautiful,” he remarked a moment later. Under his feet was the[m
[31m- velvet grass, the trees arched overhead, and he stood in mottled sunshine.[m
[31m- “I wish I could stay for a month.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll trade places with you,” Al said quickly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George laughed it off, but he felt a sinking of the heart.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Look at that oak!” he cried. “And that woodpecker! Isn’t he a beauty!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I don’t like it here,” he heard his brother mutter.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George’s lips tightened in preparation for the struggle, but he said⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m going to send Mary and the children off to the mountains. She needs[m
[31m- it, and so do they. And when you’re in shape, I’ll send you right on to[m
[31m- join them. Then you can take your summer vacation before you come back to[m
[31m- the office.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m not going to stay in this damned hole, for all you talk about it,” Al[m
[31m- announced abruptly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes you are, and you’re going to get your health and strength back again,[m
[31m- so that the look of you will put the colour in Mary’s cheeks where it used[m
[31m- to be.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m going back with you.” Al’s voice was firm. “I’m going to take the[m
[31m- same train back. It’s about time for that carriage, I guess.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I haven’t told you all my plans,” George tried to go on, but Al cut him[m
[31m- off.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You might as well quit that. I don’t want any of your soapy talking. You[m
[31m- treat me like a child. I’m not a child. My mind’s made up, and I’ll show[m
[31m- you how long it can stay made up. You needn’t talk to me. I don’t care a[m
[31m- rap for what you’re going to say.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A baleful light was in his eyes, and to his brother he seemed for all the[m
[31m- world like a cornered rat, desperate and ready to fight. As George looked[m
[31m- at him he remembered back to their childhood, and it came to him that at[m
[31m- last was aroused in Al the same old stubborn strain that had enabled him,[m
[31m- as a child, to stand against all force and persuasion.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George abandoned hope. He had lost. This creature was not human. The last[m
[31m- fine instinct of the human had fled. It was a brute, sluggish and stolid,[m
[31m- impossible to move⁠—just the raw stuff of life, combative,[m
[31m- rebellious, and indomitable. And as he contemplated his brother he felt in[m
[31m- himself the rising up of a similar brute. He became suddenly aware that[m
[31m- his fingers were tensing and crooking like a thug’s, and he knew the[m
[31m- desire to kill. And his reason, turned traitor at last, counselled that he[m
[31m- should kill, that it was the only thing left for him to do.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He was aroused by a servant calling to him through the trees that the[m
[31m- carriage was waiting. He answered. Then, looking straight before him, he[m
[31m- discovered his brother. He had forgotten it was his brother. It had been[m
[31m- only a thing the moment before. He began to talk, and as he talked the way[m
[31m- became clear to him. His reason had not turned traitor. The brute in him[m
[31m- had merely orientated his reason.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You are no earthly good, Al,” he said. “You know that. You’ve made Mary’s[m
[31m- life a hell. You are a curse to your children. And you have not made life[m
[31m- exactly a paradise for the rest of us.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There’s no use your talking,” Al interjected. “I’m not going to stay[m
[31m- here.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That’s what I’m coming to,” George continued. “You don’t have to stay[m
[31m- here.” (Al’s face brightened, and he involuntarily made a movement, as[m
[31m- though about to start toward the carriage.) “On the other hand, it is not[m
[31m- necessary that you should return with me. There is another way.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George’s hand went to his hip pocket and appeared with a revolver. It lay[m
[31m- along his palm, the butt toward Al, and toward Al he extended it. At the[m
[31m- same time, with his head, he indicated the near-by thicket.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You can’t bluff me,” Al snarled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is not a bluff, Al. Look at me. I mean it. And if you don’t do it for[m
[31m- yourself, I shall have to do it for you.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They faced each other, the proffered revolver still extended. Al debated[m
[31m- for a moment, then his eyes blazed. With a quick movement he seized the[m
[31m- revolver.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “My God! I’ll do it,” he said. “I’ll show you what I’ve got in me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George felt suddenly sick. He turned away. He did not see his brother[m
[31m- enter the thicket, but he heard the passage of his body through the leaves[m
[31m- and branches.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Good-bye, Al,” he called.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Good-bye,” came from the thicket.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George felt the sweat upon his forehead. He began mopping his face with[m
[31m- his handkerchief. He heard, as from a remote distance, the voice of the[m
[31m- servant again calling to him that the carriage was waiting. The woodpecker[m
[31m- dropped down through the mottled sunshine and lighted on the trunk of a[m
[31m- tree a dozen feet away. George felt that it was all a dream, and yet[m
[31m- through it all he felt supreme justification. It was the right thing to[m
[31m- do. It was the only thing.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His whole body gave a spasmodic start, as though the revolver had been[m
[31m- fired. It was the voice of Al, close at his back.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Here’s your gun,” Al said. “I’ll stay.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The servant appeared among the trees, approaching rapidly and calling[m
[31m- anxiously. George put the weapon in his pocket and caught both his[m
[31m- brother’s hands in his own.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “God bless you, old man,” he murmured; “and”⁠—with a final squeeze of[m
[31m- the hands⁠—“good luck!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m coming,” he called to the servant, and turned and ran through the[m
[31m- trees toward the carriage.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0005" name="link2H_4_0005">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- THE CHINAGO[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- “The coral waxes, the palm grows, but man departs.”⁠—Tahitian proverb.[m
[31m-</pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho did not understand French. He sat in the crowded court room, very[m
[31m- weary and bored, listening to the unceasing, explosive French that now one[m
[31m- official and now another uttered. It was just so much gabble to Ah Cho,[m
[31m- and he marvelled at the stupidity of the Frenchmen who took so long to[m
[31m- find out the murderer of Chung Ga, and who did not find him at all. The[m
[31m- five hundred coolies on the plantation knew that Ah San had done the[m
[31m- killing, and here was Ah San not even arrested. It was true that all the[m
[31m- coolies had agreed secretly not to testify against one another; but then,[m
[31m- it was so simple, the Frenchmen should have been able to discover that Ah[m
[31m- San was the man. They were very stupid, these Frenchmen.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho had done nothing of which to be afraid. He had had no hand in the[m
[31m- killing. It was true he had been present at it, and Schemmer, the overseer[m
[31m- on the plantation, had rushed into the barracks immediately afterward and[m
[31m- caught him there, along with four or five others; but what of that? Chung[m
[31m- Ga had been stabbed only twice. It stood to reason that five or six men[m
[31m- could not inflict two stab wounds. At the most, if a man had struck but[m
[31m- once, only two men could have done it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- So it was that Ah Cho reasoned, when he, along with his four companions,[m
[31m- had lied and blocked and obfuscated in their statements to the court[m
[31m- concerning what had taken place. They had heard the sounds of the killing,[m
[31m- and, like Schemmer, they had run to the spot. They had got there before[m
[31m- Schemmer⁠—that was all. True, Schemmer had testified that, attracted[m
[31m- by the sound of quarrelling as he chanced to pass by, he had stood for at[m
[31m- least five minutes outside; that then, when he entered, he found the[m
[31m- prisoners already inside; and that they had not entered just before,[m
[31m- because he had been standing by the one door to the barracks. But what of[m
[31m- that? Ah Cho and his four fellow-prisoners had testified that Schemmer was[m
[31m- mistaken. In the end they would be let go. They were all confident of[m
[31m- that. Five men could not have their heads cut off for two stab wounds.[m
[31m- Besides, no foreign devil had seen the killing. But these Frenchmen were[m
[31m- so stupid. In China, as Ah Cho well knew, the magistrate would order all[m
[31m- of them to the torture and learn the truth. The truth was very easy to[m
[31m- learn under torture. But these Frenchmen did not torture⁠—bigger[m
[31m- fools they! Therefore they would never find out who killed Chung Ga.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But Ah Cho did not understand everything. The English Company that owned[m
[31m- the plantation had imported into Tahiti, at great expense, the five[m
[31m- hundred coolies. The stockholders were clamouring for dividends, and the[m
[31m- Company had not yet paid any; wherefore the Company did not want its[m
[31m- costly contract labourers to start the practice of killing one another.[m
[31m- Also, there were the French, eager and willing to impose upon the Chinagos[m
[31m- the virtues and excellences of French law. There was nothing like setting[m
[31m- an example once in a while; and, besides, of what use was New Caledonia[m
[31m- except to send men to live out their days in misery and pain in payment of[m
[31m- the penalty for being frail and human?[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho did not understand all this. He sat in the court room and waited[m
[31m- for the baffled judgment that would set him and his comrades free to go[m
[31m- back to the plantation and work out the terms of their contracts. This[m
[31m- judgment would soon be rendered. Proceedings were drawing to a close. He[m
[31m- could see that. There was no more testifying, no more gabble of tongues.[m
[31m- The French devils were tired, too, and evidently waiting for the judgment.[m
[31m- And as he waited he remembered back in his life to the time when he had[m
[31m- signed the contract and set sail in the ship for Tahiti. Times had been[m
[31m- hard in his sea-coast village, and when he indentured himself to labour[m
[31m- for five years in the South Seas at fifty cents Mexican a day, he had[m
[31m- thought himself fortunate. There were men in his village who toiled a[m
[31m- whole year for ten dollars Mexican, and there were women who made nets all[m
[31m- the year round for five dollars, while in the houses of shopkeepers there[m
[31m- were maidservants who received four dollars for a year of service. And[m
[31m- here he was to receive fifty cents a day; for one day, only one day, he[m
[31m- was to receive that princely sum! What if the work were hard? At the end[m
[31m- of the five years he would return home⁠—that was in the contract⁠—and[m
[31m- he would never have to work again. He would be a rich man for life, with a[m
[31m- house of his own, a wife, and children growing up to venerate him. Yes,[m
[31m- and back of the house he would have a small garden, a place of meditation[m
[31m- and repose, with goldfish in a tiny lakelet, and wind bells tinkling in[m
[31m- the several trees, and there would be a high wall all around so that his[m
[31m- meditation and repose should be undisturbed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Well, he had worked out three of those five years. He was already a[m
[31m- wealthy man (in his own country) through his earnings, and only two years[m
[31m- more intervened between the cotton plantation on Tahiti and the meditation[m
[31m- and repose that awaited him. But just now he was losing money because of[m
[31m- the unfortunate accident of being present at the killing of Chung Ga. He[m
[31m- had lain three weeks in prison, and for each day of those three weeks he[m
[31m- had lost fifty cents. But now judgment would soon be given, and he would[m
[31m- go back to work.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho was twenty-two years old. He was happy and good-natured, and it was[m
[31m- easy for him to smile. While his body was slim in the Asiatic way, his[m
[31m- face was rotund. It was round, like the moon, and it irradiated a gentle[m
[31m- complacence and a sweet kindliness of spirit that was unusual among his[m
[31m- countrymen. Nor did his looks belie him. He never caused trouble, never[m
[31m- took part in wrangling. He did not gamble. His soul was not harsh enough[m
[31m- for the soul that must belong to a gambler. He was content with little[m
[31m- things and simple pleasures. The hush and quiet in the cool of the day[m
[31m- after the blazing toil in the cotton field was to him an infinite[m
[31m- satisfaction. He could sit for hours gazing at a solitary flower and[m
[31m- philosophizing about the mysteries and riddles of being. A blue heron on a[m
[31m- tiny crescent of sandy beach, a silvery splatter of flying fish, or a[m
[31m- sunset of pearl and rose across the lagoon, could entrance him to all[m
[31m- forgetfulness of the procession of wearisome days and of the heavy lash of[m
[31m- Schemmer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Schemmer, Karl Schemmer, was a brute, a brutish brute. But he earned his[m
[31m- salary. He got the last particle of strength out of the five hundred[m
[31m- slaves; for slaves they were until their term of years was up. Schemmer[m
[31m- worked hard to extract the strength from those five hundred sweating[m
[31m- bodies and to transmute it into bales of fluffy cotton ready for export.[m
[31m- His dominant, iron-clad, primeval brutishness was what enabled him to[m
[31m- effect the transmutation. Also, he was assisted by a thick leather belt,[m
[31m- three inches wide and a yard in length, with which he always rode and[m
[31m- which, on occasion, could come down on the naked back of a stooping coolie[m
[31m- with a report like a pistol-shot. These reports were frequent when[m
[31m- Schemmer rode down the furrowed field.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Once, at the beginning of the first year of contract labour, he had killed[m
[31m- a coolie with a single blow of his fist. He had not exactly crushed the[m
[31m- man’s head like an egg-shell, but the blow had been sufficient to addle[m
[31m- what was inside, and, after being sick for a week, the man had died. But[m
[31m- the Chinese had not complained to the French devils that ruled over[m
[31m- Tahiti. It was their own look out. Schemmer was their problem. They must[m
[31m- avoid his wrath as they avoided the venom of the centipedes that lurked in[m
[31m- the grass or crept into the sleeping quarters on rainy nights. The[m
[31m- Chinagos⁠—such they were called by the indolent, brown-skinned island[m
[31m- folk⁠—saw to it that they did not displease Schemmer too greatly.[m
[31m- This was equivalent to rendering up to him a full measure of efficient[m
[31m- toil. That blow of Schemmer’s fist had been worth thousands of dollars to[m
[31m- the Company, and no trouble ever came of it to Schemmer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The French, with no instinct for colonization, futile in their childish[m
[31m- playgame of developing the resources of the island, were only too glad to[m
[31m- see the English Company succeed. What matter of Schemmer and his[m
[31m- redoubtable fist? The Chinago that died? Well, he was only a Chinago.[m
[31m- Besides, he died of sunstroke, as the doctor’s certificate attested. True,[m
[31m- in all the history of Tahiti no one had ever died of sunstroke. But it was[m
[31m- that, precisely that, which made the death of this Chinago unique. The[m
[31m- doctor said as much in his report. He was very candid. Dividends must be[m
[31m- paid, or else one more failure would be added to the long history of[m
[31m- failure in Tahiti.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There was no understanding these white devils. Ah Cho pondered their[m
[31m- inscrutableness as he sat in the court room waiting the judgment. There[m
[31m- was no telling what went on at the back of their minds. He had seen a few[m
[31m- of the white devils. They were all alike⁠—the officers and sailors on[m
[31m- the ship, the French officials, the several white men on the plantation,[m
[31m- including Schemmer. Their minds all moved in mysterious ways there was no[m
[31m- getting at. They grew angry without apparent cause, and their anger was[m
[31m- always dangerous. They were like wild beasts at such times. They worried[m
[31m- about little things, and on occasion could out-toil even a Chinago. They[m
[31m- were not temperate as Chinagos were temperate; they were gluttons, eating[m
[31m- prodigiously and drinking more prodigiously. A Chinago never knew when an[m
[31m- act would please them or arouse a storm of wrath. A Chinago could never[m
[31m- tell. What pleased one time, the very next time might provoke an outburst[m
[31m- of anger. There was a curtain behind the eyes of the white devils that[m
[31m- screened the backs of their minds from the Chinago’s gaze. And then, on[m
[31m- top of it all, was that terrible efficiency of the white devils, that[m
[31m- ability to do things, to make things go, to work results, to bend to their[m
[31m- wills all creeping, crawling things, and the powers of the very elements[m
[31m- themselves. Yes, the white men were strange and wonderful, and they were[m
[31m- devils. Look at Schemmer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho wondered why the judgment was so long in forming. Not a man on[m
[31m- trial had laid hand on Chung Ga. Ah San alone had killed him. Ah San had[m
[31m- done it, bending Chung Ga’s head back with one hand by a grip of his[m
[31m- queue, and with the other hand, from behind, reaching over and driving the[m
[31m- knife into his body. Twice had he driven it in. There in the court room,[m
[31m- with closed eyes, Ah Cho saw the killing acted over again⁠—the[m
[31m- squabble, the vile words bandied back and forth, the filth and insult[m
[31m- flung upon venerable ancestors, the curses laid upon unbegotten[m
[31m- generations, the leap of Ah San, the grip on the queue of Chung Ga, the[m
[31m- knife that sank twice into his flesh, the bursting open of the door, the[m
[31m- irruption of Schemmer, the dash for the door, the escape of Ah San, the[m
[31m- flying belt of Schemmer that drove the rest into the corner, and the[m
[31m- firing of the revolver as a signal that brought help to Schemmer. Ah Cho[m
[31m- shivered as he lived it over. One blow of the belt had bruised his cheek,[m
[31m- taking off some of the skin. Schemmer had pointed to the bruises when, on[m
[31m- the witness-stand, he had identified Ah Cho. It was only just now that the[m
[31m- marks had become no longer visible. That had been a blow. Half an inch[m
[31m- nearer the centre and it would have taken out his eye. Then Ah Cho forgot[m
[31m- the whole happening in a vision he caught of the garden of meditation and[m
[31m- repose that would be his when he returned to his own land.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He sat with impassive face, while the magistrate rendered the judgment.[m
[31m- Likewise were the faces of his four companions impassive. And they[m
[31m- remained impassive when the interpreter explained that the five of them[m
[31m- had been found guilty of the murder of Chung Ga, and that Ah Chow should[m
[31m- have his head cut off, Ah Cho serve twenty years in prison in New[m
[31m- Caledonia, Wong Li twelve years, and Ah Tong ten years. There was no use[m
[31m- in getting excited about it. Even Ah Chow remained expressionless as a[m
[31m- mummy, though it was his head that was to be cut off. The magistrate added[m
[31m- a few words, and the interpreter explained that Ah Chow’s face having been[m
[31m- most severely bruised by Schemmer’s strap had made his identification so[m
[31m- positive that, since one man must die, he might as well be that man. Also,[m
[31m- the fact that Ah Cho’s face likewise had been severely bruised,[m
[31m- conclusively proving his presence at the murder and his undoubted[m
[31m- participation, had merited him the twenty years of penal servitude. And[m
[31m- down to the ten years of Ah Tong, the proportioned reason for each[m
[31m- sentence was explained. Let the Chinagos take the lesson to heart, the[m
[31m- Court said finally, for they must learn that the law would be fulfilled in[m
[31m- Tahiti though the heavens fell.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The five Chinagos were taken back to jail. They were not shocked nor[m
[31m- grieved. The sentences being unexpected was quite what they were[m
[31m- accustomed to in their dealings with the white devils. From them a Chinago[m
[31m- rarely expected more than the unexpected. The heavy punishment for a crime[m
[31m- they had not committed was no stranger than the countless strange things[m
[31m- that white devils did. In the weeks that followed, Ah Cho often[m
[31m- contemplated Ah Chow with mild curiosity. His head was to be cut off by[m
[31m- the guillotine that was being erected on the plantation. For him there[m
[31m- would be no declining years, no gardens of tranquillity. Ah Cho[m
[31m- philosophized and speculated about life and death. As for himself, he was[m
[31m- not perturbed. Twenty years were merely twenty years. By that much was his[m
[31m- garden removed from him⁠—that was all. He was young, and the patience[m
[31m- of Asia was in his bones. He could wait those twenty years, and by that[m
[31m- time the heats of his blood would be assuaged and he would be better[m
[31m- fitted for that garden of calm delight. He thought of a name for it; he[m
[31m- would call it The Garden of the Morning Calm. He was made happy all day by[m
[31m- the thought, and he was inspired to devise a moral maxim on the virtue of[m
[31m- patience, which maxim proved a great comfort, especially to Wong Li and Ah[m
[31m- Tong. Ah Chow, however, did not care for the maxim. His head was to be[m
[31m- separated from his body in so short a time that he had no need for[m
[31m- patience to wait for that event. He smoked well, ate well, slept well, and[m
[31m- did not worry about the slow passage of time.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Cruchot was a gendarme. He had seen twenty years of service in the[m
[31m- colonies, from Nigeria and Senegal to the South Seas, and those twenty[m
[31m- years had not perceptibly brightened his dull mind. He was as slow-witted[m
[31m- and stupid as in his peasant days in the south of France. He knew[m
[31m- discipline and fear of authority, and from God down to the sergeant of[m
[31m- gendarmes the only difference to him was the measure of slavish obedience[m
[31m- which he rendered. In point of fact, the sergeant bulked bigger in his[m
[31m- mind than God, except on Sundays when God’s mouthpieces had their say. God[m
[31m- was usually very remote, while the sergeant was ordinarily very close at[m
[31m- hand.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Cruchot it was who received the order from the Chief Justice to the jailer[m
[31m- commanding that functionary to deliver over to Cruchot the person of Ah[m
[31m- Chow. Now, it happened that the Chief Justice had given a dinner the night[m
[31m- before to the captain and officers of the French man-of-war. His hand was[m
[31m- shaking when he wrote out the order, and his eyes were aching so[m
[31m- dreadfully that he did not read over the order. It was only a Chinago’s[m
[31m- life he was signing away, anyway. So he did not notice that he had omitted[m
[31m- the final letter in Ah Chow’s name. The order read “Ah Cho,” and, when[m
[31m- Cruchot presented the order, the jailer turned over to him the person of[m
[31m- Ah Cho. Cruchot took that person beside him on the seat of a wagon, behind[m
[31m- two mules, and drove away.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho was glad to be out in the sunshine. He sat beside the gendarme and[m
[31m- beamed. He beamed more ardently than ever when he noted the mules headed[m
[31m- south toward Atimaono. Undoubtedly Schemmer had sent for him to be brought[m
[31m- back. Schemmer wanted him to work. Very well, he would work well. Schemmer[m
[31m- would never have cause to complain. It was a hot day. There had been a[m
[31m- stoppage of the trades. The mules sweated, Cruchot sweated, and Ah Cho[m
[31m- sweated. But it was Ah Cho that bore the heat with the least concern. He[m
[31m- had toiled three years under that sun on the plantation. He beamed and[m
[31m- beamed with such genial good nature that even Cruchot’s heavy mind was[m
[31m- stirred to wonderment.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You are very funny,” he said at last.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho nodded and beamed more ardently. Unlike the magistrate, Cruchot[m
[31m- spoke to him in the Kanaka tongue, and this, like all Chinagos and all[m
[31m- foreign devils, Ah Cho understood.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You laugh too much,” Cruchot chided. “One’s heart should be full of tears[m
[31m- on a day like this.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I am glad to get out of the jail.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Is that all?” The gendarme shrugged his shoulders.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Is it not enough?” was the retort.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then you are not glad to have your head cut off?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho looked at him in abrupt perplexity, and said⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why, I am going back to Atimaono to work on the plantation for Schemmer.[m
[31m- Are you not taking me to Atimaono?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Cruchot stroked his long moustaches reflectively. “Well, well,” he said[m
[31m- finally, with a flick of the whip at the off mule, “so you don’t know?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Know what?” Ah Cho was beginning to feel a vague alarm. “Won’t Schemmer[m
[31m- let me work for him any more?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Not after to-day.” Cruchot laughed heartily. It was a good joke. “You[m
[31m- see, you won’t be able to work after to-day. A man with his head off can’t[m
[31m- work, eh?” He poked the Chinago in the ribs, and chuckled.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho maintained silence while the mules trotted a hot mile. Then he[m
[31m- spoke: “Is Schemmer going to cut off my head?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Cruchot grinned as he nodded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is a mistake,” said Ah Cho, gravely. “I am not the Chinago that is to[m
[31m- have his head cut off. I am Ah Cho. The honourable judge has determined[m
[31m- that I am to stop twenty years in New Caledonia.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The gendarme laughed. It was a good joke, this funny Chinago trying to[m
[31m- cheat the guillotine. The mules trotted through a coconut grove and for[m
[31m- half a mile beside the sparkling sea before Ah Cho spoke again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I tell you I am not Ah Chow. The honourable judge did not say that my[m
[31m- head was to go off.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t be afraid,” said Cruchot, with the philanthropic intention of[m
[31m- making it easier for his prisoner. “It is not difficult to die that way.”[m
[31m- He snapped his fingers. “It is quick⁠—like that. It is not like[m
[31m- hanging on the end of a rope and kicking and making faces for five[m
[31m- minutes. It is like killing a chicken with a hatchet. You cut its head[m
[31m- off, that is all. And it is the same with a man. Pouf!⁠—it is over.[m
[31m- It doesn’t hurt. You don’t even think it hurts. You don’t think. Your head[m
[31m- is gone, so you cannot think. It is very good. That is the way I want to[m
[31m- die⁠—quick, ah, quick. You are lucky to die that way. You might get[m
[31m- the leprosy and fall to pieces slowly, a finger at a time, and now and[m
[31m- again a thumb, also the toes. I knew a man who was burned by hot water. It[m
[31m- took him two days to die. You could hear him yelling a kilometre away. But[m
[31m- you? Ah! so easy! Chck!⁠—the knife cuts your neck like that. It is[m
[31m- finished. The knife may even tickle. Who can say? Nobody who died that way[m
[31m- ever came back to say.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He considered this last an excruciating joke, and permitted himself to be[m
[31m- convulsed with laughter for half a minute. Part of his mirth was assumed,[m
[31m- but he considered it his humane duty to cheer up the Chinago.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I tell you I am Ah Cho,” the other persisted. “I don’t want my head[m
[31m- cut off.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Cruchot scowled. The Chinago was carrying the foolishness too far.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I am not Ah Chow⁠—” Ah Cho began.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “That will do,” the gendarme interrupted. He puffed up his cheeks and[m
[31m- strove to appear fierce.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I tell you I am not⁠—” Ah Cho began again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Shut up!” bawled Cruchot.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- After that they rode along in silence. It was twenty miles from Papeete to[m
[31m- Atimaono, and over half the distance was covered by the time the Chinago[m
[31m- again ventured into speech.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I saw you in the court room, when the honourable judge sought after our[m
[31m- guilt,” he began. “Very good. And do you remember that Ah Chow, whose head[m
[31m- is to be cut off⁠—do you remember that he⁠—Ah Chow⁠—was a[m
[31m- tall man? Look at me.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He stood up suddenly, and Cruchot saw that he was a short man. And just as[m
[31m- suddenly Cruchot caught a glimpse of a memory picture of Ah Chow, and in[m
[31m- that picture Ah Chow was tall. To the gendarme all Chinagos looked alike.[m
[31m- One face was like another. But between tallness and shortness he could[m
[31m- differentiate, and he knew that he had the wrong man beside him on the[m
[31m- seat. He pulled up the mules abruptly, so that the pole shot ahead of[m
[31m- them, elevating their collars.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You see, it was a mistake,” said Ah Cho, smiling pleasantly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But Cruchot was thinking. Already he regretted that he had stopped the[m
[31m- wagon. He was unaware of the error of the Chief Justice, and he had no way[m
[31m- of working it out; but he did know that he had been given this Chinago to[m
[31m- take to Atimaono and that it was his duty to take him to Atimaono. What if[m
[31m- he was the wrong man and they cut his head off? It was only a Chinago when[m
[31m- all was said, and what was a Chinago, anyway? Besides, it might not be a[m
[31m- mistake. He did not know what went on in the minds of his superiors. They[m
[31m- knew their business best. Who was he to do their thinking for them? Once,[m
[31m- in the long ago, he had attempted to think for them, and the sergeant had[m
[31m- said: “Cruchot, you are a fool! The quicker you know that, the better you[m
[31m- will get on. You are not to think; you are to obey and leave thinking to[m
[31m- your betters.” He smarted under the recollection. Also, if he turned back[m
[31m- to Papeete, he would delay the execution at Atimaono, and if he were wrong[m
[31m- in turning back, he would get a reprimand from the sergeant who was[m
[31m- waiting for the prisoner. And, furthermore, he would get a reprimand at[m
[31m- Papeete as well.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He touched the mules with the whip and drove on. He looked at his watch.[m
[31m- He would be half an hour late as it was, and the sergeant was bound to be[m
[31m- angry. He put the mules into a faster trot. The more Ah Cho persisted in[m
[31m- explaining the mistake, the more stubborn Cruchot became. The knowledge[m
[31m- that he had the wrong man did not make his temper better. The knowledge[m
[31m- that it was through no mistake of his confirmed him in the belief that the[m
[31m- wrong he was doing was the right. And, rather than incur the displeasure[m
[31m- of the sergeant, he would willingly have assisted a dozen wrong Chinagos[m
[31m- to their doom.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As for Ah Cho, after the gendarme had struck him over the head with the[m
[31m- butt of the whip and commanded him in a loud voice to shut up, there[m
[31m- remained nothing for him to do but to shut up. The long ride continued in[m
[31m- silence. Ah Cho pondered the strange ways of the foreign devils. There was[m
[31m- no explaining them. What they were doing with him was of a piece with[m
[31m- everything they did. First they found guilty five innocent men, and next[m
[31m- they cut off the head of the man that even they, in their benighted[m
[31m- ignorance, had deemed meritorious of no more than twenty years’[m
[31m- imprisonment. And there was nothing he could do. He could only sit idly[m
[31m- and take what these lords of life measured out to him. Once, he got in a[m
[31m- panic, and the sweat upon his body turned cold; but he fought his way out[m
[31m- of it. He endeavoured to resign himself to his fate by remembering and[m
[31m- repeating certain passages from the “Yin Chih Wen” (“The Tract of the[m
[31m- Quiet Way”); but, instead, he kept seeing his dream-garden of meditation[m
[31m- and repose. This bothered him, until he abandoned himself to the dream and[m
[31m- sat in his garden listening to the tinkling of the windbells in the[m
[31m- several trees. And lo! sitting thus, in the dream, he was able to remember[m
[31m- and repeat the passages from “The Tract of the Quiet Way.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- So the time passed nicely until Atimaono was reached and the mules trotted[m
[31m- up to the foot of the scaffold, in the shade of which stood the impatient[m
[31m- sergeant. Ah Cho was hurried up the ladder of the scaffold. Beneath him on[m
[31m- one side he saw assembled all the coolies of the plantation. Schemmer had[m
[31m- decided that the event would be a good object-lesson, and so he called in[m
[31m- the coolies from the fields and compelled them to be present. As they[m
[31m- caught sight of Ah Cho they gabbled among themselves in low voices. They[m
[31m- saw the mistake; but they kept it to themselves. The inexplicable white[m
[31m- devils had doubtlessly changed their minds. Instead of taking the life of[m
[31m- one innocent man, they were taking the life of another innocent man. Ah[m
[31m- Chow or Ah Cho⁠—what did it matter which? They could never understand[m
[31m- the white dogs any more than could the white dogs understand them. Ah Cho[m
[31m- was going to have his head cut off, but they, when their two remaining[m
[31m- years of servitude were up, were going back to China.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Schemmer had made the guillotine himself. He was a handy man, and though[m
[31m- he had never seen a guillotine, the French officials had explained the[m
[31m- principle to him. It was on his suggestion that they had ordered the[m
[31m- execution to take place at Atimaono instead of at Papeete. The scene of[m
[31m- the crime, Schemmer had argued, was the best possible place for the[m
[31m- punishment, and, in addition, it would have a salutary influence upon the[m
[31m- half-thousand Chinagos on the plantation. Schemmer had also volunteered to[m
[31m- act as executioner, and in that capacity he was now on the scaffold,[m
[31m- experimenting with the instrument he had made. A banana tree, of the size[m
[31m- and consistency of a man’s neck, lay under the guillotine. Ah Cho watched[m
[31m- with fascinated eyes. The German, turning a small crank, hoisted the blade[m
[31m- to the top of the little derrick he had rigged. A jerk on a stout piece of[m
[31m- cord loosed the blade and it dropped with a flash, neatly severing the[m
[31m- banana trunk.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How does it work?” The sergeant, coming out on top the scaffold, had[m
[31m- asked the question.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Beautifully,” was Schemmer’s exultant answer. “Let me show you.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Again he turned the crank that hoisted the blade, jerked the cord, and[m
[31m- sent the blade crashing down on the soft tree. But this time it went no[m
[31m- more than two-thirds of the way through.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The sergeant scowled. “That will not serve,” he said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Schemmer wiped the sweat from his forehead. “What it needs is more[m
[31m- weight,” he announced. Walking up to the edge of the scaffold, he called[m
[31m- his orders to the blacksmith for a twenty-five-pound piece of iron. As he[m
[31m- stooped over to attach the iron to the broad top of the blade, Ah Cho[m
[31m- glanced at the sergeant and saw his opportunity.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The honourable judge said that Ah Chow was to have his head cut off,” he[m
[31m- began.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The sergeant nodded impatiently. He was thinking of the fifteen-mile ride[m
[31m- before him that afternoon, to the windward side of the island, and of[m
[31m- Berthe, the pretty half-caste daughter of Lafiere, the pearl-trader, who[m
[31m- was waiting for him at the end of it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, I am not Ah Chow. I am Ah Cho. The honourable jailer has made a[m
[31m- mistake. Ah Chow is a tall man, and you see I am short.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The sergeant looked at him hastily and saw the mistake. “Schemmer!” he[m
[31m- called, imperatively. “Come here.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The German grunted, but remained bent over his task till the chunk of iron[m
[31m- was lashed to his satisfaction. “Is your Chinago ready?” he demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Look at him,” was the answer. “Is he the Chinago?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Schemmer was surprised. He swore tersely for a few seconds, and looked[m
[31m- regretfully across at the thing he had made with his own hands and which[m
[31m- he was eager to see work. “Look here,” he said finally, “we can’t postpone[m
[31m- this affair. I’ve lost three hours’ work already out of those five hundred[m
[31m- Chinagos. I can’t afford to lose it all over again for the right man.[m
[31m- Let’s put the performance through just the same. It is only a Chinago.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The sergeant remembered the long ride before him, and the pearl-trader’s[m
[31m- daughter, and debated with himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They will blame it on Cruchot⁠—if it is discovered,” the German[m
[31m- urged. “But there’s little chance of its being discovered. Ah Chow won’t[m
[31m- give it away, at any rate.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The blame won’t lie with Cruchot, anyway,” the sergeant said. “It must[m
[31m- have been the jailer’s mistake.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then let’s go on with it. They can’t blame us. Who can tell one Chinago[m
[31m- from another? We can say that we merely carried out instructions with the[m
[31m- Chinago that was turned over to us. Besides, I really can’t take all those[m
[31m- coolies a second time away from their labour.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They spoke in French, and Ah Cho, who did not understand a word of it,[m
[31m- nevertheless knew that they were determining his destiny. He knew, also,[m
[31m- that the decision rested with the sergeant, and he hung upon that[m
[31m- official’s lips.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “All right,” announced the sergeant. “Go ahead with it. He is only a[m
[31m- Chinago.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’m going to try it once more, just to make sure.” Schemmer moved the[m
[31m- banana trunk forward under the knife, which he had hoisted to the top of[m
[31m- the derrick.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ah Cho tried to remember maxims from “The Tract of the Quiet Way.” “Live[m
[31m- in concord,” came to him; but it was not applicable. He was not going to[m
[31m- live. He was about to die. No, that would not do. “Forgive malice”⁠—yes,[m
[31m- but there was no malice to forgive. Schemmer and the rest were doing this[m
[31m- thing without malice. It was to them merely a piece of work that had to be[m
[31m- done, just as clearing the jungle, ditching the water, and planting cotton[m
[31m- were pieces of work that had to be done. Schemmer jerked the cord, and Ah[m
[31m- Cho forgot “The Tract of the Quiet Way.” The knife shot down with a thud,[m
[31m- making a clean slice of the tree.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Beautiful!” exclaimed the sergeant, pausing in the act of lighting a[m
[31m- cigarette. “Beautiful, my friend.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Schemmer was pleased at the praise.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Come on, Ah Chow,” he said, in the Tahitian tongue.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But I am not Ah Chow⁠—” Ah Cho began.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Shut up!” was the answer. “If you open your mouth again, I’ll break your[m
[31m- head.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The overseer threatened him with a clenched fist, and he remained silent.[m
[31m- What was the good of protesting? Those foreign devils always had their[m
[31m- way. He allowed himself to be lashed to the vertical board that was the[m
[31m- size of his body. Schemmer drew the buckles tight⁠—so tight that the[m
[31m- straps cut into his flesh and hurt. But he did not complain. The hurt[m
[31m- would not last long. He felt the board tilting over in the air toward the[m
[31m- horizontal, and closed his eyes. And in that moment he caught a last[m
[31m- glimpse of his garden of meditation and repose. It seemed to him that he[m
[31m- sat in the garden. A cool wind was blowing, and the bells in the several[m
[31m- trees were tinkling softly. Also, birds were making sleepy noises, and[m
[31m- from beyond the high wall came the subdued sound of village life.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Then he was aware that the board had come to rest, and from muscular[m
[31m- pressures and tensions he knew that he was lying on his back. He opened[m
[31m- his eyes. Straight above him he saw the suspended knife blazing in the[m
[31m- sunshine. He saw the weight which had been added, and noted that one of[m
[31m- Schemmer’s knots had slipped. Then he heard the sergeant’s voice in sharp[m
[31m- command. Ah Cho closed his eyes hastily. He did not want to see that knife[m
[31m- descend. But he felt it⁠—for one great fleeting instant. And in that[m
[31m- instant he remembered Cruchot and what Cruchot had said. But Cruchot was[m
[31m- wrong. The knife did not tickle. That much he knew before he ceased to[m
[31m- know.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0006" name="link2H_4_0006">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- MAKE WESTING[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- Whatever you do, make westing! make westing!⁠—Sailing directions for Cape Horn.[m
[31m-</pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- For seven weeks the Mary Rogers had been between 50 degrees south in the[m
[31m- Atlantic and 50 degrees south in the Pacific, which meant that for seven[m
[31m- weeks she had been struggling to round Cape Horn. For seven weeks she had[m
[31m- been either in dirt, or close to dirt, save once, and then, following upon[m
[31m- six days of excessive dirt, which she had ridden out under the shelter of[m
[31m- the redoubtable Terra del Fuego coast, she had almost gone ashore during a[m
[31m- heavy swell in the dead calm that had suddenly fallen. For seven weeks she[m
[31m- had wrestled with the Cape Horn graybeards, and in return been buffeted[m
[31m- and smashed by them. She was a wooden ship, and her ceaseless straining[m
[31m- had opened her seams, so that twice a day the watch took its turn at the[m
[31m- pumps.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The Mary Rogers was strained, the crew was strained, and big Dan Cullen,[m
[31m- master, was likewise strained. Perhaps he was strained most of all, for[m
[31m- upon him rested the responsibility of that titanic struggle. He slept most[m
[31m- of the time in his clothes, though he rarely slept. He haunted the deck at[m
[31m- night, a great, burly, robust ghost, black with the sunburn of thirty[m
[31m- years of sea and hairy as an orang-outang. He, in turn, was haunted by one[m
[31m- thought of action, a sailing direction for the Horn: Whatever you do, make[m
[31m- westing! make westing! It was an obsession. He thought of nothing else,[m
[31m- except, at times, to blaspheme God for sending such bitter weather.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Make westing! He hugged the Horn, and a dozen times lay hove to with the[m
[31m- iron Cape bearing east-by-north, or north-north-east, a score of miles[m
[31m- away. And each time the eternal west wind smote him back and he made[m
[31m- easting. He fought gale after gale, south to 64 degrees, inside the[m
[31m- antarctic drift-ice, and pledged his immortal soul to the Powers of[m
[31m- Darkness for a bit of westing, for a slant to take him around. And he made[m
[31m- easting. In despair, he had tried to make the passage through the Straits[m
[31m- of Le Maire. Halfway through, the wind hauled to the north’ard of[m
[31m- north-west, the glass dropped to 28.88, and he turned and ran before a[m
[31m- gale of cyclonic fury, missing, by a hair’s-breadth, piling up the Mary[m
[31m- Rogers on the black-toothed rocks. Twice he had made west to the Diego[m
[31m- Ramirez Rocks, one of the times saved between two snow-squalls by sighting[m
[31m- the gravestones of ships a quarter of a mile dead ahead.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Blow! Captain Dan Cullen instanced all his thirty years at sea to prove[m
[31m- that never had it blown so before. The Mary Rogers was hove to at the time[m
[31m- he gave the evidence, and, to clinch it, inside half an hour the Mary[m
[31m- Rogers was hove down to the hatches. Her new maintopsail and brand new[m
[31m- spencer were blown away like tissue paper; and five sails, furled and fast[m
[31m- under double gaskets, were blown loose and stripped from the yards. And[m
[31m- before morning the Mary Rogers was hove down twice again, and holes were[m
[31m- knocked in her bulwarks to ease her decks from the weight of ocean that[m
[31m- pressed her down.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- On an average of once a week Captain Dan Cullen caught glimpses of the[m
[31m- sun. Once, for ten minutes, the sun shone at midday, and ten minutes[m
[31m- afterward a new gale was piping up, both watches were shortening sail, and[m
[31m- all was buried in the obscurity of a driving snow-squall. For a fortnight,[m
[31m- once, Captain Dan Cullen was without a meridian or a chronometer sight.[m
[31m- Rarely did he know his position within half of a degree, except when in[m
[31m- sight of land; for sun and stars remained hidden behind the sky, and it[m
[31m- was so gloomy that even at the best the horizons were poor for accurate[m
[31m- observations. A gray gloom shrouded the world. The clouds were gray; the[m
[31m- great driving seas were leaden gray; the smoking crests were a gray[m
[31m- churning; even the occasional albatrosses were gray, while the[m
[31m- snow-flurries were not white, but gray, under the sombre pall of the[m
[31m- heavens.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Life on board the Mary Rogers was gray⁠—gray and gloomy. The faces of[m
[31m- the sailors were blue-gray; they were afflicted with sea-cuts and[m
[31m- sea-boils, and suffered exquisitely. They were shadows of men. For seven[m
[31m- weeks, in the forecastle or on deck, they had not known what it was to be[m
[31m- dry. They had forgotten what it was to sleep out a watch, and all watches[m
[31m- it was, “All hands on deck!” They caught snatches of agonized sleep, and[m
[31m- they slept in their oilskins ready for the everlasting call. So weak and[m
[31m- worn were they that it took both watches to do the work of one. That was[m
[31m- why both watches were on deck so much of the time. And no shadow of a man[m
[31m- could shirk duty. Nothing less than a broken leg could enable a man to[m
[31m- knock off work; and there were two such, who had been mauled and pulped by[m
[31m- the seas that broke aboard.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- One other man who was the shadow of a man was George Dorety. He was the[m
[31m- only passenger on board, a friend of the firm, and he had elected to make[m
[31m- the voyage for his health. But seven weeks of Cape Horn had not bettered[m
[31m- his health. He gasped and panted in his bunk through the long, heaving[m
[31m- nights; and when on deck he was so bundled up for warmth that he resembled[m
[31m- a peripatetic old-clothes shop. At midday, eating at the cabin table in a[m
[31m- gloom so deep that the swinging sea-lamps burned always, he looked as[m
[31m- blue-gray as the sickest, saddest man for’ard. Nor did gazing across the[m
[31m- table at Captain Dan Cullen have any cheering effect upon him. Captain[m
[31m- Cullen chewed and scowled and kept silent. The scowls were for God, and[m
[31m- with every chew he reiterated the sole thought of his existence, which was[m
[31m- make westing. He was a big, hairy brute, and the sight of him was not[m
[31m- stimulating to the other’s appetite. He looked upon George Dorety as a[m
[31m- Jonah, and told him so, once each meal, savagely transferring the scowl[m
[31m- from God to the passenger and back again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Nor did the mate prove a first aid to a languid appetite. Joshua Higgins[m
[31m- by name, a seaman by profession and pull, but a pot-wolloper by capacity,[m
[31m- he was a loose-jointed, sniffling creature, heartless and selfish and[m
[31m- cowardly, without a soul, in fear of his life of Dan Cullen, and a bully[m
[31m- over the sailors, who knew that behind the mate was Captain Cullen, the[m
[31m- law-giver and compeller, the driver and the destroyer, the incarnation of[m
[31m- a dozen bucko mates. In that wild weather at the southern end of the[m
[31m- earth, Joshua Higgins ceased washing. His grimy face usually robbed George[m
[31m- Dorety of what little appetite he managed to accumulate. Ordinarily this[m
[31m- lavatorial dereliction would have caught Captain Cullen’s eye and[m
[31m- vocabulary, but in the present his mind was filled with making westing, to[m
[31m- the exclusion of all other things not contributory thereto. Whether the[m
[31m- mate’s face was clean or dirty had no bearing upon westing. Later on, when[m
[31m- 50 degrees south in the Pacific had been reached, Joshua Higgins would[m
[31m- wash his face very abruptly. In the meantime, at the cabin table, where[m
[31m- gray twilight alternated with lamplight while the lamps were being filled,[m
[31m- George Dorety sat between the two men, one a tiger and the other a hyena,[m
[31m- and wondered why God had made them. The second mate, Matthew Turner, was a[m
[31m- true sailor and a man, but George Dorety did not have the solace of his[m
[31m- company, for he ate by himself, solitary, when they had finished.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- On Saturday morning, July 24, George Dorety awoke to a feeling of life and[m
[31m- headlong movement. On deck he found the Mary Rogers running off before a[m
[31m- howling south-easter. Nothing was set but the lower topsails and the[m
[31m- foresail. It was all she could stand, yet she was making fourteen knots,[m
[31m- as Mr. Turner shouted in Dorety’s ear when he came on deck. And it was all[m
[31m- westing. She was going around the Horn at last … if the wind held. Mr. Turner looked happy. The end of the struggle was in sight. But Captain[m
[31m- Cullen did not look happy. He scowled at Dorety in passing. Captain Cullen[m
[31m- did not want God to know that he was pleased with that wind. He had a[m
[31m- conception of a malicious God, and believed in his secret soul that if God[m
[31m- knew it was a desirable wind, God would promptly efface it and send a[m
[31m- snorter from the west. So he walked softly before God, smothering his joy[m
[31m- down under scowls and muttered curses, and, so, fooling God, for God was[m
[31m- the only thing in the universe of which Dan Cullen was afraid.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- All Saturday and Saturday night the Mary Rogers raced her westing.[m
[31m- Persistently she logged her fourteen knots, so that by Sunday morning she[m
[31m- had covered three hundred and fifty miles. If the wind held, she would[m
[31m- make around. If it failed, and the snorter came from anywhere between[m
[31m- south-west and north, back the Mary Rogers would be hurled and be no[m
[31m- better off than she had been seven weeks before. And on Sunday morning the[m
[31m- wind was failing. The big sea was going down and running smooth. Both[m
[31m- watches were on deck setting sail after sail as fast as the ship could[m
[31m- stand it. And now Captain Cullen went around brazenly before God, smoking[m
[31m- a big cigar, smiling jubilantly, as if the failing wind delighted him,[m
[31m- while down underneath he was raging against God for taking the life out of[m
[31m- the blessed wind. Make westing! So he would, if God would only leave him[m
[31m- alone. Secretly, he pledged himself anew to the Powers of Darkness, if[m
[31m- they would let him make westing. He pledged himself so easily because he[m
[31m- did not believe in the Powers of Darkness. He really believed only in God,[m
[31m- though he did not know it. And in his inverted theology God was really the[m
[31m- Prince of Darkness. Captain Cullen was a devil-worshipper, but he called[m
[31m- the devil by another name, that was all.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At midday, after calling eight bells, Captain Cullen ordered the royals[m
[31m- on. The men went aloft faster than they had gone in weeks. Not alone were[m
[31m- they nimble because of the westing, but a benignant sun was shining down[m
[31m- and limbering their stiff bodies. George Dorety stood aft, near Captain[m
[31m- Cullen, less bundled in clothes than usual, soaking in the grateful warmth[m
[31m- as he watched the scene. Swiftly and abruptly the incident occurred. There[m
[31m- was a cry from the foreroyal-yard of “Man overboard!” Somebody threw a[m
[31m- life-buoy over the side, and at the same instant the second mate’s voice[m
[31m- came aft, ringing and peremptory⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Hard down your helm!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The man at the wheel never moved a spoke. He knew better, for Captain Dan[m
[31m- Cullen was standing alongside of him. He wanted to move a spoke, to move[m
[31m- all the spokes, to grind the wheel down, hard down, for his comrade[m
[31m- drowning in the sea. He glanced at Captain Dan Cullen, and Captain Dan[m
[31m- Cullen gave no sign.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Down! Hard down!” the second mate roared, as he sprang aft.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But he ceased springing and commanding, and stood still, when he saw Dan[m
[31m- Cullen by the wheel. And big Dan Cullen puffed at his cigar and said[m
[31m- nothing. Astern, and going astern fast, could be seen the sailor. He had[m
[31m- caught the life-buoy and was clinging to it. Nobody spoke. Nobody moved.[m
[31m- The men aloft clung to the royal yards and watched with terror-stricken[m
[31m- faces. And the Mary Rogers raced on, making her westing. A long, silent[m
[31m- minute passed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Who was it?” Captain Cullen demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Mops, sir,” eagerly answered the sailor at the wheel.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Mops topped a wave astern and disappeared temporarily in the trough. It[m
[31m- was a large wave, but it was no graybeard. A small boat could live easily[m
[31m- in such a sea, and in such a sea the Mary Rogers could easily come to. But[m
[31m- she could not come to and make westing at the same time.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- For the first time in all his years, George Dorety was seeing a real drama[m
[31m- of life and death⁠—a sordid little drama in which the scales balanced[m
[31m- an unknown sailor named Mops against a few miles of longitude. At first he[m
[31m- had watched the man astern, but now he watched big Dan Cullen, hairy and[m
[31m- black, vested with power of life and death, smoking a cigar.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Captain Dan Cullen smoked another long, silent minute. Then he removed the[m
[31m- cigar from his mouth. He glanced aloft at the spars of the Mary Rogers,[m
[31m- and overside at the sea.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Sheet home the royals!” he cried.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Fifteen minutes later they sat at table, in the cabin, with food served[m
[31m- before them. On one side of George Dorety sat Dan Cullen, the tiger, on[m
[31m- the other side, Joshua Higgins, the hyena. Nobody spoke. On deck the men[m
[31m- were sheeting home the skysails. George Dorety could hear their cries,[m
[31m- while a persistent vision haunted him of a man called Mops, alive and[m
[31m- well, clinging to a life-buoy miles astern in that lonely ocean. He[m
[31m- glanced at Captain Cullen, and experienced a feeling of nausea, for the[m
[31m- man was eating his food with relish, almost bolting it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Captain Cullen,” Dorety said, “you are in command of this ship, and it is[m
[31m- not proper for me to comment now upon what you do. But I wish to say one[m
[31m- thing. There is a hereafter, and yours will be a hot one.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Captain Cullen did not even scowl. In his voice was regret as he said⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It was blowing a living gale. It was impossible to save the man.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He fell from the royal-yard,” Dorety cried hotly. “You were setting the[m
[31m- royals at the time. Fifteen minutes afterward you were setting the[m
[31m- skysails.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It was a living gale, wasn’t it, Mr. Higgins?” Captain Cullen said,[m
[31m- turning to the mate.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If you’d brought her to, it’d have taken the sticks out of her,” was the[m
[31m- mate’s answer. “You did the proper thing, Captain Cullen. The man hadn’t a[m
[31m- ghost of a show.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- George Dorety made no answer, and to the meal’s end no one spoke. After[m
[31m- that, Dorety had his meals served in his state-room. Captain Cullen[m
[31m- scowled at him no longer, though no speech was exchanged between them,[m
[31m- while the Mary Rogers sped north toward warmer latitudes. At the end of[m
[31m- the week, Dan Cullen cornered Dorety on deck.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What are you going to do when we get to ‘Frisco?” he demanded bluntly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I am going to swear out a warrant for your arrest,” Dorety answered[m
[31m- quietly. “I am going to charge you with murder, and I am going to see you[m
[31m- hanged for it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’re almighty sure of yourself,” Captain Cullen sneered, turning on his[m
[31m- heel.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- A second week passed, and one morning found George Dorety standing in the[m
[31m- coach-house companionway at the for’ard end of the long poop, taking his[m
[31m- first gaze around the deck. The Mary Rogers was reaching full-and-by, in a[m
[31m- stiff breeze. Every sail was set and drawing, including the staysails.[m
[31m- Captain Cullen strolled for’ard along the poop. He strolled carelessly,[m
[31m- glancing at the passenger out of the corner of his eye. Dorety was looking[m
[31m- the other way, standing with head and shoulders outside the companionway,[m
[31m- and only the back of his head was to be seen. Captain Cullen, with swift[m
[31m- eye, embraced the mainstaysail-block and the head and estimated the[m
[31m- distance. He glanced about him. Nobody was looking. Aft, Joshua Higgins,[m
[31m- pacing up and down, had just turned his back and was going the other way.[m
[31m- Captain Cullen bent over suddenly and cast the staysail-sheet off from its[m
[31m- pin. The heavy block hurtled through the air, smashing Dorety’s head like[m
[31m- an egg-shell and hurtling on and back and forth as the staysail whipped[m
[31m- and slatted in the wind. Joshua Higgins turned around to see what had[m
[31m- carried away, and met the full blast of the vilest portion of Captain[m
[31m- Cullen’s profanity.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I made the sheet fast myself,” whimpered the mate in the first lull,[m
[31m- “with an extra turn to make sure. I remember it distinctly.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Made fast?” the Captain snarled back, for the benefit of the watch as it[m
[31m- struggled to capture the flying sail before it tore to ribbons. “You[m
[31m- couldn’t make your grandmother fast, you useless hell’s scullion. If you[m
[31m- made that sheet fast with an extra turn, why in hell didn’t it stay fast?[m
[31m- That’s what I want to know. Why in hell didn’t it stay fast?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The mate whined inarticulately.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Oh, shut up!” was the final word of Captain Cullen.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Half an hour later he was as surprised as any when the body of George[m
[31m- Dorety was found inside the companionway on the floor. In the afternoon,[m
[31m- alone in his room, he doctored up the log.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ordinary seaman, Karl Brun,” he wrote, “lost overboard from[m
[31m- foreroyal-yard in a gale of wind. Was running at the time, and for the[m
[31m- safety of the ship did not dare come up to the wind. Nor could a boat have[m
[31m- lived in the sea that was running.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- On another page, he wrote[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Had often warned Mr. Dorety about the danger he ran because of his[m
[31m- carelessness on deck. I told him, once, that some day he would get his[m
[31m- head knocked off by a block. A carelessly fastened mainstaysail sheet was[m
[31m- the cause of the accident, which was deeply to be regretted because Mr. Dorety was a favourite with all of us.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Captain Dan Cullen read over his literary effort with admiration, blotted[m
[31m- the page, and closed the log. He lighted a cigar and stared before him. He[m
[31m- felt the Mary Rogers lift, and heel, and surge along, and knew that she[m
[31m- was making nine knots. A smile of satisfaction slowly dawned on his black[m
[31m- and hairy face. Well, anyway, he had made his westing and fooled God.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0007" name="link2H_4_0007">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- SEMPER IDEM[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Doctor Bicknell was in a remarkably gracious mood. Through a minor[m
[31m- accident, a slight bit of carelessness, that was all, a man who might have[m
[31m- pulled through had died the preceding night. Though it had been only a[m
[31m- sailorman, one of the innumerable unwashed, the steward of the receiving[m
[31m- hospital had been on the anxious seat all the morning. It was not that the[m
[31m- man had died that gave him discomfort, he knew the Doctor too well for[m
[31m- that, but his distress lay in the fact that the operation had been done so[m
[31m- well. One of the most delicate in surgery, it had been as successful as it[m
[31m- was clever and audacious. All had then depended upon the treatment, the[m
[31m- nurses, the steward. And the man had died. Nothing much, a bit of[m
[31m- carelessness, yet enough to bring the professional wrath of Doctor[m
[31m- Bicknell about his ears and to perturb the working of the staff and nurses[m
[31m- for twenty-four hours to come.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But, as already stated, the Doctor was in a remarkably gracious mood. When[m
[31m- informed by the steward, in fear and trembling, of the man’s unexpected[m
[31m- take-off, his lips did not so much as form one syllable of censure; nay,[m
[31m- they were so pursed that snatches of rag-time floated softly from them, to[m
[31m- be broken only by a pleasant query after the health of the other’s[m
[31m- eldest-born. The steward, deeming it impossible that he could have caught[m
[31m- the gist of the case, repeated it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, yes,” Doctor Bicknell said impatiently; “I understand. But how about[m
[31m- Semper Idem? Is he ready to leave?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes. They’re helping him dress now,” the steward answered, passing on to[m
[31m- the round of his duties, content that peace still reigned within the[m
[31m- iodine-saturated walls.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was Semper Idem’s recovery which had so fully compensated Doctor[m
[31m- Bicknell for the loss of the sailorman. Lives were to him as nothing, the[m
[31m- unpleasant but inevitable incidents of the profession, but cases, ah,[m
[31m- cases were everything. People who knew him were prone to brand him a[m
[31m- butcher, but his colleagues were at one in the belief that a bolder and[m
[31m- yet a more capable man never stood over the table. He was not an[m
[31m- imaginative man. He did not possess, and hence had no tolerance for,[m
[31m- emotion. His nature was accurate, precise, scientific. Men were to him no[m
[31m- more than pawns, without individuality or personal value. But as cases it[m
[31m- was different. The more broken a man was, the more precarious his grip on[m
[31m- life, the greater his significance in the eyes of Doctor Bicknell. He[m
[31m- would as readily forsake a poet laureate suffering from a common accident[m
[31m- for a nameless, mangled vagrant who defied every law of life by refusing[m
[31m- to die, as would a child forsake a Punch and Judy for a circus.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- So it had been in the case of Semper Idem. The mystery of the man had not[m
[31m- appealed to him, nor had his silence and the veiled romance which the[m
[31m- yellow reporters had so sensationally and so fruitlessly exploited in[m
[31m- divers Sunday editions. But Semper Idem’s throat had been cut. That was[m
[31m- the point. That was where his interest had centred. Cut from ear to ear,[m
[31m- and not one surgeon in a thousand to give a snap of the fingers for his[m
[31m- chance of recovery. But, thanks to the swift municipal ambulance service[m
[31m- and to Doctor Bicknell, he had been dragged back into the world he had[m
[31m- sought to leave. The Doctor’s co-workers had shaken their heads when the[m
[31m- case was brought in. Impossible, they said. Throat, windpipe, jugular, all[m
[31m- but actually severed, and the loss of blood frightful. As it was such a[m
[31m- foregone conclusion, Doctor Bicknell had employed methods and done things[m
[31m- which made them, even in their professional capacities, shudder. And lo![m
[31m- the man had recovered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- So, on this morning that Semper Idem was to leave the hospital, hale and[m
[31m- hearty, Doctor Bicknell’s geniality was in nowise disturbed by the[m
[31m- steward’s report, and he proceeded cheerfully to bring order out of the[m
[31m- chaos of a child’s body which had been ground and crunched beneath the[m
[31m- wheels of an electric car.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As many will remember, the case of Semper Idem aroused a vast deal of[m
[31m- unseemly yet highly natural curiosity. He had been found in a slum[m
[31m- lodging, with throat cut as aforementioned, and blood dripping down upon[m
[31m- the inmates of the room below and disturbing their festivities. He had[m
[31m- evidently done the deed standing, with head bowed forward that he might[m
[31m- gaze his last upon a photograph which stood on the table propped against a[m
[31m- candlestick. It was this attitude which had made it possible for Doctor[m
[31m- Bicknell to save him. So terrific had been the sweep of the razor that had[m
[31m- he had his head thrown back, as he should have done to have accomplished[m
[31m- the act properly, with his neck stretched and the elastic vascular walls[m
[31m- distended, he would have of a certainty well-nigh decapitated himself.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At the hospital, during all the time he travelled the repugnant road back[m
[31m- to life, not a word had left his lips. Nor could anything be learned of[m
[31m- him by the sleuths detailed by the chief of police. Nobody knew him, nor[m
[31m- had ever seen or heard of him before. He was strictly, uniquely, of the[m
[31m- present. His clothes and surroundings were those of the lowest labourer,[m
[31m- his hands the hands of a gentleman. But not a shred of writing was[m
[31m- discovered, nothing, save in one particular, which would serve to indicate[m
[31m- his past or his position in life.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And that one particular was the photograph. If it were at all a likeness,[m
[31m- the woman who gazed frankly out upon the onlooker from the card-mount must[m
[31m- have been a striking creature indeed. It was an amateur production, for[m
[31m- the detectives were baffled in that no professional photographer’s[m
[31m- signature or studio was appended. Across a corner of the mount, in[m
[31m- delicate feminine tracery, was written: “Semper idem; semper fidelis.” And[m
[31m- she looked it. As many recollect, it was a face one could never forget.[m
[31m- Clever half-tones, remarkably like, were published in all the leading[m
[31m- papers at the time; but such procedure gave rise to nothing but the[m
[31m- uncontrollable public curiosity and interminable copy to the[m
[31m- space-writers.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- For want of a better name, the rescued suicide was known to the hospital[m
[31m- attendants, and to the world, as Semper Idem. And Semper Idem he remained.[m
[31m- Reporters, detectives, and nurses gave him up in despair. Not one word[m
[31m- could he be persuaded to utter; yet the flitting conscious light of his[m
[31m- eyes showed that his ears heard and his brain grasped every question put[m
[31m- to him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But this mystery and romance played no part in Doctor Bicknell’s interest[m
[31m- when he paused in the office to have a parting word with his patient. He,[m
[31m- the Doctor, had performed a prodigy in the matter of this man, done what[m
[31m- was virtually unprecedented in the annals of surgery. He did not care who[m
[31m- or what the man was, and it was highly improbable that he should ever see[m
[31m- him again; but, like the artist gazing upon a finished creation, he wished[m
[31m- to look for the last time upon the work of his hand and brain.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Semper Idem still remained mute. He seemed anxious to be gone. Not a word[m
[31m- could the Doctor extract from him, and little the Doctor cared. He[m
[31m- examined the throat of the convalescent carefully, idling over the hideous[m
[31m- scar with the lingering, half-caressing fondness of a parent. It was not a[m
[31m- particularly pleasing sight. An angry line circled the throat⁠—for[m
[31m- all the world as though the man had just escaped the hangman’s noose⁠—and,[m
[31m- disappearing below the ear on either side, had the appearance of[m
[31m- completing the fiery periphery at the nape of the neck.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Maintaining his dogged silence, yielding to the other’s examination in[m
[31m- much the manner of a leashed lion, Semper Idem betrayed only his desire to[m
[31m- drop from out of the public eye.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Well, I’ll not keep you,” Doctor Bicknell finally said, laying a hand on[m
[31m- the man’s shoulder and stealing a last glance at his own handiwork. “But[m
[31m- let me give you a bit of advice. Next time you try it on, hold your chin[m
[31m- up, so. Don’t snuggle it down and butcher yourself like a cow. Neatness[m
[31m- and despatch, you know. Neatness and despatch.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Semper Idem’s eyes flashed in token that he heard, and a moment later the[m
[31m- hospital door swung to on his heel.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was a busy day for Doctor Bicknell, and the afternoon was well along[m
[31m- when he lighted a cigar preparatory to leaving the table upon which it[m
[31m- seemed the sufferers almost clamoured to be laid. But the last one, an old[m
[31m- rag-picker with a broken shoulder-blade, had been disposed of, and the[m
[31m- first fragrant smoke wreaths had begun to curl about his head, when the[m
[31m- gong of a hurrying ambulance came through the open window from the street,[m
[31m- followed by the inevitable entry of the stretcher with its ghastly[m
[31m- freight.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Lay it on the table,” the Doctor directed, turning for a moment to place[m
[31m- his cigar in safety. “What is it?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Suicide⁠—throat cut,” responded one of the stretcher bearers. “Down[m
[31m- on Morgan Alley. Little hope, I think, sir. He’s ‘most gone.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Eh? Well, I’ll give him a look, anyway.” He leaned over the man at the[m
[31m- moment when the quick made its last faint flutter and succumbed.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’s Semper Idem come back again,” the steward said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ay,” replied Doctor Bicknell, “and gone again. No bungling this time.[m
[31m- Properly done, upon my life, sir, properly done. Took my advice to the[m
[31m- letter. I’m not required here. Take it along to the morgue.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Doctor Bicknell secured his cigar and relighted it. “That,” he said[m
[31m- between the puffs, looking at the steward, “that evens up for the one you[m
[31m- lost last night. We’re quits now.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0008" name="link2H_4_0008">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- A NOSE FOR THE KING[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the morning calm of Korea, when its peace and tranquillity truly[m
[31m- merited its ancient name, “Cho-sen,” there lived a politician by name Yi[m
[31m- Chin Ho. He was a man of parts, and⁠—who shall say?⁠—perhaps in[m
[31m- no wise worse than politicians the world over. But, unlike his brethren in[m
[31m- other lands, Yi Chin Ho was in jail. Not that he had inadvertently[m
[31m- diverted to himself public moneys, but that he had inadvertently diverted[m
[31m- too much. Excess is to be deplored in all things, even in grafting, and Yi[m
[31m- Chin Ho’s excess had brought him to most deplorable straits.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Ten thousand strings of cash he owed the Government, and he lay in prison[m
[31m- under sentence of death. There was one advantage to the situation⁠—he[m
[31m- had plenty of time in which to think. And he thought well. Then called he[m
[31m- the jailer to him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Most worthy man, you see before you one most wretched,” he began. “Yet[m
[31m- all will be well with me if you will but let me go free for one short hour[m
[31m- this night. And all will be well with you, for I shall see to your[m
[31m- advancement through the years, and you shall come at length to the[m
[31m- directorship of all the prisons of Cho-sen.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How now?” demanded the jailer. “What foolishness is this? One short hour,[m
[31m- and you but waiting for your head to be chopped off! And I, with an aged[m
[31m- and much-to-be-respected mother, not to say anything of a wife and several[m
[31m- children of tender years! Out upon you for the scoundrel that you are!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “From the Sacred City to the ends of all the Eight Coasts there is no[m
[31m- place for me to hide,” Yi Chin Ho made reply. “I am a man of wisdom, but[m
[31m- of what worth my wisdom here in prison? Were I free, well I know I could[m
[31m- seek out and obtain the money wherewith to repay the Government. I know of[m
[31m- a nose that will save me from all my difficulties.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A nose!” cried the jailer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A nose,” said Yi Chin Ho. “A remarkable nose, if I may say so, a most[m
[31m- remarkable nose.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The jailer threw up his hands despairingly. “Ah, what a wag you are, what[m
[31m- a wag,” he laughed. “To think that that very admirable wit of yours must[m
[31m- go the way of the chopping-block!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And so saying, he turned and went away. But in the end, being a man soft[m
[31m- of head and heart, when the night was well along he permitted Yi Chin Ho[m
[31m- to go.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Straight he went to the Governor, catching him alone and arousing him from[m
[31m- his sleep.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yi Chin Ho, or I’m no Governor!” cried the Governor. “What do you here[m
[31m- who should be in prison waiting on the chopping-block?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I pray Your Excellency to listen to me,” said Yi Chin Ho, squatting on[m
[31m- his hams by the bedside and lighting his pipe from the fire-box. “A dead[m
[31m- man is without value. It is true, I am as a dead man, without value to the[m
[31m- Government, to Your Excellency, or to myself. But if, so to say, Your[m
[31m- Excellency were to give me my freedom⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Impossible!” cried the Governor. “Beside, you are condemned to death.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Your Excellency well knows that if I can repay the ten thousand strings[m
[31m- of cash, the Government will pardon me,” Yi Chin Ho went on. “So, as I[m
[31m- say, if Your Excellency were to give me my freedom for a few days, being a[m
[31m- man of understanding, I should then repay the Government and be in[m
[31m- position to be of service to Your Excellency. I should be in position to[m
[31m- be of very great service to Your Excellency.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Have you a plan whereby you hope to obtain this money?” asked the[m
[31m- Governor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I have,” said Yi Chin Ho.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then come with it to me to-morrow night; I would now sleep,” said the[m
[31m- Governor, taking up his snore where it had been interrupted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- On the following night, having again obtained leave of absence from the[m
[31m- jailer, Yi Chin Ho presented himself at the Governor’s bedside.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Is it you, Yi Chin Ho?” asked the Governor. “And have you the plan?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is I, Your Excellency,” answered Yi Chin Ho, “and the plan is here.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Speak,” commanded the Governor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The plan is here,” repeated Yi Chin Ho, “here in my hand.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The Governor sat up and opened his eyes. Yi Chin Ho proffered in his hand[m
[31m- a sheet of paper. The Governor held it to the light.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Nothing but a nose,” said he.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A bit pinched, so, and so, Your Excellency,” said Yi Chin Ho.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Yes, a bit pinched here and there, as you say,” said the Governor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Withal it is an exceeding corpulent nose, thus, and so, all in one place,[m
[31m- at the end,” proceeded Yi Chin Ho. “Your Excellency would seek far and[m
[31m- wide and many a day for that nose and find it not!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An unusual nose,” admitted the Governor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There is a wart upon it,” said Yi Chin Ho.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A most unusual nose,” said the Governor. “Never have I seen the like. But[m
[31m- what do you with this nose, Yi Chin Ho?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I seek it whereby to repay the money to the Government,” said Yi Chin Ho.[m
[31m- “I seek it to be of service to Your Excellency, and I seek it to save my[m
[31m- own worthless head. Further, I seek Your Excellency’s seal upon this[m
[31m- picture of the nose.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And the Governor laughed and affixed the seal of State, and Yi Chin Ho[m
[31m- departed. For a month and a day he travelled the King’s Road which leads[m
[31m- to the shore of the Eastern Sea; and there, one night, at the gate of the[m
[31m- largest mansion of a wealthy city he knocked loudly for admittance.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “None other than the master of the house will I see,” said he fiercely to[m
[31m- the frightened servants. “I travel upon the King’s business.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Straightway was he led to an inner room, where the master of the house was[m
[31m- roused from his sleep and brought blinking before him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You are Pak Chung Chang, head man of this city,” said Yi Chin Ho in tones[m
[31m- that were all-accusing. “I am upon the King’s business.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Pak Chung Chang trembled. Well he knew the King’s business was ever a[m
[31m- terrible business. His knees smote together, and he near fell to the[m
[31m- floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The hour is late,” he quavered. “Were it not well to⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “The King’s business never waits!” thundered Yi Chin Ho. “Come apart with[m
[31m- me, and swiftly. I have an affair of moment to discuss with you.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is the King’s affair,” he added with even greater fierceness; so that[m
[31m- Pak Chung Chang’s silver pipe dropped from his nerveless fingers and[m
[31m- clattered on the floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Know then,” said Yi Chin Ho, when they had gone apart, “that the King is[m
[31m- troubled with an affliction, a very terrible affliction. In that he failed[m
[31m- to cure, the Court physician has had nothing else than his head chopped[m
[31m- off. From all the Eight Provinces have the physicians come to wait upon[m
[31m- the King. Wise consultation have they held, and they have decided that for[m
[31m- a remedy for the King’s affliction nothing else is required than a nose, a[m
[31m- certain kind of nose, a very peculiar certain kind of nose.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then by none other was I summoned than His Excellency the Prime Minister[m
[31m- himself. He put a paper into my hand. Upon this paper was the very[m
[31m- peculiar kind of nose drawn by the physicians of the Eight Provinces, with[m
[31m- the seal of State upon it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ‘Go,’ said His Excellency the Prime Minister. ‘Seek out this nose, for[m
[31m- the King’s affliction is sore. And wheresoever you find this nose upon the[m
[31m- face of a man, strike it off forthright and bring it in all haste to the[m
[31m- Court, for the King must be cured. Go, and come not back until your search[m
[31m- is rewarded.’[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And so I departed upon my quest,” said Yi Chin Ho. “I have sought out the[m
[31m- remotest corners of the kingdom; I have travelled the Eight Highways,[m
[31m- searched the Eight Provinces, and sailed the seas of the Eight Coasts. And[m
[31m- here I am.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- With a great flourish he drew a paper from his girdle, unrolled it with[m
[31m- many snappings and cracklings, and thrust it before the face of Pak Chung[m
[31m- Chang. Upon the paper was the picture of the nose.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Pak Chung Chang stared upon it with bulging eyes.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Never have I beheld such a nose,” he began.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There is a wart upon it,” said Yi Chin Ho.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Never have I beheld⁠—” Pak Chung Chang began again.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Bring your father before me,” Yi Chin Ho interrupted sternly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “My ancient and very-much-to-be-respected ancestor sleeps,” said Pak Chung[m
[31m- Chang.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Why dissemble?” demanded Yi Chin Ho. “You know it is your father’s nose.[m
[31m- Bring him before me that I may strike it off and be gone. Hurry, lest I[m
[31m- make bad report of you.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Mercy!” cried Pak Chung Chang, falling on his knees. “It is impossible![m
[31m- It is impossible! You cannot strike off my father’s nose. He cannot go[m
[31m- down without his nose to the grave. He will become a laughter and a[m
[31m- byword, and all my days and nights will be filled with woe. O reflect![m
[31m- Report that you have seen no such nose in your travels. You, too, have a[m
[31m- father.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Pak Chung Chang clasped Yi Chin Ho’s knees and fell to weeping on his[m
[31m- sandals.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “My heart softens strangely at your tears,” said Yi Chin Ho. “I, too, know[m
[31m- filial piety and regard. But⁠—” He hesitated, then added, as though[m
[31m- thinking aloud, “It is as much as my head is worth.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How much is your head worth?” asked Pak Chung Chang in a thin, small[m
[31m- voice.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A not remarkable head,” said Yi Chin Ho. “An absurdly unremarkable head;[m
[31m- but, such is my great foolishness, I value it at nothing less than one[m
[31m- hundred thousand strings of cash.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “So be it,” said Pak Chung Chang, rising to his feet.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I shall need horses to carry the treasure,” said Yi Chin Ho, “and men to[m
[31m- guard it well as I journey through the mountains. There are robbers abroad[m
[31m- in the land.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “There are robbers abroad in the land,” said Pak Chung Chang, sadly. “But[m
[31m- it shall be as you wish, so long as my ancient and[m
[31m- very-much-to-be-respected ancestor’s nose abide in its appointed place.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Say nothing to any man of this occurrence,” said Yi Chin Ho, “else will[m
[31m- other and more loyal servants than I be sent to strike off your father’s[m
[31m- nose.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And so Yi Chin Ho departed on his way through the mountains, blithe of[m
[31m- heart and gay of song as he listened to the jingling bells of his[m
[31m- treasure-laden ponies.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There is little more to tell. Yi Chin Ho prospered through the years. By[m
[31m- his efforts the jailer attained at length to the directorship of all the[m
[31m- prisons of Cho-sen; the Governor ultimately betook himself to the Sacred[m
[31m- City to be Prime Minister to the King, while Yi Chin Ho became the King’s[m
[31m- boon companion and sat at table with him to the end of a round, fat life.[m
[31m- But Pak Chung Chang fell into a melancholy, and ever after he shook his[m
[31m- head sadly, with tears in his eyes, whenever he regarded the expensive[m
[31m- nose of his ancient and very-much-to-be-respected ancestor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0009" name="link2H_4_0009">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- THE “FRANCIS SPAIGHT”[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<h3>[m
[31m- (A TRUE TALE RETOLD)[m
[31m- </h3>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The Francis Spaight was running before it solely under a mizzentopsail,[m
[31m- when the thing happened. It was not due to carelessness so much as to the[m
[31m- lack of discipline of the crew and to the fact that they were indifferent[m
[31m- seamen at best. The man at the wheel in particular, a Limerick man, had[m
[31m- had no experience with salt water beyond that of rafting timber on the[m
[31m- Shannon between the Quebec vessels and the shore. He was afraid of the[m
[31m- huge seas that rose out of the murk astern and bore down upon him, and he[m
[31m- was more given to cowering away from their threatened impact than he was[m
[31m- to meeting their blows with the wheel and checking the ship’s rush to[m
[31m- broach to.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was three in the morning when his unseamanlike conduct precipitated the[m
[31m- catastrophe. At sight of a sea far larger than its fellows, he crouched[m
[31m- down, releasing his hands from the spokes. The Francis Spaight sheered as[m
[31m- her stern lifted on the sea, receiving the full fling of the cap on her[m
[31m- quarter. The next instant she was in the trough, her lee-rail buried till[m
[31m- the ocean was level with her hatch-coamings, sea after sea breaking over[m
[31m- her weather rail and sweeping what remained exposed of the deck with icy[m
[31m- deluges.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The men were out of hand, helpless and hopeless, stupid in their[m
[31m- bewilderment and fear, and resolute only in that they would not obey[m
[31m- orders. Some wailed, others clung silently in the weather shrouds, and[m
[31m- still others muttered prayers or shrieked vile imprecations; and neither[m
[31m- captain nor mate could get them to bear a hand at the pumps or at setting[m
[31m- patches of sails to bring the vessel up to the wind and sea. Inside the[m
[31m- hour the ship was over on her beam ends, the lubberly cowards climbing up[m
[31m- her side and hanging on in the rigging. When she went over, the mate was[m
[31m- caught and drowned in the after-cabin, as were two sailors who had sought[m
[31m- refuge in the forecastle.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The mate had been the ablest man on board, and the captain was now[m
[31m- scarcely less helpless than his men. Beyond cursing them for their[m
[31m- worthlessness, he did nothing; and it remained for a man named Mahoney, a[m
[31m- Belfast man, and a boy, O’Brien, of Limerick, to cut away the fore and[m
[31m- main masts. This they did at great risk on the perpendicular wall of the[m
[31m- wreck, sending the mizzentopmast overside along in the general crash. The[m
[31m- Francis Spaight righted, and it was well that she was lumber laden, else[m
[31m- she would have sunk, for she was already water-logged. The mainmast, still[m
[31m- fast by the shrouds, beat like a thunderous sledge-hammer against the[m
[31m- ship’s side, every stroke bringing groans from the men.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Day dawned on the savage ocean, and in the cold gray light all that could[m
[31m- be seen of the Francis Spaight emerging from the sea were the poop, the[m
[31m- shattered mizzenmast, and a ragged line of bulwarks. It was midwinter in[m
[31m- the North Atlantic, and the wretched men were half-dead from cold. But[m
[31m- there was no place where they could find rest. Every sea breached clean[m
[31m- over the wreck, washing away the salt incrustations from their bodies and[m
[31m- depositing fresh incrustations. The cabin under the poop was awash to the[m
[31m- knees, but here at least was shelter from the chill wind, and here the[m
[31m- survivors congregated, standing upright, holding on by the cabin[m
[31m- furnishings, and leaning against one another for support.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In vain Mahoney strove to get the men to take turns in watching aloft from[m
[31m- the mizzenmast for any chance vessel. The icy gale was too much for them,[m
[31m- and they preferred the shelter of the cabin. O’Brien, the boy, who was[m
[31m- only fifteen, took turns with Mahoney on the freezing perch. It was the[m
[31m- boy, at three in the afternoon, who called down that he had sighted a[m
[31m- sail. This did bring them from the cabin, and they crowded the poop rail[m
[31m- and weather mizzen shrouds as they watched the strange ship. But its[m
[31m- course did not lie near, and when it disappeared below the skyline, they[m
[31m- returned shivering to the cabin, not one offering to relieve the watch at[m
[31m- the mast head.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- By the end of the second day, Mahoney and O’Brien gave up their attempt,[m
[31m- and thereafter the vessel drifted in the gale uncared for and without a[m
[31m- lookout. There were thirteen alive, and for seventy-two hours they stood[m
[31m- knee-deep in the sloshing water on the cabin floor, half-frozen, without[m
[31m- food, and with but three bottles of wine shared among them. All food and[m
[31m- fresh water were below, and there was no getting at such supplies in the[m
[31m- water-logged condition of the wreck. As the days went by, no food whatever[m
[31m- passed their lips. Fresh water, in small quantities, they were able to[m
[31m- obtain by holding a cover of a tureen under the saddle of the mizzenmast.[m
[31m- But the rain fell infrequently, and they were hard put. When it rained,[m
[31m- they also soaked their handkerchiefs, squeezing them out into their mouths[m
[31m- or into their shoes. As the wind and sea went down, they were even able to[m
[31m- mop the exposed portions of the deck that were free from brine and so add[m
[31m- to their water supply. But food they had none, and no way of getting it,[m
[31m- though sea-birds flew repeatedly overhead.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the calm weather that followed the gale, after having remained on their[m
[31m- feet for ninety-six hours, they were able to find dry planks in the cabin[m
[31m- on which to lie. But the long hours of standing in the salt water had[m
[31m- caused sores to form on their legs. These sores were extremely painful.[m
[31m- The slightest contact or scrape caused severe anguish, and in their weak[m
[31m- condition and crowded situation they were continually hurting one another[m
[31m- in this manner. Not a man could move about without being followed by[m
[31m- volleys of abuse, curses, and groans. So great was their misery that the[m
[31m- strong oppressed the weak, shoving them aside from the dry planks to shift[m
[31m- for themselves in the cold and wet. The boy, O’Brien, was specially[m
[31m- maltreated. Though there were three other boys, it was O’Brien who came in[m
[31m- for most of the abuse. There was no explaining it, except on the ground[m
[31m- that his was a stronger and more dominant spirit than those of the other[m
[31m- boys, and that he stood up more for his rights, resenting the petty[m
[31m- injustices that were meted out to all the boys by the men. Whenever[m
[31m- O’Brien came near the men in search of a dry place to sleep, or merely[m
[31m- moved about, he was kicked and cuffed away. In return, he cursed them for[m
[31m- their selfish brutishness, and blows and kicks and curses were rained upon[m
[31m- him. Miserable as were all of them, he was thus made far more miserable;[m
[31m- and it was only the flame of life, unusually strong in him, that enabled[m
[31m- him to endure.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As the days went by and they grew weaker, their peevishness and ill-temper[m
[31m- increased, which, in turn, increased the ill-treatment and sufferings of[m
[31m- O’Brien. By the sixteenth day all hands were far gone with hunger, and[m
[31m- they stood together in small groups, talking in undertones and[m
[31m- occasionally glancing at O’Brien. It was at high noon that the conference[m
[31m- came to a head. The captain was the spokesman. All were collected on the[m
[31m- poop.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Men,” the captain began, “we have been a long time without food⁠—two[m
[31m- weeks and two days it is, though it seems more like two years and two[m
[31m- months. We can’t hang out much longer. It is beyond human nature to go on[m
[31m- hanging out with nothing in our stomachs. There is a serious question to[m
[31m- consider: whether it is better for all to die, or for one to die. We are[m
[31m- standing with our feet in our graves. If one of us dies, the rest may live[m
[31m- until a ship is sighted. What say you?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Michael Behane, the man who had been at the wheel when the Francis Spaight[m
[31m- broached to, called out that it was well. The others joined in the cry.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Let it be one of the b’ys!” cried Sullivan, a Tarbert man, glancing at[m
[31m- the same time significantly at O’Brien.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It is my opinion,” the captain went on, “that it will be a good deed for[m
[31m- one of us to die for the rest.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A good deed! A good deed!” the men interjected.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “And it is my opinion that ’tis best for one of the boys to die. They have[m
[31m- no families to support, nor would they be considered so great a loss to[m
[31m- their friends as those who have wives and children.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis right.” “Very right.” “Very fit it should be done,” the men muttered[m
[31m- one to another.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But the four boys cried out against the injustice of it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Our lives is just as dear to us as the rest iv yez,” O’Brien protested.[m
[31m- “An’ our famblies, too. As for wives an’ childer, who is there savin’[m
[31m- meself to care for me old mother that’s a widow, as you know well, Michael[m
[31m- Behane, that comes from Limerick? ’Tis not fair. Let the lots be drawn[m
[31m- between all of us, men and b’ys.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Mahoney was the only man who spoke in favour of the boys, declaring that[m
[31m- it was the fair thing for all to share alike. Sullivan and the captain[m
[31m- insisted on the drawing of lots being confined to the boys. There were[m
[31m- high words, in the midst of which Sullivan turned upon O’Brien, snarling⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Twould be a good deed to put you out of the way. You deserve it. ’Twould[m
[31m- be the right way to serve you, an’ serve you we will.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He started toward O’Brien, with intent to lay hands on him and proceed at[m
[31m- once with the killing, while several others likewise shuffled toward him[m
[31m- and reached for him. He stumbled backwards to escape them, at the same[m
[31m- time crying that he would submit to the drawing of the lots among the[m
[31m- boys.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The captain prepared four sticks of different lengths and handed them to[m
[31m- Sullivan.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You’re thinkin’ the drawin’ll not be fair,” the latter sneered to[m
[31m- O’Brien. “So it’s yerself’ll do the drawin’.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- To this O’Brien agreed. A handkerchief was tied over his eyes,[m
[31m- blindfolding him, and he knelt down on the deck with his back to Sullivan.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Whoever you name for the shortest stick’ll die,” the captain said.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sullivan held up one of the sticks. The rest were concealed in his hand so[m
[31m- that no one could see whether it was the short stick or not.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ whose stick will it be?” Sullivan demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “For little Johnny Sheehan,” O’Brien answered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sullivan laid the stick aside. Those who looked could not tell if it were[m
[31m- the fatal one. Sullivan held up another stick.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Whose will it be?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “For George Burns,” was the reply.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The stick was laid with the first one, and a third held up.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ whose is this wan?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “For myself,” said O’Brien.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- With a quick movement, Sullivan threw the four sticks together. No one had[m
[31m- seen.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis for yourself ye’ve drawn it,” Sullivan announced.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A good deed,” several of the men muttered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- O’Brien was very quiet. He arose to his feet, took the bandage off, and[m
[31m- looked around.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Where is ut?” he demanded. “The short stick? The wan for me?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The captain pointed to the four sticks lying on the deck.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How do you know the stick was mine?” O’Brien questioned. “Did you see ut,[m
[31m- Johnny Sheehan?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny Sheehan, who was the youngest of the boys, did not answer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Did you see ut?” O’Brien next asked Mahoney.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “No, I didn’t see ut.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The men were muttering and growling.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Twas a fair drawin’,” Sullivan said. “Ye had yer chanct an’ ye lost,[m
[31m- that’s all iv ut.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “A fair drawin’,” the captain added. “Didn’t I behold it myself? The stick[m
[31m- was yours, O’Brien, an’ ye may as well get ready. Where’s the cook?[m
[31m- Gorman, come here. Fetch the tureen cover, some of ye. Gorman, do your[m
[31m- duty like a man.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “But how’ll I do it,” the cook demanded. He was a weak-eyed, weak-chinned,[m
[31m- indecisive man.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis a damned murder!” O’Brien cried out.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll have none of ut,” Mahoney announced. “Not a bite shall pass me[m
[31m- lips.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Then ’tis yer share for better men than yerself,” Sullivan sneered. “Go[m
[31m- on with yer duty, cook.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis not me duty, the killin’ of b’ys,” Gorman protested irresolutely.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If yez don’t make mate for us, we’ll be makin’ mate of yerself,” Behane[m
[31m- threatened. “Somebody must die, an’ as well you as another.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Johnny Sheehan began to cry. O’Brien listened anxiously. His face was[m
[31m- pale. His lips trembled, and at times his whole body shook.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I signed on as cook,” Gorman enounced. “An’ cook I wud if galley there[m
[31m- was. But I’ll not lay me hand to murder. ’Tis not in the articles. I’m the[m
[31m- cook⁠—”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ cook ye’ll be for wan minute more only,” Sullivan said grimly, at the[m
[31m- same moment gripping the cook’s head from behind and bending it back till[m
[31m- the windpipe and jugular were stretched taut. “Where’s yer knife, Mike?[m
[31m- Pass it along.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At the touch of the steel, Gorman whimpered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll do ut, if yez’ll hold the b’y.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The pitiable condition of the cook seemed in some fashion to nerve up[m
[31m- O’Brien.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “It’s all right, Gorman,” he said. “Go on with ut. ’Tis meself knows yer[m
[31m- not wantin’ to do ut. It’s all right, sir”⁠—this to the captain, who[m
[31m- had laid a hand heavily on his arm. “Ye won’t have to hold me, sir. I’ll[m
[31m- stand still.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Stop yer blitherin’, an’ go an’ get the tureen cover,” Behane commanded[m
[31m- Johnny Sheehan, at the same time dealing him a heavy cuff alongside the[m
[31m- head.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The boy, who was scarcely more than a child, fetched the cover. He crawled[m
[31m- and tottered along the deck, so weak was he from hunger. The tears still[m
[31m- ran down his cheeks. Behane took the cover from him, at the same time[m
[31m- administering another cuff.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- O’Brien took off his coat and bared his right arm. His under lip still[m
[31m- trembled, but he held a tight grip on himself. The captain’s penknife was[m
[31m- opened and passed to Gorman.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Mahoney, tell me mother what happened to me, if ever ye get back,”[m
[31m- O’Brien requested.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Mahoney nodded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis black murder, black an’ damned,” he said. “The b’y’s flesh’ll do[m
[31m- none iv yez anny good. Mark me words. Ye’ll not profit by it, none iv[m
[31m- yez.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Get ready,” the captain ordered. “You, Sullivan, hold the cover⁠—that’s[m
[31m- it⁠—close up. Spill nothing. It’s precious stuff.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Gorman made an effort. The knife was dull. He was weak. Besides, his hand[m
[31m- was shaking so violently that he nearly dropped the knife. The three boys[m
[31m- were crouched apart, in a huddle, crying and sobbing. With the exception[m
[31m- of Mahoney, the men were gathered about the victim, craning their necks to[m
[31m- see.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Be a man, Gorman,” the captain cautioned.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The wretched cook was seized with a spasm of resolution, sawing back and[m
[31m- forth with the blade on O’Brien’s wrist. The veins were severed. Sullivan[m
[31m- held the tureen cover close underneath. The cut veins gaped wide, but no[m
[31m- ruddy flood gushed forth. There was no blood at all. The veins were dry[m
[31m- and empty. No one spoke. The grim and silent figures swayed in unison with[m
[31m- each heave of the ship. Every eye was turned fixedly upon that[m
[31m- inconceivable and monstrous thing, the dry veins of a creature that was[m
[31m- alive.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis a warnin’,” Mahoney cried. “Lave the b’y alone. Mark me words. His[m
[31m- death’ll do none iv yez anny good.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Try at the elbow⁠—the left elbow, ’tis nearer the heart,” the[m
[31m- captain said finally, in a dim and husky voice that was unlike his own.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Give me the knife,” O’Brien said roughly, taking it out of the cook’s[m
[31m- hand. “I can’t be lookin’ at ye puttin’ me to hurt.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Quite coolly he cut the vein at the left elbow, but, like the cook, he[m
[31m- failed to bring blood.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “This is all iv no use,” Sullivan said. “ ’Tis better to put him out iv his[m
[31m- misery by bleedin’ him at the throat.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The strain had been too much for the lad.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Don’t be doin’ ut,” he cried. “There’ll be no blood in me throat. Give me[m
[31m- a little time. ’Tis cold an’ weak I am. Be lettin’ me lay down an’ slape a[m
[31m- bit. Then I’ll be warm an’ the blood’ll flow.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis no use,” Sullivan objected. “As if ye cud be slapin’ at a time like[m
[31m- this. Ye’ll not slape, and ye’ll not warm up. Look at ye now. You’ve an[m
[31m- ague.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I was sick at Limerick wan night,” O’Brien hurried on, “an’ the dochtor[m
[31m- cudn’t bleed me. But after slapin’ a few hours an’ gettin’ warm in bed the[m
[31m- blood came freely. It’s God’s truth I’m tellin’ yez. Don’t be murderin’[m
[31m- me!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “His veins are open now,” the captain said. “ ’Tis no use leavin’ him in[m
[31m- his pain. Do it now an’ be done with it.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They started to reach for O’Brien, but he backed away.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I’ll be the death iv yez!” he screamed. “Take yer hands off iv me,[m
[31m- Sullivan! I’ll come back! I’ll haunt yez! Wakin’ or slapin’, I’ll haunt[m
[31m- yez till you die!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “ ’Tis disgraceful!” yelled Behane. “If the short stick’d ben mine, I’d[m
[31m- a-let me mates cut the head off iv me an’ died happy.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sullivan leaped in and caught the unhappy lad by the hair. The rest of the[m
[31m- men followed, O’Brien kicked and struggled, snarling and snapping at the[m
[31m- hands that clutched him from every side. Little Johnny Sheehan broke out[m
[31m- into wild screaming, but the men took no notice of him. O’Brien was bent[m
[31m- backward to the deck, the tureen cover under his neck. Gorman was shoved[m
[31m- forward. Some one had thrust a large sheath-knife into his hand.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Do yer duty! Do yer duty!” the men cried.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The cook bent over, but he caught the boy’s eyes and faltered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If ye don’t, I’ll kill ye with me own hands,” Behane shouted.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- From every side a torrent of abuse and threats poured in upon the cook.[m
[31m- Still he hung back.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Maybe there’ll be more blood in his veins than O’Brien’s,” Sullivan[m
[31m- suggested significantly.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Behane caught Gorman by the hair and twisted his head back, while Sullivan[m
[31m- attempted to take possession of the sheath-knife. But Gorman clung to it[m
[31m- desperately.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Lave go, an’ I’ll do ut!” he screamed frantically. “Don’t be cuttin’ me[m
[31m- throat! I’ll do the deed! I’ll do the deed!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “See that you do it, then,” the captain threatened him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Gorman allowed himself to be shoved forward. He looked at the boy, closed[m
[31m- his eyes, and muttered a prayer. Then, without opening his eyes, he did[m
[31m- the deed that had been appointed him. O’Brien emitted a shriek that sank[m
[31m- swiftly to a gurgling sob. The men held him till his struggles ceased,[m
[31m- when he was laid upon the deck. They were eager and impatient, and with[m
[31m- oaths and threats they urged Gorman to hurry with the preparation of the[m
[31m- meal.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Lave ut, you bloody butchers,” Mahoney said quietly. “Lave ut, I tell[m
[31m- yez. Ye’ll not be needin’ anny iv ut now. ’Tis as I said: ye’ll not be[m
[31m- profitin’ by the lad’s blood. Empty ut overside, Behane. Empty ut[m
[31m- overside.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Behane, still holding the tureen cover in both his hands, glanced to[m
[31m- windward. He walked to the rail and threw the cover and contents into the[m
[31m- sea. A full-rigged ship was bearing down upon them a short mile away. So[m
[31m- occupied had they been with the deed just committed, that none had had[m
[31m- eyes for a lookout. All hands watched her coming on⁠—the brightly[m
[31m- coppered forefoot parting the water like a golden knife, the headsails[m
[31m- flapping lazily and emptily at each downward surge, and the towering[m
[31m- canvas tiers dipping and curtsying with each stately swing of the sea. No[m
[31m- man spoke.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- As she hove to, a cable length away, the captain of the Francis Spaight[m
[31m- bestirred himself and ordered a tarpaulin to be thrown over O’Brien’s[m
[31m- corpse. A boat was lowered from the stranger’s side and began to pull[m
[31m- toward them. John Gorman laughed. He laughed softly at first, but he[m
[31m- accompanied each stroke of the oars with spasmodically increasing glee. It[m
[31m- was this maniacal laughter that greeted the rescue boat as it hauled[m
[31m- alongside and the first officer clambered on board.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0010" name="link2H_4_0010">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- A CURIOUS FRAGMENT[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<pre xml:space="preserve">[m
[31m- [The capitalist, or industrial oligarch, Roger Vanderwater,[m
[31m- mentioned in the narrative, has been identified as the ninth[m
[31m- in the line of the Vanderwaters that controlled for hundreds[m
[31m- of years the cotton factories of the South. This Roger[m
[31m- Vanderwater flourished in the last decades of the twenty-[m
[31m- sixth century after Christ, which was the fifth century of[m
[31m- the terrible industrial oligarchy that was reared upon the[m
[31m- ruins of the early Republic.[m
[31m-[m
[31m- From internal evidences we are convinced that the narrative[m
[31m- which follows was not reduced to writing till the twenty-[m
[31m- ninth century. Not only was it unlawful to write or print[m
[31m- such matter during that period, but the working-class was so[m
[31m- illiterate that only in rare instances were its members able[m
[31m- to read and write. This was the dark reign of the overman,[m
[31m- in whose speech the great mass of the people were[m
[31m- characterized as the “herd animals.” All literacy was[m
[31m- frowned upon and stamped out. From the statute-books of the[m
[31m- times may be instanced that black law that made it a capital[m
[31m- offence for any man, no matter of what class, to teach even[m
[31m- the alphabet to a member of the working-class. Such[m
[31m- stringent limitation of education to the ruling class was[m
[31m- necessary if that class was to continue to rule.[m
[31m-[m
[31m- One result of the foregoing was the development of the[m
[31m- professional story-tellers. These story-tellers were paid by[m
[31m- the oligarchy, and the tales they told were legendary,[m
[31m- mythical, romantic, and harmless. But the spirit of freedom[m
[31m- never quite died out, and agitators, under the guise of[m
[31m- story-tellers, preached revolt to the slave class. That the[m
[31m- following tale was banned by the oligarchs we have proof[m
[31m- from the records of the criminal police court of Ashbury,[m
[31m- wherein, on January 27, 2734, one John Tourney, found guilty[m
[31m- of telling the tale in a boozing-ken of labourers, was[m
[31m- sentenced to five years’ penal servitude in the borax mines[m
[31m- of the Arizona Desert.⁠—EDITOR’S NOTE.][m
[31m-</pre>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Listen, my brothers, and I will tell you a tale of an arm. It was the arm[m
[31m- of Tom Dixon, and Tom Dixon was a weaver of the first class in a factory[m
[31m- of that hell-hound and master, Roger Vanderwater. This factory was called[m
[31m- “Hell’s Bottom” … by the slaves who toiled in it, and I guess they ought[m
[31m- to know; and it was situated in Kingsbury, at the other end of the town[m
[31m- from Vanderwater’s summer palace. You do not know where Kingsbury is?[m
[31m- There are many things, my brothers, that you do not know, and it is sad.[m
[31m- It is because you do not know that you are slaves. When I have told you[m
[31m- this tale, I should like to form a class among you for the learning of[m
[31m- written and printed speech. Our masters read and write and possess many[m
[31m- books, and it is because of that that they are our masters, and live in[m
[31m- palaces, and do not work. When the toilers learn to read and write⁠—all[m
[31m- of them⁠—they will grow strong; then they will use their strength to[m
[31m- break their bonds, and there will be no more masters and no more slaves.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Kingsbury, my brothers, is in the old State of Alabama. For three hundred[m
[31m- years the Vanderwaters have owned Kingsbury and its slave pens and[m
[31m- factories, and slave pens and factories in many other places and States.[m
[31m- You have heard of the Vanderwaters⁠—who has not?⁠—but let me[m
[31m- tell you things you do not know about them. The first Vanderwater was a[m
[31m- slave, even as you and I. Have you got that? He was a slave, and that was[m
[31m- over three hundred years ago. His father was a machinist in the slave pen[m
[31m- of Alexander Burrell, and his mother was a washerwoman in the same slave[m
[31m- pen. There is no doubt about this. I am telling you truth. It is history.[m
[31m- It is printed, every word of it, in the history books of our masters,[m
[31m- which you cannot read because your masters will not permit you to learn to[m
[31m- read. You can understand why they will not permit you to learn to read,[m
[31m- when there are such things in the books. They know, and they are very[m
[31m- wise. If you did read such things, you might be wanting in respect to your[m
[31m- masters, which would be a dangerous thing … to your masters. But I know,[m
[31m- for I can read, and I am telling you what I have read with my own eyes in[m
[31m- the history books of our masters.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The first Vanderwater’s name was not Vanderwater; it was Vange⁠—Bill[m
[31m- Vange, the son of Yergis Vange, the machinist, and Laura Carnly, the[m
[31m- washerwoman. Young Bill Vange was strong. He might have remained with the[m
[31m- slaves and led them to freedom; instead, however, he served the masters[m
[31m- and was well rewarded. He began his service, when yet a small child, as a[m
[31m- spy in his home slave pen. He is known to have informed on his own father[m
[31m- for seditious utterance. This is fact. I have read it with my own eyes in[m
[31m- the records. He was too good a slave for the slave pen. Alexander Burrell[m
[31m- took him out, while yet a child, and he was taught to read and write. He[m
[31m- was taught many things, and he was entered in the secret service of the[m
[31m- Government. Of course, he no longer wore the slave dress, except for[m
[31m- disguise at such times when he sought to penetrate the secrets and plots[m
[31m- of the slaves. It was he, when but eighteen years of age, who brought that[m
[31m- great hero and comrade, Ralph Jacobus, to trial and execution in the[m
[31m- electric chair. Of course, you have all heard the sacred name of Ralph[m
[31m- Jacobus, but it is news to you that he was brought to his death by the[m
[31m- first Vanderwater, whose name was Vange. I know. I have read it in the[m
[31m- books. There are many interesting things like that in the books.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And after Ralph Jacobus died his shameful death, Bill Vange’s name began[m
[31m- the many changes it was to undergo. He was known as “Sly Vange” far and[m
[31m- wide. He rose high in the secret service, and he was rewarded in grand[m
[31m- ways, but still he was not a member of the master class. The men were[m
[31m- willing that he should become so; it was the women of the master class who[m
[31m- refused to have Sly Vange one of them. Sly Vange gave good service to the[m
[31m- masters. He had been a slave himself, and he knew the ways of the slaves.[m
[31m- There was no fooling him. In those days the slaves were braver than now,[m
[31m- and they were always trying for their freedom. And Sly Vange was[m
[31m- everywhere, in all their schemes and plans, bringing their schemes and[m
[31m- plans to naught and their leaders to the electric chair. It was in 2255[m
[31m- that his name was next changed for him. It was in that year that the Great[m
[31m- Mutiny took place. In that region west of the Rocky Mountains, seventeen[m
[31m- millions of slaves strove bravely to overthrow their masters. Who knows,[m
[31m- if Sly Vange had not lived, but that they would have succeeded? But Sly[m
[31m- Vange was very much alive. The masters gave him supreme command of the[m
[31m- situation. In eight months of fighting, one million and three hundred and[m
[31m- fifty thousand slaves were killed. Vange, Bill Vange, Sly Vange, killed[m
[31m- them, and he broke the Great Mutiny. And he was greatly rewarded, and so[m
[31m- red were his hands with the blood of the slaves that thereafter he was[m
[31m- called “Bloody Vange.” You see, my brothers, what interesting things are[m
[31m- to be found in the books when one can read them. And, take my word for it,[m
[31m- there are many other things, even more interesting, in the books. And if[m
[31m- you will but study with me, in a year’s time you can read those books for[m
[31m- yourselves⁠—ay, in six months some of you will be able to read those[m
[31m- books for yourselves.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Bloody Vange lived to a ripe old age, and always, to the last, was he[m
[31m- received in the councils of the masters; but never was he made a master[m
[31m- himself. He had first opened his eyes, you see, in a slave pen. But oh, he[m
[31m- was well rewarded! He had a dozen palaces in which to live. He, who was no[m
[31m- master, owned thousands of slaves. He had a great pleasure yacht upon the[m
[31m- sea that was a floating palace, and he owned a whole island in the sea[m
[31m- where toiled ten thousand slaves on his coffee plantations. But in his old[m
[31m- age he was lonely, for he lived apart, hated by his brothers, the slaves,[m
[31m- and looked down upon by those he had served and who refused to be his[m
[31m- brothers. The masters looked down upon him because he had been born a[m
[31m- slave. Enormously wealthy he died; but he died horribly, tormented by his[m
[31m- conscience, regretting all he had done and the red stain on his name.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But with his children it was different. They had not been born in the[m
[31m- slave pen, and by the special ruling of the Chief Oligarch of that time,[m
[31m- John Morrison, they were elevated to the master class. And it was then[m
[31m- that the name of Vange disappears from the page of history. It becomes[m
[31m- Vanderwater, and Jason Vange, the son of Bloody Vange, becomes Jason[m
[31m- Vanderwater, the founder of the Vanderwater line. But that was three[m
[31m- hundred years ago, and the Vanderwaters of to-day forget their beginnings[m
[31m- and imagine that somehow the clay of their bodies is different stuff from[m
[31m- the clay in your body and mine and in the bodies of all slaves. And I ask[m
[31m- you, Why should a slave become the master of another slave? And why should[m
[31m- the son of a slave become the master of many slaves? I leave these[m
[31m- questions for you to answer for yourselves, but do not forget that in the[m
[31m- beginning the Vanderwaters were slaves.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And now, my brothers, I come back to the beginning of my tale to tell you[m
[31m- of Tom Dixon’s arm. Roger Vanderwater’s factory in Kingsbury was rightly[m
[31m- named “Hell’s Bottom,” but the men who toiled in it were men, as you shall[m
[31m- see. Women toiled there, too, and children, little children. All that[m
[31m- toiled there had the regular slave rights under the law, but only under[m
[31m- the law, for they were deprived of many of their rights by the two[m
[31m- overseers of Hell’s Bottom, Joseph Clancy and Adolph Munster.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It is a long story, but I shall not tell all of it to you. I shall tell[m
[31m- only about the arm. It happened that, according to the law, a portion of[m
[31m- the starvation wage of the slaves was held back each month and put into a[m
[31m- fund. This fund was for the purpose of helping such unfortunate[m
[31m- fellow-workmen as happened to be injured by accidents or to be overtaken[m
[31m- by sickness. As you know with yourselves, these funds are controlled by[m
[31m- the overseers. It is the law, and so it was that the fund at Hell’s Bottom[m
[31m- was controlled by the two overseers of accursed memory.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Now, Clancy and Munster took this fund for their own use. When accidents[m
[31m- happened to the workmen, their fellows, as was the custom, made grants[m
[31m- from the fund; but the overseers refused to pay over the grants. What[m
[31m- could the slaves do? They had their rights under the law, but they had no[m
[31m- access to the law. Those that complained to the overseers were punished.[m
[31m- You know yourselves what form such punishment takes⁠—the fines for[m
[31m- faulty work that is not faulty; the overcharging of accounts in the[m
[31m- Company’s store; the vile treatment of one’s women and children; and the[m
[31m- allotment to bad machines whereon, work as one will, he starves.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Once, the slaves of Hell’s Bottom protested to Vanderwater. It was the[m
[31m- time of the year when he spent several months in Kingsbury. One of the[m
[31m- slaves could write; it chanced that his mother could write, and she had[m
[31m- secretly taught him as her mother had secretly taught her. So this slave[m
[31m- wrote a round robin, wherein was contained their grievances, and all the[m
[31m- slaves signed by mark. And, with proper stamps upon the envelope, the[m
[31m- round robin was mailed to Roger Vanderwater. And Roger Vanderwater did[m
[31m- nothing, save to turn the round robin over to the two overseers. Clancy[m
[31m- and Munster were angered. They turned the guards loose at night on the[m
[31m- slave pen. The guards were armed with pick handles. It is said that next[m
[31m- day only half of the slaves were able to work in Hell’s Bottom. They were[m
[31m- well beaten. The slave who could write was so badly beaten that he lived[m
[31m- only three months. But before he died, he wrote once more, to what purpose[m
[31m- you shall hear.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Four or five weeks afterward, Tom Dixon, a slave, had his arm torn off by[m
[31m- a belt in Hell’s Bottom. His fellow-workmen, as usual, made a grant to him[m
[31m- from the fund, and Clancy and Munster, as usual, refused to pay it over[m
[31m- from the fund. The slave who could write, and who even then was dying,[m
[31m- wrote anew a recital of their grievances. And this document was thrust[m
[31m- into the hand of the arm that had been torn from Tom Dixon’s body.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Now it chanced that Roger Vanderwater was lying ill in his palace at the[m
[31m- other end of Kingsbury⁠—not the dire illness that strikes down you[m
[31m- and me, brothers; just a bit of biliousness, mayhap, or no more than a bad[m
[31m- headache because he had eaten too heartily or drunk too deeply. But it was[m
[31m- enough for him, being tender and soft from careful rearing. Such men,[m
[31m- packed in cotton wool all their lives, are exceeding tender and soft.[m
[31m- Believe me, brothers, Roger Vanderwater felt as badly with his aching[m
[31m- head, or THOUGHT he felt as badly, as Tom Dixon really felt with his arm[m
[31m- torn out by the roots.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It happened that Roger Vanderwater was fond of scientific farming, and[m
[31m- that on his farm, three miles outside of Kingsbury, he had managed to grow[m
[31m- a new kind of strawberry. He was very proud of that new strawberry of his,[m
[31m- and he would have been out to see and pick the first ripe ones, had it not[m
[31m- been for his illness. Because of his illness he had ordered the old farm[m
[31m- slave to bring in personally the first box of the berries. All this was[m
[31m- learned from the gossip of a palace scullion, who slept each night in the[m
[31m- slave pen. The overseer of the plantation should have brought in the[m
[31m- berries, but he was on his back with a broken leg from trying to break a[m
[31m- colt. The scullion brought the word in the night, and it was known that[m
[31m- next day the berries would come in. And the men in the slave pen of Hell’s[m
[31m- Bottom, being men and not cowards, held a council.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The slave who could write, and who was sick and dying from the pick-handle[m
[31m- beating, said he would carry Tom Dixon’s arm; also, he said he must die[m
[31m- anyway, and that it mattered nothing if he died a little sooner. So five[m
[31m- slaves stole from the slave pen that night after the guards had made their[m
[31m- last rounds. One of the slaves was the man who could write. They lay in[m
[31m- the brush by the roadside until late in the morning, when the old farm[m
[31m- slave came driving to town with the precious fruit for the master. What of[m
[31m- the farm slave being old and rheumatic, and of the slave who could write[m
[31m- being stiff and injured from his beating, they moved their bodies about[m
[31m- when they walked, very much in the same fashion. The slave who could write[m
[31m- put on the other’s clothes, pulled the broad-brimmed hat over his eyes,[m
[31m- climbed upon the seat of the wagon, and drove on to town. The old farm[m
[31m- slave was kept tied all day in the bushes until evening, when the others[m
[31m- loosed him and went back to the slave pen to take their punishment for[m
[31m- having broken bounds.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- In the meantime, Roger Vanderwater lay waiting for the berries in his[m
[31m- wonderful bedroom⁠—such wonders and such comforts were there that[m
[31m- they would have blinded the eyes of you and me who have never seen such[m
[31m- things. The slave who could write said afterward that it was like a[m
[31m- glimpse of Paradise! And why not? The labour and the lives of ten thousand[m
[31m- slaves had gone to the making of that bedchamber, while they themselves[m
[31m- slept in vile lairs like wild beasts. The slave who could write brought in[m
[31m- the berries on a silver tray or platter⁠—you see, Roger Vanderwater[m
[31m- wanted to speak with him in person about the berries.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The slave who could write tottered his dying body across the wonderful[m
[31m- room and knelt by the couch of Vanderwater, holding out before him the[m
[31m- tray. Large green leaves covered the top of the tray, and these the[m
[31m- body-servant alongside whisked away so that Vanderwater could see. And[m
[31m- Roger Vanderwater, propped upon his elbow, saw. He saw the fresh,[m
[31m- wonderful fruit lying there like precious jewels, and in the midst of it[m
[31m- the arm of Tom Dixon as it had been torn from his body, well washed, of[m
[31m- course, my brothers, and very white against the blood-red fruit. And also[m
[31m- he saw, clutched in the stiff, dead fingers, the petition of his slaves[m
[31m- who toiled in Hell’s Bottom.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Take and read,” said the slave who could write. And even as the master[m
[31m- took the petition, the body-servant, who till then had been motionless[m
[31m- with surprise, struck with his fist the kneeling slave upon the mouth. The[m
[31m- slave was dying anyway, and was very weak, and did not mind. He made no[m
[31m- sound, and, having fallen over on his side, he lay there quietly, bleeding[m
[31m- from the blow on the mouth. The physician, who had run for the palace[m
[31m- guards, came back with them, and the slave was dragged upright upon his[m
[31m- feet. But as they dragged him up, his hand clutched Tom Dixon’s arm from[m
[31m- where it had fallen on the floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “He shall be flung alive to the hounds!” the body-servant was crying in[m
[31m- great wrath. “He shall be flung alive to the hounds!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But Roger Vanderwater, forgetting his headache, still leaning on his[m
[31m- elbow, commanded silence, and went on reading the petition. And while he[m
[31m- read, there was silence, all standing upright, the wrathful body-servant,[m
[31m- the physician, the palace guards, and in their midst the slave, bleeding[m
[31m- at the mouth and still holding Tom Dixon’s arm. And when Roger Vanderwater[m
[31m- had done, he turned upon the slave, saying⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “If in this paper there be one lie, you shall be sorry that you were ever[m
[31m- born.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And the slave said, “I have been sorry all my life that I was born.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Roger Vanderwater looked at him closely, and the slave said⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “You have done your worst to me. I am dying now. In a week I shall be[m
[31m- dead, so it does not matter if you kill me now.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What do you with that?” the master asked, pointing to the arm; and the[m
[31m- slave made answer⁠—</p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I take it back to the pen to give it burial. Tom Dixon was my friend. We[m
[31m- worked beside each other at our looms.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- There is little more to my tale, brothers. The slave and the arm were sent[m
[31m- back in a cart to the pen. Nor were any of the slaves punished for what[m
[31m- they had done. Indeed, Roger Vanderwater made investigation and punished[m
[31m- the two overseers, Joseph Clancy and Adolph Munster. Their freeholds were[m
[31m- taken from them. They were branded, each upon the forehead, their right[m
[31m- hands were cut off, and they were turned loose upon the highway to wander[m
[31m- and beg until they died. And the fund was managed rightfully thereafter[m
[31m- for a time⁠—for a time only, my brothers; for after Roger Vanderwater[m
[31m- came his son, Albert, who was a cruel master and half mad.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Brothers, that slave who carried the arm into the presence of the master[m
[31m- was my father. He was a brave man. And even as his mother secretly taught[m
[31m- him to read, so did he teach me. Because he died shortly after from the[m
[31m- pick-handle beating, Roger Vanderwater took me out of the slave pen and[m
[31m- tried to make various better things out of me. I might have become an[m
[31m- overseer in Hell’s Bottom, but I chose to become a story-teller, wandering[m
[31m- over the land and getting close to my brothers, the slaves, everywhere.[m
[31m- And I tell you stories like this, secretly, knowing that you will not[m
[31m- betray me; for if you did, you know as well as I that my tongue will be[m
[31m- torn out and that I shall tell stories no more. And my message is,[m
[31m- brothers, that there is a good time coming, when all will be well in the[m
[31m- world and there will be neither masters nor slaves. But first you must[m
[31m- prepare for that good time by learning to read. There is power in the[m
[31m- printed word. And here am I to teach you to read, and as well there are[m
[31m- others to see that you get the books when I am gone along upon my way⁠—the[m
[31m- history books wherein you will learn about your masters, and learn to[m
[31m- become strong even as they.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- [EDITOR’S NOTE.⁠—From “Historical Fragments and Sketches,” first[m
[31m- published in fifty volumes in 4427, and now, after two hundred years,[m
[31m- because of its accuracy and value, edited and republished by the National[m
[31m- Committee on Historical Research.][m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m-<a id="link2H_4_0011" name="link2H_4_0011">[m
[31m-<!-- H2 anchor --> </a>[m
[31m-</p>[m
[31m-<div style="height: 4em;">[m
[31m-<br/><br/><br/><br/>[m
[31m-</div>[m
[31m-<h2>[m
[31m- A PIECE OF STEAK[m
[31m- </h2>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- With the last morsel of bread Tom King wiped his plate clean of the last[m
[31m- particle of flour gravy and chewed the resulting mouthful in a slow and[m
[31m- meditative way. When he arose from the table, he was oppressed by the[m
[31m- feeling that he was distinctly hungry. Yet he alone had eaten. The two[m
[31m- children in the other room had been sent early to bed in order that in[m
[31m- sleep they might forget they had gone supperless. His wife had touched[m
[31m- nothing, and had sat silently and watched him with solicitous eyes. She[m
[31m- was a thin, worn woman of the working-class, though signs of an earlier[m
[31m- prettiness were not wanting in her face. The flour for the gravy she had[m
[31m- borrowed from the neighbour across the hall. The last two ha’pennies had[m
[31m- gone to buy the bread.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He sat down by the window on a rickety chair that protested under his[m
[31m- weight, and quite mechanically he put his pipe in his mouth and dipped[m
[31m- into the side pocket of his coat. The absence of any tobacco made him[m
[31m- aware of his action, and, with a scowl for his forgetfulness, he put the[m
[31m- pipe away. His movements were slow, almost hulking, as though he were[m
[31m- burdened by the heavy weight of his muscles. He was a solid-bodied,[m
[31m- stolid-looking man, and his appearance did not suffer from being[m
[31m- overprepossessing. His rough clothes were old and slouchy. The uppers of[m
[31m- his shoes were too weak to carry the heavy re-soling that was itself of no[m
[31m- recent date. And his cotton shirt, a cheap, two shilling affair, showed a[m
[31m- frayed collar and ineradicable paint stains.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- But it was Tom King’s face that advertised him unmistakably for what he[m
[31m- was. It was the face of a typical prize-fighter; of one who had put in[m
[31m- long years of service in the squared ring and, by that means, developed[m
[31m- and emphasized all the marks of the fighting beast. It was distinctly a[m
[31m- lowering countenance, and, that no feature of it might escape notice, it[m
[31m- was clean-shaven. The lips were shapeless and constituted a mouth harsh to[m
[31m- excess, that was like a gash in his face. The jaw was aggressive, brutal,[m
[31m- heavy. The eyes, slow of movement and heavy-lidded, were almost[m
[31m- expressionless under the shaggy, indrawn brows. Sheer animal that he was,[m
[31m- the eyes were the most animal-like feature about him. They were sleepy,[m
[31m- lion-like⁠—the eyes of a fighting animal. The forehead slanted[m
[31m- quickly back to the hair, which, clipped close, showed every bump of a[m
[31m- villainous-looking head. A nose twice broken and moulded variously by[m
[31m- countless blows, and a cauliflower ear, permanently swollen and distorted[m
[31m- to twice its size, completed his adornment, while the beard, fresh-shaven[m
[31m- as it was, sprouted in the skin and gave the face a blue-black stain.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Altogether, it was the face of a man to be afraid of in a dark alley or[m
[31m- lonely place. And yet Tom King was not a criminal, nor had he ever done[m
[31m- anything criminal. Outside of brawls, common to his walk in life, he had[m
[31m- harmed no one. Nor had he ever been known to pick a quarrel. He was a[m
[31m- professional, and all the fighting brutishness of him was reserved for his[m
[31m- professional appearances. Outside the ring he was slow-going,[m
[31m- easy-natured, and, in his younger days, when money was flush, too[m
[31m- open-handed for his own good. He bore no grudges and had few enemies.[m
[31m- Fighting was a business with him. In the ring he struck to hurt, struck to[m
[31m- maim, struck to destroy; but there was no animus in it. It was a plain[m
[31m- business proposition. Audiences assembled and paid for the spectacle of[m
[31m- men knocking each other out. The winner took the big end of the purse.[m
[31m- When Tom King faced the Woolloomoolloo Gouger, twenty years before, he[m
[31m- knew that the Gouger’s jaw was only four months healed after having been[m
[31m- broken in a Newcastle bout. And he had played for that jaw and broken it[m
[31m- again in the ninth round, not because he bore the Gouger any ill-will, but[m
[31m- because that was the surest way to put the Gouger out and win the big end[m
[31m- of the purse. Nor had the Gouger borne him any ill-will for it. It was the[m
[31m- game, and both knew the game and played it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Tom King had never been a talker, and he sat by the window, morosely[m
[31m- silent, staring at his hands. The veins stood out on the backs of the[m
[31m- hands, large and swollen; and the knuckles, smashed and battered and[m
[31m- malformed, testified to the use to which they had been put. He had never[m
[31m- heard that a man’s life was the life of his arteries, but well he knew the[m
[31m- meaning of those big upstanding veins. His heart had pumped too much blood[m
[31m- through them at top pressure. They no longer did the work. He had[m
[31m- stretched the elasticity out of them, and with their distension had passed[m
[31m- his endurance. He tired easily now. No longer could he do a fast twenty[m
[31m- rounds, hammer and tongs, fight, fight, fight, from gong to gong, with[m
[31m- fierce rally on top of fierce rally, beaten to the ropes and in turn[m
[31m- beating his opponent to the ropes, and rallying fiercest and fastest of[m
[31m- all in that last, twentieth round, with the house on its feet and yelling,[m
[31m- himself rushing, striking, ducking, raining showers of blows upon showers[m
[31m- of blows and receiving showers of blows in return, and all the time the[m
[31m- heart faithfully pumping the surging blood through the adequate veins. The[m
[31m- veins, swollen at the time, had always shrunk down again, though each[m
[31m- time, imperceptibly at first, not quite⁠—remaining just a trifle[m
[31m- larger than before. He stared at them and at his battered knuckles, and,[m
[31m- for the moment, caught a vision of the youthful excellence of those hands[m
[31m- before the first knuckle had been smashed on the head of Benny Jones,[m
[31m- otherwise known as the Welsh Terror.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The impression of his hunger came back on him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Blimey, but couldn’t I go a piece of steak!” he muttered aloud, clenching[m
[31m- his huge fists and spitting out a smothered oath.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I tried both Burke’s an’ Sawley’s,” his wife said half apologetically.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ they wouldn’t?” he demanded.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Not a ha’penny. Burke said⁠—” She faltered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “G’wan! Wot’d he say?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “As how ‘e was thinkin’ Sandel ud do ye to-night, an’ as how yer score was[m
[31m- comfortable big as it was.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Tom King grunted, but did not reply. He was busy thinking of the bull[m
[31m- terrier he had kept in his younger days to which he had fed steaks without[m
[31m- end. Burke would have given him credit for a thousand steaks⁠—then.[m
[31m- But times had changed. Tom King was getting old; and old men, fighting[m
[31m- before second-rate clubs, couldn’t expect to run bills of any size with[m
[31m- the tradesmen.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He had got up in the morning with a longing for a piece of steak, and the[m
[31m- longing had not abated. He had not had a fair training for this fight. It[m
[31m- was a drought year in Australia, times were hard, and even the most[m
[31m- irregular work was difficult to find. He had had no sparring partner, and[m
[31m- his food had not been of the best nor always sufficient. He had done a few[m
[31m- days’ navvy work when he could get it, and he had run around the Domain in[m
[31m- the early mornings to get his legs in shape. But it was hard, training[m
[31m- without a partner and with a wife and two kiddies that must be fed. Credit[m
[31m- with the tradesmen had undergone very slight expansion when he was matched[m
[31m- with Sandel. The secretary of the Gayety Club had advanced him three[m
[31m- pounds⁠—the loser’s end of the purse⁠—and beyond that had[m
[31m- refused to go. Now and again he had managed to borrow a few shillings from[m
[31m- old pals, who would have lent more only that it was a drought year and[m
[31m- they were hard put themselves. No⁠—and there was no use in disguising[m
[31m- the fact⁠—his training had not been satisfactory. He should have had[m
[31m- better food and no worries. Besides, when a man is forty, it is harder to[m
[31m- get into condition than when he is twenty.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “What time is it, Lizzie?” he asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His wife went across the hall to inquire, and came back.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Quarter before eight.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “They’ll be startin’ the first bout in a few minutes,” he said. “Only a[m
[31m- try-out. Then there’s a four-round spar ’tween Dealer Wells an’ Gridley,[m
[31m- an’ a ten-round go ’tween Starlight an’ some sailor bloke. I don’t come on[m
[31m- for over an hour.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At the end of another silent ten minutes, he rose to his feet.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Truth is, Lizzie, I ain’t had proper trainin’.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He reached for his hat and started for the door. He did not offer to kiss[m
[31m- her⁠—he never did on going out⁠—but on this night she dared to[m
[31m- kiss him, throwing her arms around him and compelling him to bend down to[m
[31m- her face. She looked quite small against the massive bulk of the man.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Good luck, Tom,” she said. “You gotter do ’im.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Ay, I gotter do ’im,” he repeated. “That’s all there is to it. I jus’[m
[31m- gotter do ’im.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He laughed with an attempt at heartiness, while she pressed more closely[m
[31m- against him. Across her shoulders he looked around the bare room. It was[m
[31m- all he had in the world, with the rent overdue, and her and the kiddies.[m
[31m- And he was leaving it to go out into the night to get meat for his mate[m
[31m- and cubs⁠—not like a modern working-man going to his machine grind,[m
[31m- but in the old, primitive, royal, animal way, by fighting for it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “I gotter do ’im,” he repeated, this time a hint of desperation in his[m
[31m- voice. “If it’s a win, it’s thirty quid⁠—an’ I can pay all that’s[m
[31m- owin’, with a lump o’ money left over. If it’s a lose, I get naught⁠—not[m
[31m- even a penny for me to ride home on the tram. The secretary’s give all[m
[31m- that’s comin’ from a loser’s end. Good-bye, old woman. I’ll come straight[m
[31m- home if it’s a win.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “An’ I’ll be waitin’ up,” she called to him along the hall.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- It was full two miles to the Gayety, and as he walked along he remembered[m
[31m- how in his palmy days⁠—he had once been the heavyweight champion of[m
[31m- New South Wales⁠—he would have ridden in a cab to the fight, and how,[m
[31m- most likely, some heavy backer would have paid for the cab and ridden with[m
[31m- him. There were Tommy Burns and that Yankee nigger, Jack Johnson⁠—they[m
[31m- rode about in motor-cars. And he walked! And, as any man knew, a hard two[m
[31m- miles was not the best preliminary to a fight. He was an old un, and the[m
[31m- world did not wag well with old uns. He was good for nothing now except[m
[31m- navvy work, and his broken nose and swollen ear were against him even in[m
[31m- that. He found himself wishing that he had learned a trade. It would have[m
[31m- been better in the long run. But no one had told him, and he knew, deep[m
[31m- down in his heart, that he would not have listened if they had. It had[m
[31m- been so easy. Big money⁠—sharp, glorious fights⁠—periods of rest[m
[31m- and loafing in between⁠—a following of eager flatterers, the slaps on[m
[31m- the back, the shakes of the hand, the toffs glad to buy him a drink for[m
[31m- the privilege of five minutes’ talk⁠—and the glory of it, the yelling[m
[31m- houses, the whirlwind finish, the referee’s “King wins!” and his name in[m
[31m- the sporting columns next day.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Those had been times! But he realized now, in his slow, ruminating way,[m
[31m- that it was the old uns he had been putting away. He was Youth, rising;[m
[31m- and they were Age, sinking. No wonder it had been easy⁠—they with[m
[31m- their swollen veins and battered knuckles and weary in the bones of them[m
[31m- from the long battles they had already fought. He remembered the time he[m
[31m- put out old Stowsher Bill, at Rush-Cutters Bay, in the eighteenth round,[m
[31m- and how old Bill had cried afterward in the dressing-room like a baby.[m
[31m- Perhaps old Bill’s rent had been overdue. Perhaps he’d had at home a[m
[31m- missus an’ a couple of kiddies. And perhaps Bill, that very day of the[m
[31m- fight, had had a hungering for a piece of steak. Bill had fought game and[m
[31m- taken incredible punishment. He could see now, after he had gone through[m
[31m- the mill himself, that Stowsher Bill had fought for a bigger stake, that[m
[31m- night twenty years ago, than had young Tom King, who had fought for glory[m
[31m- and easy money. No wonder Stowsher Bill had cried afterward in the[m
[31m- dressing-room.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Well, a man had only so many fights in him, to begin with. It was the iron[m
[31m- law of the game. One man might have a hundred hard fights in him, another[m
[31m- man only twenty; each, according to the make of him and the quality of his[m
[31m- fibre, had a definite number, and, when he had fought them, he was done.[m
[31m- Yes, he had had more fights in him than most of them, and he had had far[m
[31m- more than his share of the hard, gruelling fights⁠—the kind that[m
[31m- worked the heart and lungs to bursting, that took the elastic out of the[m
[31m- arteries and made hard knots of muscle out of Youth’s sleek suppleness,[m
[31m- that wore out nerve and stamina and made brain and bones weary from excess[m
[31m- of effort and endurance overwrought. Yes, he had done better than all of[m
[31m- them. There were none of his old fighting partners left. He was the last[m
[31m- of the old guard. He had seen them all finished, and he had had a hand in[m
[31m- finishing some of them.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- They had tried him out against the old uns, and one after another he had[m
[31m- put them away⁠—laughing when, like old Stowsher Bill, they cried in[m
[31m- the dressing-room. And now he was an old un, and they tried out the[m
[31m- youngsters on him. There was that bloke, Sandel. He had come over from New[m
[31m- Zealand with a record behind him. But nobody in Australia knew anything[m
[31m- about him, so they put him up against old Tom King. If Sandel made a[m
[31m- showing, he would be given better men to fight, with bigger purses to win;[m
[31m- so it was to be depended upon that he would put up a fierce battle. He had[m
[31m- everything to win by it⁠—money and glory and career; and Tom King was[m
[31m- the grizzled old chopping-block that guarded the highway to fame and[m
[31m- fortune. And he had nothing to win except thirty quid, to pay to the[m
[31m- landlord and the tradesmen. And, as Tom King thus ruminated, there came to[m
[31m- his stolid vision the form of Youth, glorious Youth, rising exultant and[m
[31m- invincible, supple of muscle and silken of skin, with heart and lungs that[m
[31m- had never been tired and torn and that laughed at limitation of effort.[m
[31m- Yes, Youth was the Nemesis. It destroyed the old uns and recked not that,[m
[31m- in so doing, it destroyed itself. It enlarged its arteries and smashed its[m
[31m- knuckles, and was in turn destroyed by Youth. For Youth was ever youthful.[m
[31m- It was only Age that grew old.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At Castlereagh Street he turned to the left, and three blocks along came[m
[31m- to the Gayety. A crowd of young larrikins hanging outside the door made[m
[31m- respectful way for him, and he heard one say to another: “That’s ’im![m
[31m- That’s Tom King!”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Inside, on the way to his dressing-room, he encountered the secretary, a[m
[31m- keen-eyed, shrewd-faced young man, who shook his hand.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “How are you feelin’, Tom?” he asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Fit as a fiddle,” King answered, though he knew that he lied, and that if[m
[31m- he had a quid, he would give it right there for a good piece of steak.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- When he emerged from the dressing-room, his seconds behind him, and came[m
[31m- down the aisle to the squared ring in the centre of the hall, a burst of[m
[31m- greeting and applause went up from the waiting crowd. He acknowledged[m
[31m- salutations right and left, though few of the faces did he know. Most of[m
[31m- them were the faces of kiddies unborn when he was winning his first[m
[31m- laurels in the squared ring. He leaped lightly to the raised platform and[m
[31m- ducked through the ropes to his corner, where he sat down on a folding[m
[31m- stool. Jack Ball, the referee, came over and shook his hand. Ball was a[m
[31m- broken-down pugilist who for over ten years had not entered the ring as a[m
[31m- principal. King was glad that he had him for referee. They were both old[m
[31m- uns. If he should rough it with Sandel a bit beyond the rules, he knew[m
[31m- Ball could be depended upon to pass it by.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Aspiring young heavyweights, one after another, were climbing into the[m
[31m- ring and being presented to the audience by the referee. Also, he issued[m
[31m- their challenges for them.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Young Pronto,” Bill announced, “from North Sydney, challenges the winner[m
[31m- for fifty pounds side bet.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The audience applauded, and applauded again as Sandel himself sprang[m
[31m- through the ropes and sat down in his corner. Tom King looked across the[m
[31m- ring at him curiously, for in a few minutes they would be locked together[m
[31m- in merciless combat, each trying with all the force of him to knock the[m
[31m- other into unconsciousness. But little could he see, for Sandel, like[m
[31m- himself, had trousers and sweater on over his ring costume. His face was[m
[31m- strongly handsome, crowned with a curly mop of yellow hair, while his[m
[31m- thick, muscular neck hinted at bodily magnificence.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Young Pronto went to one corner and then the other, shaking hands with the[m
[31m- principals and dropping down out of the ring. The challenges went on. Ever[m
[31m- Youth climbed through the ropes⁠—Youth unknown, but insatiable⁠—crying[m
[31m- out to mankind that with strength and skill it would match issues with the[m
[31m- winner. A few years before, in his own heyday of invincibleness, Tom King[m
[31m- would have been amused and bored by these preliminaries. But now he sat[m
[31m- fascinated, unable to shake the vision of Youth from his eyes. Always were[m
[31m- these youngsters rising up in the boxing game, springing through the ropes[m
[31m- and shouting their defiance; and always were the old uns going down before[m
[31m- them. They climbed to success over the bodies of the old uns. And ever[m
[31m- they came, more and more youngsters⁠—Youth unquenchable and[m
[31m- irresistible⁠—and ever they put the old uns away, themselves becoming[m
[31m- old uns and travelling the same downward path, while behind them, ever[m
[31m- pressing on them, was Youth eternal⁠—the new babies, grown lusty and[m
[31m- dragging their elders down, with behind them more babies to the end of[m
[31m- time⁠—Youth that must have its will and that will never die.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- King glanced over to the press box and nodded to Morgan, of the Sportsman,[m
[31m- and Corbett, of the Referee. Then he held out his hands, while Sid[m
[31m- Sullivan and Charley Bates, his seconds, slipped on his gloves and laced[m
[31m- them tight, closely watched by one of Sandel’s seconds, who first examined[m
[31m- critically the tapes on King’s knuckles. A second of his own was in[m
[31m- Sandel’s corner, performing a like office. Sandel’s trousers were pulled[m
[31m- off, and, as he stood up, his sweater was skinned off over his head. And[m
[31m- Tom King, looking, saw Youth incarnate, deep-chested, heavy-thewed, with[m
[31m- muscles that slipped and slid like live things under the white satin skin.[m
[31m- The whole body was a-crawl with life, and Tom King knew that it was a life[m
[31m- that had never oozed its freshness out through the aching pores during the[m
[31m- long fights wherein Youth paid its toll and departed not quite so young as[m
[31m- when it entered.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The two men advanced to meet each other, and, as the gong sounded and the[m
[31m- seconds clattered out of the ring with the folding stools, they shook[m
[31m- hands and instantly took their fighting attitudes. And instantly, like a[m
[31m- mechanism of steel and springs balanced on a hair trigger, Sandel was in[m
[31m- and out and in again, landing a left to the eyes, a right to the ribs,[m
[31m- ducking a counter, dancing lightly away and dancing menacingly back again.[m
[31m- He was swift and clever. It was a dazzling exhibition. The house yelled[m
[31m- its approbation. But King was not dazzled. He had fought too many fights[m
[31m- and too many youngsters. He knew the blows for what they were⁠—too[m
[31m- quick and too deft to be dangerous. Evidently Sandel was going to rush[m
[31m- things from the start. It was to be expected. It was the way of Youth,[m
[31m- expending its splendour and excellence in wild insurgence and furious[m
[31m- onslaught, overwhelming opposition with its own unlimited glory of[m
[31m- strength and desire.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sandel was in and out, here, there, and everywhere, light-footed and[m
[31m- eager-hearted, a living wonder of white flesh and stinging muscle that[m
[31m- wove itself into a dazzling fabric of attack, slipping and leaping like a[m
[31m- flying shuttle from action to action through a thousand actions, all of[m
[31m- them centred upon the destruction of Tom King, who stood between him and[m
[31m- fortune. And Tom King patiently endured. He knew his business, and he knew[m
[31m- Youth now that Youth was no longer his. There was nothing to do till the[m
[31m- other lost some of his steam, was his thought, and he grinned to himself[m
[31m- as he deliberately ducked so as to receive a heavy blow on the top of his[m
[31m- head. It was a wicked thing to do, yet eminently fair according to the[m
[31m- rules of the boxing game. A man was supposed to take care of his own[m
[31m- knuckles, and, if he insisted on hitting an opponent on the top of the[m
[31m- head, he did so at his own peril. King could have ducked lower and let the[m
[31m- blow whiz harmlessly past, but he remembered his own early fights and how[m
[31m- he smashed his first knuckle on the head of the Welsh Terror. He was but[m
[31m- playing the game. That duck had accounted for one of Sandel’s knuckles.[m
[31m- Not that Sandel would mind it now. He would go on, superbly regardless,[m
[31m- hitting as hard as ever throughout the fight. But later on, when the long[m
[31m- ring battles had begun to tell, he would regret that knuckle and look back[m
[31m- and remember how he smashed it on Tom King’s head.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The first round was all Sandel’s, and he had the house yelling with the[m
[31m- rapidity of his whirlwind rushes. He overwhelmed King with avalanches of[m
[31m- punches, and King did nothing. He never struck once, contenting himself[m
[31m- with covering up, blocking and ducking and clinching to avoid punishment.[m
[31m- He occasionally feinted, shook his head when the weight of a punch landed,[m
[31m- and moved stolidly about, never leaping or springing or wasting an ounce[m
[31m- of strength. Sandel must foam the froth of Youth away before discreet Age[m
[31m- could dare to retaliate. All King’s movements were slow and methodical,[m
[31m- and his heavy-lidded, slow-moving eyes gave him the appearance of being[m
[31m- half asleep or dazed. Yet they were eyes that saw everything, that had[m
[31m- been trained to see everything through all his twenty years and odd in the[m
[31m- ring. They were eyes that did not blink or waver before an impending blow,[m
[31m- but that coolly saw and measured distance.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Seated in his corner for the minute’s rest at the end of the round, he lay[m
[31m- back with outstretched legs, his arms resting on the right angle of the[m
[31m- ropes, his chest and abdomen heaving frankly and deeply as he gulped down[m
[31m- the air driven by the towels of his seconds. He listened with closed eyes[m
[31m- to the voices of the house, “Why don’t yeh fight, Tom?” many were crying.[m
[31m- “Yeh ain’t afraid of ’im, are yeh?”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Muscle-bound,” he heard a man on a front seat comment. “He can’t move[m
[31m- quicker. Two to one on Sandel, in quids.”[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The gong struck and the two men advanced from their corners. Sandel came[m
[31m- forward fully three-quarters of the distance, eager to begin again; but[m
[31m- King was content to advance the shorter distance. It was in line with his[m
[31m- policy of economy. He had not been well trained, and he had not had enough[m
[31m- to eat, and every step counted. Besides, he had already walked two miles[m
[31m- to the ringside. It was a repetition of the first round, with Sandel[m
[31m- attacking like a whirlwind and with the audience indignantly demanding why[m
[31m- King did not fight. Beyond feinting and several slowly delivered and[m
[31m- ineffectual blows he did nothing save block and stall and clinch. Sandel[m
[31m- wanted to make the pace fast, while King, out of his wisdom, refused to[m
[31m- accommodate him. He grinned with a certain wistful pathos in his[m
[31m- ring-battered countenance, and went on cherishing his strength with the[m
[31m- jealousy of which only Age is capable. Sandel was Youth, and he threw his[m
[31m- strength away with the munificent abandon of Youth. To King belonged the[m
[31m- ring generalship, the wisdom bred of long, aching fights. He watched with[m
[31m- cool eyes and head, moving slowly and waiting for Sandel’s froth to foam[m
[31m- away. To the majority of the onlookers it seemed as though King was[m
[31m- hopelessly outclassed, and they voiced their opinion in offers of three to[m
[31m- one on Sandel. But there were wise ones, a few, who knew King of old time,[m
[31m- and who covered what they considered easy money.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The third round began as usual, one-sided, with Sandel doing all the[m
[31m- leading, and delivering all the punishment. A half-minute had passed when[m
[31m- Sandel, over-confident, left an opening. King’s eyes and right arm flashed[m
[31m- in the same instant. It was his first real blow⁠—a hook, with the[m
[31m- twisted arch of the arm to make it rigid, and with all the weight of the[m
[31m- half-pivoted body behind it. It was like a sleepy-seeming lion suddenly[m
[31m- thrusting out a lightning paw. Sandel, caught on the side of the jaw, was[m
[31m- felled like a bullock. The audience gasped and murmured awe-stricken[m
[31m- applause. The man was not muscle-bound, after all, and he could drive a[m
[31m- blow like a trip-hammer.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sandel was shaken. He rolled over and attempted to rise, but the sharp[m
[31m- yells from his seconds to take the count restrained him. He knelt on one[m
[31m- knee, ready to rise, and waited, while the referee stood over him,[m
[31m- counting the seconds loudly in his ear. At the ninth he rose in fighting[m
[31m- attitude, and Tom King, facing him, knew regret that the blow had not been[m
[31m- an inch nearer the point of the jaw. That would have been a knock-out, and[m
[31m- he could have carried the thirty quid home to the missus and the kiddies.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The round continued to the end of its three minutes, Sandel for the first[m
[31m- time respectful of his opponent and King slow of movement and sleepy-eyed[m
[31m- as ever. As the round neared its close, King, warned of the fact by sight[m
[31m- of the seconds crouching outside ready for the spring in through the[m
[31m- ropes, worked the fight around to his own corner. And when the gong[m
[31m- struck, he sat down immediately on the waiting stool, while Sandel had to[m
[31m- walk all the way across the diagonal of the square to his own corner. It[m
[31m- was a little thing, but it was the sum of little things that counted.[m
[31m- Sandel was compelled to walk that many more steps, to give up that much[m
[31m- energy, and to lose a part of the precious minute of rest. At the[m
[31m- beginning of every round King loafed slowly out from his corner, forcing[m
[31m- his opponent to advance the greater distance. The end of every round found[m
[31m- the fight manoeuvred by King into his own corner so that he could[m
[31m- immediately sit down.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Two more rounds went by, in which King was parsimonious of effort and[m
[31m- Sandel prodigal. The latter’s attempt to force a fast pace made King[m
[31m- uncomfortable, for a fair percentage of the multitudinous blows showered[m
[31m- upon him went home. Yet King persisted in his dogged slowness, despite the[m
[31m- crying of the young hot-heads for him to go in and fight. Again, in the[m
[31m- sixth round, Sandel was careless, again Tom King’s fearful right flashed[m
[31m- out to the jaw, and again Sandel took the nine seconds count.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- By the seventh round Sandel’s pink of condition was gone, and he settled[m
[31m- down to what he knew was to be the hardest fight in his experience. Tom[m
[31m- King was an old un, but a better old un than he had ever encountered⁠—an[m
[31m- old un who never lost his head, who was remarkably able at defence, whose[m
[31m- blows had the impact of a knotted club, and who had a knockout in either[m
[31m- hand. Nevertheless, Tom King dared not hit often. He never forgot his[m
[31m- battered knuckles, and knew that every hit must count if the knuckles were[m
[31m- to last out the fight. As he sat in his corner, glancing across at his[m
[31m- opponent, the thought came to him that the sum of his wisdom and Sandel’s[m
[31m- youth would constitute a world’s champion heavyweight. But that was the[m
[31m- trouble. Sandel would never become a world champion. He lacked the wisdom,[m
[31m- and the only way for him to get it was to buy it with Youth; and when[m
[31m- wisdom was his, Youth would have been spent in buying it.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- King took every advantage he knew. He never missed an opportunity to[m
[31m- clinch, and in effecting most of the clinches his shoulder drove stiffly[m
[31m- into the other’s ribs. In the philosophy of the ring a shoulder was as[m
[31m- good as a punch so far as damage was concerned, and a great deal better so[m
[31m- far as concerned expenditure of effort. Also, in the clinches King rested[m
[31m- his weight on his opponent, and was loath to let go. This compelled the[m
[31m- interference of the referee, who tore them apart, always assisted by[m
[31m- Sandel, who had not yet learned to rest. He could not refrain from using[m
[31m- those glorious flying arms and writhing muscles of his, and when the other[m
[31m- rushed into a clinch, striking shoulder against ribs, and with head[m
[31m- resting under Sandel’s left arm, Sandel almost invariably swung his right[m
[31m- behind his own back and into the projecting face. It was a clever stroke,[m
[31m- much admired by the audience, but it was not dangerous, and was,[m
[31m- therefore, just that much wasted strength. But Sandel was tireless and[m
[31m- unaware of limitations, and King grinned and doggedly endured.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sandel developed a fierce right to the body, which made it appear that[m
[31m- King was taking an enormous amount of punishment, and it was only the old[m
[31m- ringsters who appreciated the deft touch of King’s left glove to the[m
[31m- other’s biceps just before the impact of the blow. It was true, the blow[m
[31m- landed each time; but each time it was robbed of its power by that touch[m
[31m- on the biceps. In the ninth round, three times inside a minute, King’s[m
[31m- right hooked its twisted arch to the jaw; and three times Sandel’s body,[m
[31m- heavy as it was, was levelled to the mat. Each time he took the nine[m
[31m- seconds allowed him and rose to his feet, shaken and jarred, but still[m
[31m- strong. He had lost much of his speed, and he wasted less effort. He was[m
[31m- fighting grimly; but he continued to draw upon his chief asset, which was[m
[31m- Youth. King’s chief asset was experience. As his vitality had dimmed and[m
[31m- his vigour abated, he had replaced them with cunning, with wisdom born of[m
[31m- the long fights and with a careful shepherding of strength. Not alone had[m
[31m- he learned never to make a superfluous movement, but he had learned how to[m
[31m- seduce an opponent into throwing his strength away. Again and again, by[m
[31m- feint of foot and hand and body he continued to inveigle Sandel into[m
[31m- leaping back, ducking, or countering. King rested, but he never permitted[m
[31m- Sandel to rest. It was the strategy of Age.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Early in the tenth round King began stopping the other’s rushes with[m
[31m- straight lefts to the face, and Sandel, grown wary, responded by drawing[m
[31m- the left, then by ducking it and delivering his right in a swinging hook[m
[31m- to the side of the head. It was too high up to be vitally effective; but[m
[31m- when first it landed, King knew the old, familiar descent of the black[m
[31m- veil of unconsciousness across his mind. For the instant, or for the[m
[31m- slighest fraction of an instant, rather, he ceased. In the one moment he[m
[31m- saw his opponent ducking out of his field of vision and the background of[m
[31m- white, watching faces; in the next moment he again saw his opponent and[m
[31m- the background of faces. It was as if he had slept for a time and just[m
[31m- opened his eyes again, and yet the interval of unconsciousness was so[m
[31m- microscopically short that there had been no time for him to fall. The[m
[31m- audience saw him totter and his knees give, and then saw him recover and[m
[31m- tuck his chin deeper into the shelter of his left shoulder.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Several times Sandel repeated the blow, keeping King partially dazed, and[m
[31m- then the latter worked out his defence, which was also a counter. Feinting[m
[31m- with his left he took a half-step backward, at the same time upper cutting[m
[31m- with the whole strength of his right. So accurately was it timed that it[m
[31m- landed squarely on Sandel’s face in the full, downward sweep of the duck,[m
[31m- and Sandel lifted in the air and curled backward, striking the mat on his[m
[31m- head and shoulders. Twice King achieved this, then turned loose and[m
[31m- hammered his opponent to the ropes. He gave Sandel no chance to rest or to[m
[31m- set himself, but smashed blow in upon blow till the house rose to its feet[m
[31m- and the air was filled with an unbroken roar of applause. But Sandel’s[m
[31m- strength and endurance were superb, and he continued to stay on his feet.[m
[31m- A knock-out seemed certain, and a captain of police, appalled at the[m
[31m- dreadful punishment, arose by the ringside to stop the fight. The gong[m
[31m- struck for the end of the round and Sandel staggered to his corner,[m
[31m- protesting to the captain that he was sound and strong. To prove it, he[m
[31m- threw two back-air-springs, and the police captain gave in.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Tom King, leaning back in his corner and breathing hard, was disappointed.[m
[31m- If the fight had been stopped, the referee, perforce, would have rendered[m
[31m- him the decision and the purse would have been his. Unlike Sandel, he was[m
[31m- not fighting for glory or career, but for thirty quid. And now Sandel[m
[31m- would recuperate in the minute of rest.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Youth will be served⁠—this saying flashed into King’s mind, and he[m
[31m- remembered the first time he had heard it, the night when he had put away[m
[31m- Stowsher Bill. The toff who had bought him a drink after the fight and[m
[31m- patted him on the shoulder had used those words. Youth will be served! The[m
[31m- toff was right. And on that night in the long ago he had been Youth.[m
[31m- To-night Youth sat in the opposite corner. As for himself, he had been[m
[31m- fighting for half an hour now, and he was an old man. Had he fought like[m
[31m- Sandel, he would not have lasted fifteen minutes. But the point was that[m
[31m- he did not recuperate. Those upstanding arteries and that sorely tried[m
[31m- heart would not enable him to gather strength in the intervals between the[m
[31m- rounds. And he had not had sufficient strength in him to begin with. His[m
[31m- legs were heavy under him and beginning to cramp. He should not have[m
[31m- walked those two miles to the fight. And there was the steak which he had[m
[31m- got up longing for that morning. A great and terrible hatred rose up in[m
[31m- him for the butchers who had refused him credit. It was hard for an old[m
[31m- man to go into a fight without enough to eat. And a piece of steak was[m
[31m- such a little thing, a few pennies at best; yet it meant thirty quid to[m
[31m- him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- With the gong that opened the eleventh round, Sandel rushed, making a show[m
[31m- of freshness which he did not really possess. King knew it for what it was⁠—a[m
[31m- bluff as old as the game itself. He clinched to save himself, then, going[m
[31m- free, allowed Sandel to get set. This was what King desired. He feinted[m
[31m- with his left, drew the answering duck and swinging upward hook, then made[m
[31m- the half-step backward, delivered the upper cut full to the face and[m
[31m- crumpled Sandel over to the mat. After that he never let him rest,[m
[31m- receiving punishment himself, but inflicting far more, smashing Sandel to[m
[31m- the ropes, hooking and driving all manner of blows into him, tearing away[m
[31m- from his clinches or punching him out of attempted clinches, and ever when[m
[31m- Sandel would have fallen, catching him with one uplifting hand and with[m
[31m- the other immediately smashing him into the ropes where he could not fall.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The house by this time had gone mad, and it was his house, nearly every[m
[31m- voice yelling: “Go it, Tom!” “Get ’im! Get ’im!” “You’ve got ’im, Tom![m
[31m- You’ve got ’im!” It was to be a whirlwind finish, and that was what a[m
[31m- ringside audience paid to see.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- And Tom King, who for half an hour had conserved his strength, now[m
[31m- expended it prodigally in the one great effort he knew he had in him. It[m
[31m- was his one chance⁠—now or not at all. His strength was waning fast,[m
[31m- and his hope was that before the last of it ebbed out of him he would have[m
[31m- beaten his opponent down for the count. And as he continued to strike and[m
[31m- force, coolly estimating the weight of his blows and the quality of the[m
[31m- damage wrought, he realized how hard a man Sandel was to knock out.[m
[31m- Stamina and endurance were his to an extreme degree, and they were the[m
[31m- virgin stamina and endurance of Youth. Sandel was certainly a coming man.[m
[31m- He had it in him. Only out of such rugged fibre were successful fighters[m
[31m- fashioned.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Sandel was reeling and staggering, but Tom King’s legs were cramping and[m
[31m- his knuckles going back on him. Yet he steeled himself to strike the[m
[31m- fierce blows, every one of which brought anguish to his tortured hands.[m
[31m- Though now he was receiving practically no punishment, he was weakening as[m
[31m- rapidly as the other. His blows went home, but there was no longer the[m
[31m- weight behind them, and each blow was the result of a severe effort of[m
[31m- will. His legs were like lead, and they dragged visibly under him; while[m
[31m- Sandel’s backers, cheered by this symptom, began calling encouragement to[m
[31m- their man.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- King was spurred to a burst of effort. He delivered two blows in[m
[31m- succession⁠—a left, a trifle too high, to the solar plexus, and a[m
[31m- right cross to the jaw. They were not heavy blows, yet so weak and dazed[m
[31m- was Sandel that he went down and lay quivering. The referee stood over[m
[31m- him, shouting the count of the fatal seconds in his ear. If before the[m
[31m- tenth second was called, he did not rise, the fight was lost. The house[m
[31m- stood in hushed silence. King rested on trembling legs. A mortal dizziness[m
[31m- was upon him, and before his eyes the sea of faces sagged and swayed,[m
[31m- while to his ears, as from a remote distance, came the count of the[m
[31m- referee. Yet he looked upon the fight as his. It was impossible that a man[m
[31m- so punished could rise.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- Only Youth could rise, and Sandel rose. At the fourth second he rolled[m
[31m- over on his face and groped blindly for the ropes. By the seventh second[m
[31m- he had dragged himself to his knee, where he rested, his head rolling[m
[31m- groggily on his shoulders. As the referee cried “Nine!” Sandel stood[m
[31m- upright, in proper stalling position, his left arm wrapped about his face,[m
[31m- his right wrapped about his stomach. Thus were his vital points guarded,[m
[31m- while he lurched forward toward King in the hope of effecting a clinch and[m
[31m- gaining more time.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- At the instant Sandel arose, King was at him, but the two blows he[m
[31m- delivered were muffled on the stalled arms. The next moment Sandel was in[m
[31m- the clinch and holding on desperately while the referee strove to drag the[m
[31m- two men apart. King helped to force himself free. He knew the rapidity[m
[31m- with which Youth recovered, and he knew that Sandel was his if he could[m
[31m- prevent that recovery. One stiff punch would do it. Sandel was his,[m
[31m- indubitably his. He had out-generalled him, out-fought him, out-pointed[m
[31m- him. Sandel reeled out of the clinch, balanced on the hair line between[m
[31m- defeat or survival. One good blow would topple him over and down and out.[m
[31m- And Tom King, in a flash of bitterness, remembered the piece of steak and[m
[31m- wished that he had it then behind that necessary punch he must deliver. He[m
[31m- nerved himself for the blow, but it was not heavy enough nor swift enough.[m
[31m- Sandel swayed, but did not fall, staggering back to the ropes and holding[m
[31m- on. King staggered after him, and, with a pang like that of dissolution,[m
[31m- delivered another blow. But his body had deserted him. All that was left[m
[31m- of him was a fighting intelligence that was dimmed and clouded from[m
[31m- exhaustion. The blow that was aimed for the jaw struck no higher than the[m
[31m- shoulder. He had willed the blow higher, but the tired muscles had not[m
[31m- been able to obey. And, from the impact of the blow, Tom King himself[m
[31m- reeled back and nearly fell. Once again he strove. This time his punch[m
[31m- missed altogether, and, from absolute weakness, he fell against Sandel and[m
[31m- clinched, holding on to him to save himself from sinking to the floor.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- King did not attempt to free himself. He had shot his bolt. He was gone.[m
[31m- And Youth had been served. Even in the clinch he could feel Sandel growing[m
[31m- stronger against him. When the referee thrust them apart, there, before[m
[31m- his eyes, he saw Youth recuperate. From instant to instant Sandel grew[m
[31m- stronger. His punches, weak and futile at first, became stiff and[m
[31m- accurate. Tom King’s bleared eyes saw the gloved fist driving at his jaw,[m
[31m- and he willed to guard it by interposing his arm. He saw the danger,[m
[31m- willed the act; but the arm was too heavy. It seemed burdened with a[m
[31m- hundredweight of lead. It would not lift itself, and he strove to lift it[m
[31m- with his soul. Then the gloved fist landed home. He experienced a sharp[m
[31m- snap that was like an electric spark, and, simultaneously, the veil of[m
[31m- blackness enveloped him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- When he opened his eyes again he was in his corner, and he heard the[m
[31m- yelling of the audience like the roar of the surf at Bondi Beach. A wet[m
[31m- sponge was being pressed against the base of his brain, and Sid Sullivan[m
[31m- was blowing cold water in a refreshing spray over his face and chest. His[m
[31m- gloves had already been removed, and Sandel, bending over him, was shaking[m
[31m- his hand. He bore no ill-will toward the man who had put him out and he[m
[31m- returned the grip with a heartiness that made his battered knuckles[m
[31m- protest. Then Sandel stepped to the centre of the ring and the audience[m
[31m- hushed its pandemonium to hear him accept young Pronto’s challenge and[m
[31m- offer to increase the side bet to one hundred pounds. King looked on[m
[31m- apathetically while his seconds mopped the streaming water from him, dried[m
[31m- his face, and prepared him to leave the ring. He felt hungry. It was not[m
[31m- the ordinary, gnawing kind, but a great faintness, a palpitation at the[m
[31m- pit of the stomach that communicated itself to all his body. He remembered[m
[31m- back into the fight to the moment when he had Sandel swaying and tottering[m
[31m- on the hair-line balance of defeat. Ah, that piece of steak would have[m
[31m- done it! He had lacked just that for the decisive blow, and he had lost.[m
[31m- It was all because of the piece of steak.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- His seconds were half-supporting him as they helped him through the ropes.[m
[31m- He tore free from them, ducked through the ropes unaided, and leaped[m
[31m- heavily to the floor, following on their heels as they forced a passage[m
[31m- for him down the crowded centre aisle. Leaving the dressing-room for the[m
[31m- street, in the entrance to the hall, some young fellow spoke to him.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “W’y didn’t yuh go in an’ get ’im when yuh ‘ad ’im?” the young fellow[m
[31m- asked.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- “Aw, go to hell!” said Tom King, and passed down the steps to the[m
[31m- sidewalk.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- The doors of the public-house at the corner were swinging wide, and he saw[m
[31m- the lights and the smiling barmaids, heard the many voices discussing the[m
[31m- fight and the prosperous chink of money on the bar. Somebody called to him[m
[31m- to have a drink. He hesitated perceptibly, then refused and went on his[m
[31m- way.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He had not a copper in his pocket, and the two-mile walk home seemed very[m
[31m- long. He was certainly getting old. Crossing the Domain, he sat down[m
[31m- suddenly on a bench, unnerved by the thought of the missus sitting up for[m
[31m- him, waiting to learn the outcome of the fight. That was harder than any[m
[31m- knockout, and it seemed almost impossible to face.[m
[31m- </p>[m
[31m-<p>[m
[31m- He felt weak and sore, and the pain of his smashed knuckles warned him[m
[31m- that, even if he could find a job at navvy work, it would be a week before[m
[31m- he could grip a pick handle or a shovel. The hunger palpitation at the pit[m
[31m- of the stomach was sickening. His wretchedness overwhelmed him, and into[m
[31m- his eyes came an unwonted moisture. He covered his face with his hands,[m
[31m- and, as he cried, he remembered Stowsher Bill and how he had served him[m
[31m- that night in the long ago. Poor old Stowsher Bill! He could understand[m
[31m- now why Bill had cried in the dressing-room.[m
[31m- </p>[m
